imaryHeader|team=Penn State Nittany Lions|Coach|Years|Seasons|Record|Pct.|Cnf. record|Pct.|Cnf. Titles|Bowls|Nat. Titles}}\n|- \n|''No coach''\n|1887\u20131891\n|5\n|12\u20138\u20131\n|{{winning percentage|12|8|1}}\n|4\u20131\u20130\n|{{winning percentage|4|1|0}}\n|1\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[George Hoskins (coach)|George Hoskins]]\n|1892\u20131895\n|4\n|17\u20134\u20134\n|{{winning percentage|17|4|4}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Samuel B. Newton|Samuel Newton]]\n|1896\u20131898\n|3\n|12\u201314\u20130\n|{{winning percentage|12|14|0}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Sam Boyle]]\n|1899\n|1\n|4\u20136\u20131\n|{{winning percentage|4|6|1}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Pop Golden]]\n|1900\u20131902\n|3\n|16\u201312\u20131\n|{{winning percentage|16|12|1}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Daniel A. Reed]]\n|1903\n|1\n|5\u20133\u20130\n|{{winning percentage|5|3|0}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Tom Fennell]]\n|1904\u20131908\n|5\n|33\u201317\u20131\n|{{winning percentage|33|17|1}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Bill Hollenback]]\n|1909, 1911\u20131914\n|5\n|28\u20139\u20134\n|{{winning percentage|28|9|4}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Jack Hollenback]]\n|1910\n|1\n|5\u20132\u20131\n|{{winning percentage|5|2|1}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Dick Harlow]]\n|1915\u20131917\n|3\n|20\u20138\u20130\n|{{winning percentage|20|8|0}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Hugo Bezdek]]\n|1918\u20131929\n|12\n|65\u201330\u201311\n|{{winning percentage|65|30|11}}\n|\n|\n|\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Bob Higgins (football player)|Bob Higgins]]\n|1930\u20131948\n|19\n|91\u201357\u201311\n|{{winning percentage|91|57|11}}\n|\n|\n|\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Joe Bedenk]]\n|1949\n|1\n|5\u20134\u20130\n|{{winning percentage|5|4|0}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Rip Engle]]\n|1950\u20131965\n|16\n|104\u201348\u20134\n|{{winning percentage|104|48|4}}\n|\n|\n|\n|4\n|\n|-\n|[[Joe Paterno]]\n|1966\u20132011\n|45\n|409\u2013136\u20133\n|{{winning percentage|409|136|3}}\n|95\u201354\u20130\n|{{winning percentage|95|54|0}}\n|3\n|37\n|2\n|-\n|[[Tom Bradley (American football)|Tom Bradley]]\n|2011\n|<1\n|1\u20133\n|{{winning percentage|1|3}}\n|1\u20132\n|{{winning percentage|1|2}}\n|\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Bill O'Brien (American football)|Bill O'Brien]]\n|2012\u20132013\n|2\n|15\u20139\n|{{winning percentage|15|9}}\n|10\u20136\n|{{winning percentage|10|6}}\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[James Franklin (American football coach)|James Franklin]]\n|2014\u2013 present\n| 6th season\n| 56\u201323\n|{{winning percentage|56|23}}\n| 34\u201318\n|{{winning percentage|34|18}}\n| 1\n| 6\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n==Rivalries==\n\n===Michigan State===\n{{main|Michigan State\u2013Penn State football rivalry}}\nSince 1993, Penn State has played [[Michigan State Spartans football|Michigan State]] for the [[Land Grant Trophy]]. Penn State currently holds possession of the trophy after winning the 2019 contest. Beginning with the league's expansion and new division format in 2011, the two teams were in different divisions and did not play annually, however this [[Michigan State\u2013Penn State football rivalry|series]] renewed in the 2014 season and continue yearly as they will both be in the Big Ten's Eastern Division. Penn State has a 15\u20139 record in these trophy games. Michigan State leads the series 17\u201316\u20131 through the 2019 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.winsipedia.com/penn-state/vs/michigan-state|title=Winsipedia - Penn State Nittany Lions vs. Michigan State Spartans football series history|website=Winsipedia}}</ref>\n\n===Minnesota===\n{{main|Minnesota\u2013Penn State football rivalry}}\n[[File:Taking the field.jpg|thumb|200px|right|The Nittany Lions taking the field against Minnesota in 2005.]]\nSince 1993, Penn State has played [[Minnesota Golden Gophers football|Minnesota]] for the Governor's Victory Bell sporadically in their Big Ten schedule. \n\nDue to the latest changes in the Big Ten's scheduling procedures, the [[Minnesota\u2013Penn State football rivalry|series]] will be held approximately two times every seven years starting in 2014; this will change to three times every seven years when the Big Ten adds another conference game effective 2016. Minnesota won the most recent meeting 31\u201326 on November 9, 2019 in Minnesota. The next game is scheduled for November 19, 2022 at Penn State. Penn State leads the all-time series 9\u20136 through the 2019 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.winsipedia.com/penn-state/vs/minnesota|title=Winsipedia - Penn State Nittany Lions vs. Minnesota Golden Gophers football series history|website=Winsipedia}}</ref>\n\n=== Pittsburgh ===\n{{main|Penn State\u2013Pittsburgh football rivalry}}\nThis is a long-standing series between in-state rivals Penn State and [[Pittsburgh Panthers football|Pittsburgh]]. The rivalry, once one of the fiercest and most important in college football north of the [[Mason\u2013Dixon line]], began on November 6, 1893 at the inaugural game of [[Beaver Field]] in State College, and Penn State won the contest 32\u20130.<ref>{{cite web |author=Geoff Rushton |url=https://news.psu.edu/story/157346/2011/06/13/beaver-stadium-home-penn-state-football |title=Beaver Stadium: The Home of Penn State Football |website=Penn State News |date=June 13, 2011 |accessdate=April 21, 2019 }}</ref> The first two decades of the series was dominated by Penn State taking 12 of 15 matchups between 1893\u20131912. From 1913\u20131949 Pitt would hold a 26\u20136\u20132 advantage, before [[Rip Engle]] took over as head coach for Penn State in 1950. With Joe Paterno as an assistant coach, Engle led Penn State to a 9\u20136\u20131 record against the Panthers from 1950\u20131965. When Paterno was named head coach in 1965, the next 31 games would swing heavily in the Nittany Lion's favor, holding a 23\u20137\u20131 advantage from 1966\u20132000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadspin.com/with-the-rivalry-reborn-pitt-and-penn-state-players-re-1786437658|title=With The Rivalry Reborn, Pitt And Penn State Players Remember The Game That Defined It|last=Cosentino|first=Dom|website=Deadspin|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-24}}</ref> \n\nThe Rivalry went on a 15-year hiatus prior to the scheduling of a 4-game series in 2011<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pennlive.com/patriotnewssports/2011/06/pitt_penn_state_announce_resum.html|title=Pitt, Penn State resume rivalry with 2016 football game|last=Vigna|first=Paul|date=2011-06-14|website=pennlive.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-24}}</ref> that would see Penn State travel to Pittsburgh in 2016 & 2018 with Pitt returning to Happy Valley in 2017 & 2019. The series was branded the Keystone Classic in 2016,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gopsusports.com/news/2016/8/26/Penn_State_Pitt_Series_Dubbed_Keystone_Classic_Presented_by_Peoples_Natural_Gas.aspx|title=Penn State-Pitt Series Dubbed Keystone Classic Presented by Peoples Natural Gas|website=Penn State University Athletics}}</ref> which saw Pitt hold on for a thrilling 42\u201339<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/game?gameId=400869436|title=Penn State vs. Pittsburgh - Game Summary - September 10, 2016 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-24}}</ref> victory fending off a fierce fourth quarter comeback that fell short on an interception late in the 4th quarter.<ref>The Nittany Lions would drop the first matchup in Pittsburgh, before winning the last three games of the series. The Pennsylvania rivals do not currently have any future games scheduled in the series.</ref> The Nittany Lions would take the final three games, winning 33\u201313 in 2017, 51\u20136 in 2018, and most recently 17\u201310<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/game?gameId=401112259|title=Pittsburgh vs. Penn State - Game Summary - September 14, 2019 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-24}}</ref> in Beaver Stadium in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://onwardstate.com/2019/09/14/penn-state-pitt-series-ends-in-fitting-fashion/|title=Penn State-Pitt Series Ends In Fitting Fashion|date=2019-09-14|website=Onward State|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-24}}</ref>  \n\nThere are no future games currently scheduled between the two schools, although there is talk of a potential neutral site matchup sometime in the future.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pennlive.com/pennstatefootball/2019/09/could-the-next-penn-state-pitt-matchup-be-at-a-neutral-site.html|title=Could the next Penn State-Pitt matchup be at a neutral site?|last=Pickel|first=Greg|date=2019-09-10|website=pennlive.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-24}}</ref>  The Nittany Lions and Panthers have met on the football field 100 times. Penn State holds a 10-win advantage in the series, 53\u201343\u20134, through the 2019 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.winsipedia.com/penn-state/vs/pittsburgh|title=Winsipedia - Penn State Nittany Lions vs. Pittsburgh Panthers football series history|website=Winsipedia}}</ref>\n\n===Ohio State===\n{{main|Ohio State\u2013Penn State football rivalry}}\nThe rivalry began before Penn State was a member of the Big Ten. Penn State won the first four meetings of the series, which were held between 1912 and 1964. Then Ohio State won in 1975 in a game held in Columbus, Ohio and again in 1976 during the first ever matchup between the two teams in State College, Pennsylvania. Penn State and Ohio State would meet again in 1980 in their first and only postseason bowl, the 1980 Fiesta Bowl, which Penn State won. After the Fiesta Bowl, the two teams would not meet again until Penn State joined the Big Ten in 1993. Since then, the Nittany Lions and Buckeyes have played each other annually.  Ohio State leads the series 19\u201314 through the 2019 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.winsipedia.com/penn-state/vs/ohio-state|title=Winsipedia - Penn State Nittany Lions vs. Ohio State Buckeyes football series history|website=Winsipedia}}</ref>\n\n=== Maryland ===\n{{main|Maryland\u2013Penn State football rivalry}}\nPenn State and Maryland met in briefly interrupted stretches between 1917 and 1993, with a near-consecutive run played all but three years (1976, 1981, and 1983) between 1960 and 1993. However, the one-sided record belies what was often a competitive matchup until its final years. While Maryland only compiled one win and one tie, numerous games were narrowly lost by missed [[Field goal (football)|field goals]] and [[Turnover (football)|turnovers]]. In 1975, a field goal attempt by kicker Mike Sochko hit the upright with under a minute left, and Maryland lost 15\u201313. Ten years later, the Terps missed three field goals to eventually lose 20\u201318. After the Nittany Lions' move to the Big Ten Conference in 1993, the series was cancelled. However, Maryland ended up joining the Big Ten as well, in 2014, reinstating the rivalry after more than 2 decades of being dormant. Maryland would win the first matchup by a point (20\u201319) after infamously declining to shake hands with Penn State captains at midfield during the coin toss at Beaver Stadium. \n\nThe second meeting as conference foes would be played in Baltimore at [[M&T Bank Stadium]] and would again be decided by a point, this time a Penn State win 31\u201330. The last four matchups (2016\u20132019), all victories for Penn State have seen the Nittany Lions outscore the Terrapins by a combined score of 201\u201320. (38\u201314, 66\u20133, 38\u20133, 59\u20130)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.winsipedia.com/games/penn-state/vs/maryland|title=Winsipedia - Penn State Nittany Lions vs. Maryland Terrapins football series history games list|website=Winsipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>  The next matchup will take place on November 21, 2020 at Beaver Stadium.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gopsusports.com/schedule.aspx?schedule=517|title=2020 Football Schedule|website=Penn State University Athletics|language=en|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>  Penn State leads the series 40\u20132\u20131 through the 2019 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.winsipedia.com/penn-state/vs/maryland|title=Winsipedia - Penn State Nittany Lions vs. Maryland Terrapins football series history|website=Winsipedia}}</ref>\n\n===West Virginia===\n{{main|Penn State\u2013West Virginia football rivalry}}\nPenn State and [[West Virginia Mountaineers football|West Virginia]] have played each other 59 times. The first game was in 1904 when Penn State won that game 34\u20130. The two teams announced on September 19, 2013 that a home and home series has been scheduled for 2023 and 2024. This series has been dominated by the Nittany Lions who lead the series 48\u20139\u20132.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.winsipedia.com/penn-state/vs/west-virginia|title=Winsipedia - Penn State Nittany Lions vs. West Virginia Mountaineers football series history|website=Winsipedia}}</ref>\n\n===Historic Rivalries===\n\n==== Syracuse ====\n{{main|Penn State\u2013Syracuse football rivalry}}\nThe rivalry started in 1922, when Syracuse fought Penn State to a scoreless tie. But it was during the 1950s and 1960s that the rivalry intensified, as it enjoyed a competitive and often controversial string of contests. Syracuse football was led by [[Ben Schwartzwalder]], and Penn State by [[Rip Engle]], then [[Joe Paterno]]. From [[1950 college football season|1950]] to [[1970 NCAA University Division football season|1970]], Syracuse won 11 games to Penn State's 10. \n\nAfter Schwartzwalder retired in [[1973 NCAA Division I football season|1973]], Syracuse floundered. Penn State won 16 straight from [[1971 NCAA University Division football season|1971]] to [[1986 NCAA Division I-A football season|1986]]. Conference realignment and scheduling disagreements also dampened the intensity of the rivalry. Penn State fans and players increasingly turned their attention to the [[Penn State\u2013Pittsburgh football rivalry|rivalry]] with [[Pittsburgh Panthers football|Pittsburgh]].\n\nIn [[1987 NCAA Division I-A football season|1987]], Coach [[Dick MacPherson]] finally led Syracuse to a resounding 48\u201321 victory over the Nittany Lions in the [[Carrier Dome]]. Syracuse won again the following year in [[Beaver Stadium|Happy Valley]] but lost the last two games before the series was suspended in [[1991 NCAA Division I-A football season|1991]]. The rivalry has since been renewed three times since the series suspension \u2014 in 2008, 2009, and 2013. The Nittany Lions won all three of these contests. Penn State leads the series 43\u201323\u20135 with the most recent game played in 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.winsipedia.com/penn-state/vs/syracuse|title=Winsipedia - Penn State Nittany Lions vs. Syracuse Orange football series history|website=Winsipedia}}</ref>\n\n==== Alabama ====\n{{main|Alabama\u2013Penn State football rivalry}}\nThough the Crimson Tide are not as much of a traditional opponent for the Nittany Lions, the two teams are still often considered among the best in the country, claim a combined 18 national titles, and have met in a bowl game three times. The series began on December 19, 1959 in that year's edition of the [[1959 Liberty Bowl|Liberty Bowl]], a 7\u20130 win for #12 Penn State. Sixteen years later, the Nittany Lions and Crimson Tide met in the 1975 Sugar Bowl, resulting in a 13\u20136 Tide victory in New Orleans. Perhaps the most notable game between these two teams came four years later, in a 1979 Sugar Bowl rematch, resulting in another Alabama victory. The rivalry was intensified during the 1980s, when the Lions and Tide met in 10 consecutive seasons, all during regular season play. After this time, the rivalry went dormant for two decades before being renewed for a 2-game home-and-home series in 2010 and 2011. Alabama leads the series 10\u20135 with the last game played in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.winsipedia.com/penn-state/vs/alabama|title=Winsipedia - Penn State Nittany Lions vs. Alabama Crimson Tide football series history|website=Winsipedia}}</ref>\n\n==Traditions==\n\n=== The Whiteout ===\nThis Whiteout tradition dates back to a student section white out in 2004 and has become one of the most eagerly anticipated games during the football season. In recent years, Penn State students have donned white clothes, paint - anything white - to show their solidarity and support for the Nittany Lions. Forming a mass of bouncing and infectious enthusiasm, the students have \"Whited Out\" Beaver Stadium, the Bryce Jordan Center and other sports venues, making them some of the noisiest and most intimidating stadiums in America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/259947-a-brief-history-of-penn-state-whiteouts|title=A Brief History of the Penn State Whiteout|last=Ferguson|first=Alex|website=Bleacher Report|language=en|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref>\n\nBeano Cook of ESPN says, \"If you aren't impressed with the White Out, you're probably one of those people who think the moon landing was faked.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.psu.edu/story/184509/2008/08/16/nittany-lion-student-section-ranked-nations-best|title=Nittany Lion student section ranked nation's best {{!}} Penn State University|website=news.psu.edu|language=en|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref>\n\n===Nittanyville===\nOriginally named \"Paternoville,\" Nittanyville is a student camp out that occurs every week of a Penn State home football game. The students camp out to support the team and to acquire the best possible seats for the weekend's upcoming game, since seating is first-come, first serve for students. While the name \"Paternoville\" came about during Penn State's 2005 football season, students have long camped out for first row seats. Prior to 1993, the University distributed non-seat-specific tickets. Starting the same year Penn State football began competition in the Big Ten Conference, students were assigned seats on a first-come-first-serve basis, so that the first students to pass through \"Gate A\" at the south-east corner of the stadium would be assigned first row seats, and so on down the line.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.collegian.psu.edu/archives/article_75803a19-86de-5025-9e9d-2a1cb5da4a8b.html|title=Students adjust to assigned seating|last=Epstein|first=Brian|website=The Daily Collegian|language=en|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref> Since then, students have camped out in small to massive numbers in order to guarantee themselves a rail-side seat (though the students hardly ever sit) for the most amazing of sports spectacles; a Penn State home football game.\n\nMany generations of campers have come and gone, but it wasn't until the 2005 season that the students had a name for their tent-city. In anticipation of the 2005 clash between #16 Penn State and #6 Ohio State, students began camping six days in advance of the game outside the gate so that they would get a first row seat for, arguably, the biggest game of the 2005 season for Penn State. On Tuesday of the week preceding the game, \"Paternoville\" first appeared. Credited with the naming, freshman Dan Clark and the other students camping with him created a banner reading \"Paternoville.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/25/sports/ncaafootball/25psu.html|title=Penn State Tent City Now Has Rule Book|last=Viera|first=Mark|date=2008-09-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-09-26|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nThe name stuck. On Wednesday morning, October 5th, 2005, newspapers were already referring to the campsite as \"Paternoville.\" State-wide, regional, and even national media outlets began paying attention to the show in front of Gate A. Local businesses printed t-shirts up for the students, brought truckloads of food, and distributed various things like magazines and small footballs to keep the students occupied. Throughout the week, players, coaches, and many alumni and media personalities paid visits to Paternoville.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.collegian.psu.edu/archives/article_166c7e20-cb29-5ac9-afbe-1c195f0b3368.html|title=Paterno, Spanier visit stadium camp|last=Yassin|first=Sirage|website=The Daily Collegian|language=en|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref>\n\nOn Friday, ESPN's \"Cold Pizza\" morning show was broadcast from in front of the Bryce Jordan Center, across from the stadium, with some of the cast walking through Paternoville interviewing students and taping their activities, despite the constant drizzle. The next day, ESPN's College Gameday also was broadcast in front of the Bryce Jordan Center, hours before the showdown between the cross-border rivals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.collegian.psu.edu/archives/article_28dd1a20-a408-544b-a67d-2481bb18e06f.html|title=ESPN's Cold Pizza to film at PSU|website=The Daily Collegian|language=en|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref>\n\nBefore noon, the tents were packed away and hundreds of students began to line up for entry into the stadium. That night, in a historic match, the Nittany Lions upset the #6 ranked Buckeys 17-10 in front of a crowd of almost 110,000. The game being decided on a fumble by Ohio State quarterback and future Heisman Trophy winner Troy Smith, caused by Penn State defensive end Tamba Hali and recovered by defensive tackle Scott Paxson. After the final whistle, the jubilant students rushed the field.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/game?gameId=252810213|title=Ohio State vs. Penn State - Game Summary - October 8, 2005 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref>\n\nThe Paternoville name continued after the game. Since the original \"Paternoville,\" two other games have garnered comparable camp-outs. They were the 2005 contest against the University of Wisconsin Badgers (Senior Day for the 2005 season),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.psu.edu/story/207233/2005/11/08/football-2005-year-review|title=Football 2005 year in review {{!}} Penn State University|website=news.psu.edu|language=en|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref> and the 2006 contest against University of Michigan Wolverines. However, students camp out for every game, not just the \"big\" games. On average, about 10-15 tents appear for every game, while the number of tents for the 2005 Ohio State and Wisconsin games and the 2006 Michigan game exceeded 100.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lancasteronline.com/sports/psu-michigan-pick-your-subplot/article_e12f5c4b-3c6b-5d79-8b8e-28fc59f64466.html|title=PSU-Michigan: Pick your subplot|last=Freeman|first=Kevin|website=LancasterOnline|language=en|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the 2006 season, the University placed several markers around Beaver Stadium commemorating various traditions related to Penn State football. To the left of Gate A there is a marker for the Penn State \"student section\" and to the right of the gate there is a marker for \"Paternoville.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gopsusports.com/news/2006/9/29/First_Phase_of_Beaver_Stadium_Enhancements_Complete.aspx|title=First Phase of Beaver Stadium Enhancements Complete|website=Penn State University Athletics|language=en|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref>\n\nSince 2006, the practice of camping out has grown every year until 2009, when over 2,000 different students camped out for one or multiple games throughout the season. In 2011, the record was broken because of Penn State's high-powered home schedule, which included SEC powerhouse Alabama and new in-conference foe Nebraska, amongst other teams.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blackshoediaries.com/2012/7/16/3163713/paternoville-is-now-nittanyville|title=Paternoville Is Now Nittanyville|last=Vecellio|first=Dan|date=2012-07-16|website=Black Shoe Diaries|language=en|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2012, \"Paternoville\" officially became \"Nittanyville.\" As Coach Paterno was no longer the coach of Penn State's football team, the organization decided that since it was unlikely another coach would stay as long as Coach Paterno had, changing the name for each new coach would be impractical. However, aside from the name, nothing has changed and students will continue to support the team and camp out for the best seats long into the future.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.collegian.psu.edu/archives/article_df06bef8-ed7a-515a-a83c-fd921ee25270.html|title='Paternoville' changes name to 'Nittanyville'|last=Gilbert|first=Tim|website=The Daily Collegian|language=en|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref>\n\n===Success with Honor===\nJoe Paterno was widely known for his \"grand experiment\" in which he challenged his players to be successful both on the field and in the classroom.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.foxsports.com/college-football/story/paternos-grand-experiment-produced-perfection-38536635-012312|title=Paterno's Grand Experiment produced perfection|date=2012-01-23|work=FOX Sports|access-date=2018-06-13|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2011, the Nittany Lion football team posted an 87% graduation rate, tied with Stanford for No. 10 overall among the nation's 120 Football Bowl Subdivision (FBS) institutions, above the national average of 67%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gopsusports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/110211aaa.html |title=Penn State Football Tied For Best Graduation Success Rate Among BCS/AP Top 25 Teams|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=The Official Home of the Penn State Nittany Lions |date=November 2, 2011 |accessdate=August 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe June 2012 conviction of former assistant coach [[Jerry Sandusky]] on multiple counts of child sexual abuse marred the \"Success with Honor\" image.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2012/06/23/juror-sandusky-lacked-emotion-confirming-correct-verdict/#ixzz1zMjaPKhU |title=Juror: Sandusky lacked emotion, confirming correct verdict |publisher=Fox News |date= June 23, 2012|accessdate=August 10, 2012}}</ref> President Rodney Erickson, athletics director Dave Joyner, and head football coach Bill O'Brien, all of whom accepted their jobs in the wake of the scandal, have made statements in which they express commitment to maintaining integrity at the university and within the athletics programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackshoediaries.com/2012/7/23/3177470/erickson-joyner-obrien-release-statements |title=Erickson, Joyner, O'Brien Release Statements |publisher=Black Shoe Diaries |date=July 23, 2012|accessdate=August 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, a group of alumni and supporters established a non-profit organization [501(c)(3) and registered trademark] that will build upon the \"Success with Honor\" motto. Their mission is to promote and support charitable endeavors as well as to inspire others to \"Get in the Game.\" Success with Honor is a Social Network Community that has identified more than 60+ charities. Success with Honor helps individuals to identify and connect with causes they\u2019d like to volunteer their skills, time, and/or money to. Similarly, SWH assists charities in finding individuals to meet their current needs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.collegian.psu.edu/archive/2013/02/01/Success_with_honor_alumni_group.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-02-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130217094758/http://www.collegian.psu.edu/archive/2013/02/01/Success_with_honor_alumni_group.aspx |archivedate=2013-02-17 }}</ref>\n\n===Uniform===\n[[File:UVA v. Penn State, Sep. 8 2012.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The Nittany Lions playing against the [[Virginia Cavaliers football|Virginia Cavaliers]] in 2012 at [[Scott Stadium]]: note the simple uniforms of the Nittany Lions during their away games.]]\n\nThe team is widely noted for their simple game uniforms. They only wear white pants, and the jerseys are simple blue for home games, and white for away games.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fornelli|title=Penn State making uniform change|url=http://college-football.blogs.cbssports.com/mcc/blogs/entry/24156338/27656427|accessdate=May 7, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110228224731/http://college-football.blogs.cbssports.com/mcc/blogs/entry/24156338/27656427|archivedate=February 28, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The team is only allowed to wear simple black [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] shoes with white calf socks for game days, though blue tights are permitted underneath the white socks for cold weather games. The helmet is white with a blue stripe down the center, and a blue on white \"Penn State\" sticker covers up the forehead helmet logo. No team logos, conference logos, numbers, or other stickers are permitted on the helmet, though two Nike logos are on facemask visors that some players choose to wear. Penn State has started to wear bowl decals only starting with [[1997 Fiesta Bowl (January)|1997 Fiesta Bowl]]. Before that, Penn State always declined the decals so they can play out of their simple game uniforms. The blue and white uniforms replaced pink and black ones in 1890.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://studentblog.worldcampus.psu.edu/index.php/2009/10/bleed-pink-and-black/ |title=Bleed Pink and Black? &#124; Corner of College and Allen |publisher=Studentblog.worldcampus.psu.edu |date=October 16, 2009 |accessdate=August 10, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120116091510/http://studentblog.worldcampus.psu.edu/index.php/2009/10/bleed-pink-and-black/ |archivedate=January 16, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe uniforms became even simpler for the 2011 season, as the white cuffs and collars on the home jerseys and the corresponding blue cuffs and collars on the road jerseys were eliminated, leaving the jerseys solid blue and white, respectively.\n\nIn 2012 Penn State started wearing names on their uniforms for the first time as a way to note the players who stuck with the school through the scandal and a blue ribbon in support the victims of child abuse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/sports/colleges/Penn-State-to-add-names-to-back-of-football-jerseys.html |title=Penn State to add names to back of football jerseys |publisher=Philly.com |date=August 7, 2012 |accessdate=August 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the Nittany Lion logo was added to the base of the jersey collar along with the Big Ten logo on the right side of the jersey.\n\nStarting in 2015, the names that were added throughout the 2012\u201314 seasons to honor those who stayed with the program were removed and the team reverted to the traditional nameless jerseys while still retaining the Nittany Lion logo at the base of the jersey collar. The team also began sporting new Nike Elite 51 jerseys which feature a new design on the collars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gopsusports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/071615aaa.html|title=Penn State Football to Remove Names from Jerseys|publisher=}}</ref> In addition, the team added the words \"Nittany Lions\" onto the back of the football helmets.\n\nFor the 2017 homecoming game against the [[Indiana Hoosiers]], Penn State broke tradition by donning throwback jerseys in what was dubbed the \"Generations of Greatness\" game. These uniforms integrated elements from past uniforms, including: numbers on helmets' sides, block uniform numbers, white stripes on sleeves, blue stripes on pants, striped socks, gray facemasks, white cleats, and a few other subtle changes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gopsusports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/061517aag.html|title=FB Announces Generations of Greatness Game|access-date=2018-06-13|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Captains===\nCaptains are chosen by the team, with the head coach's approval.{{CN|date=February 2018}} Being named a captain is an honor almost always given to a senior, but there are some notable exceptions: Linebacker [[Sean Lee]] was named a captain in the beginning of Spring practice in 2008, the beginning of his 4th year with the team. However, he suffered a torn ACL during spring practice, redshirted in 2008, and returned as a captain again in 2009. The most recent example of a \"true\" junior being named was [[Paul Posluszny]], who was named a captain in both 2005 and 2006, his junior and senior years, respectively. The last time a junior was named captain before Posluszny was in 1968, when [[Steve Smear]] and [[Mike Reid (singer)|Mike Reid]] were named captains during their junior years.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hudson|first=Beth|title=PSU tri-captains bring a solid mix to the table|url=http://articles.mcall.com/2005-08-02/sports/3623814_1_posluszny-zemaitis-senior-quarterback-michael-robinson|accessdate=April 10, 2013|newspaper=[[The Morning Call]]|date=August 2, 2005|location=[[Allentown, Pennsylvania]]}}</ref> In 2014, [[Christian Hackenberg]] became the first true sophomore to be named team captain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.centredaily.com/2014/08/13/4303432/penn-state-football-nittany-lions.html?sp=/99/116/|title=Community \u2013 CentreDaily.com|work=centredaily.com}}</ref>\n\n===Linebacker U===\n\nPenn State is often referred to as Linebacker U for its reputation of producing outstanding linebackers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.collegian.psu.edu/football/article_f454f924-578c-11e5-a45c-53d3fa3a8f77.html|title=The origins of Penn State football's Linebacker U|last=Collegian|first=Anthony Picardi {{!}} The Daily|work=The Daily Collegian|access-date=2018-06-13|language=en}}</ref>\n\n* [[Dennis Onkotz]] was a two-time All American in 1968 and 1969 and played on two undefeated teams.<ref name=bsd>{{cite web|last=Hubbell|first=Mike|title=The Greatest Penn State Linebackers of All Time|url=http://www.blackshoediaries.com/2007/6/10/214341/999|work=Black Shoe Diaries \u2013 SB Nation|publisher=Vox Media|accessdate=April 10, 2013|date=January 10, 2007}}</ref>\n* [[Jack Ham]] finished his career with 251 tackles, blocked two punts and went on to play on two undefeated teams.  Ham later went on to the NFL, playing for the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]], and was inducted into the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"bsd\"/>\n* [[Charlie Zapiec]] a fourth round draft pick of the Dallas Cowboys, went on to star in the Canadian Football League as a linebacker with the Montreal Alouettes coached by future NFL Legend Marv Levy.  Zapiec switched from offensive guard in his senior year and also received All-American honors; in the two years he started as a guard and the one year as a linebacker, he accumulated 34 wins, including three major bowl victories, while suffering only one loss, the best record for a starter at Penn State.\n*[[Ed O'Neil|Edward William O'Neil]], an American football coach and former professional linebacker, played seven seasons in the National Football League (NFL). From 1970\u20131973, he played linebacker at Penn State. A three-year letterman, he was team captain of the Nittany Lions' undefeated 1973 team and was named an All-American that same season.\n* [[Greg Buttle]] was a linebacker during the 1973\u20131975 seasons, finishing with 305 tackles in his junior and senior year.  He was drafted by the [[New York Jets]] and is a part of the All Jet team.\n* [[Shane Conlan]] was a two-time All-American and defensive MVP of the 1987 National Championship Fiesta Bowl. He was drafted No. 1 by the Bills in 1987, named NFL Defensive Rookie of the Year and was named to three straight Pro Bowls (1988\u201390).<ref name=\"bsd\"/>\n* [[Lavar Arrington]] finished with 319 career tackles and 139 tackles for losses.  He was later drafted second overall by the [[Washington Redskins]].<ref name=\"bsd\"/>\n* [[Cameron Wake]]  (Known as Derek Wake when at Penn State) went on to capture MVP honors for the [[British Columbia Lions]] in the [[Canadian Football League]] before moving on to the [[Miami Dolphins]] and leading the [[National Football League]] in sacks during the 2010 season.<ref name=\"lee/wake\"/>\n* [[Tamba Hali]] was the 20th overall pick in the [[2006 NFL Draft]] and led the AFC in sacks during the 2010 NFL season, helping the Kansas City Chiefs reach the playoffs. He played defensive end during his college career.<ref name=\"lee/wake\"/>\n* [[Paul Posluszny]] played from 2003\u20132006.  Posluszny won the [[Dick Butkus Award]] in 2005 and the [[Chuck Bednarik Award]] in 2005 and 2006.  He finished with 372 tackles and was drafted by the [[Buffalo Bills]].<ref name=\"bsd\"/> Currently playing for the Jacksonville Jaguars.\n* [[Dan Connor (American football)|Dan Connor]] finished his career as the all-time leading tackler for Penn State with 419 and was drafted by the [[Carolina Panthers]].<ref name=\"bsd\"/>\n* [[Sean Lee]] graduated from Penn State in 2009 and is an inside linebacker for the [[Dallas Cowboys]].<ref name=\"lee/wake\">{{cite web|last=Archer|first=Todd|title=Sean Lee part of new/old Linebacker U|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/dallas/cowboys/post/_/id/4685717/sean-lee-part-of-newold-linebacker-u|work=Dallas Cowboys Blog |publisher=ESPN Dallas |accessdate=April 10, 2013|date=October 26, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[NaVorro Bowman]], drafted by the [[San Francisco 49ers]] in the third round of the 2010 draft, ranked seventh in the league in tackles in 2011<ref>{{cite web|author=Sat, Aug 188:00 PM ET |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/player/_/id/13262/navorro-bowman |title=NaVorro Bowman Stats, News, Videos, Highlights, Pictures, Bio \u2013 San Francisco 49ers |publisher=ESPN |date=May 28, 1988|accessdate=August 10, 2012}}</ref> and was named an AP first team All-Pro for his 2011 campaign. Bowman currently play for the Oakland Raiders.\n* [[Michael Mauti]] and [[Gerald Hodges]] were \"Co-Linebacker U\" in 2012, both achieved over 95 tackles and both were drafted by the Minnesota Vikings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/player/gamelog/_/id/377894/michael-mauti|title=Michael Mauti|publisher=ESPN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/player/gamelog/_/id/481918/gerald-hodges|title=Gerald Hodges|publisher=ESPN}}</ref> Both players now play for Mauti's hometown team New Orleans Saints.\n\n==2011 child sex abuse scandal==\n{{main article|Penn State child sex abuse scandal}}\n{{very long section|date=February 2018}}\n\nThe [[Penn State child sex abuse scandal]] centered on then retired [[Pennsylvania State University]] football assistant coach [[Jerry Sandusky]]'s [[sexual assault]] of two underage boys on or near university property.  After an extensive [[grand jury]] investigation, Sandusky was indicted on 52 counts of child molestation dating from 1994<ref name=1970s>{{cite news|url=http://www.pennlive.com/midstate/index.ssf/2011/11/exclusive_jerry_sandusky_inter.html |title=Exclusive: Jerry Sandusky interview prompts long-ago victims to contact lawyer |author=Sara Ganim |work=[[The Patriot-News]] |date=November 17, 2011 |accessdate=November 21, 2011}}</ref> The trial of Jerry Sandusky on 52 charges of sexual crimes against children started on June 11, 2012, at the [[Centre County Courthouse]] in [[Bellefonte, Pennsylvania]]<ref name=\"Trial\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/12/sports/ncaafootball/jerry-sandusky-child-sexual-abuse-trial-begins.html?pagewanted=all |title=Sandusky's Trial Begins With Graphic Testimony|work=The New York Times|date=June 11, 2012|author=Belson, Ken|accessdate=June 12, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"contract\">{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/jerry-sandusky-trial-hears-victim-testify-years-sex/story?id=16539947#.T9hI4NWlWTU|title=Jerry Sandusky Offered Victim 4 a Contract to Keep Seeing Him|publisher=ABC News|date=June 11, 2012|author1=Curry, Colleen|author2=Avila, Jim|accessdate=June 12, 2012}}</ref> and ended on the evening of June 22, 2012, when the jury found Sandusky guilty on 45 of the 48 counts against him.<ref name=\"apverdict\">{{cite news|last1=Scolforo|first1=Mark|last2=Armas|first2=Genaro|title=Ex-Penn St. assistant Sandusky convicted of abuse|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_PENN_STATE_ABUSE?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2012-06-22-22-18-58|accessdate=June 22, 2012|agency=Associated Press|date=June 22, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-guilty\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/22/sports/ncaafootball/jerry-sandusky-convicted-of-sexually-abusing-boys.html|title=Sandusky Convicted of Sexually Abusing Boys|last=Drape|first=Joe|date=June 22, 2012|work=The New York Times|accessdate=June 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSeveral high-level school officials were charged with [[perjury]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Two Top Officials Step Down Amid Penn State Scandal|url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2011/11/05/penn-state-ex-coach-others-charged-in-child-sex-case/|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=November 9, 2011|publisher=Fox News|date=November 7, 2011}}</ref> suspended, or dismissed for allegedly [[cover-up|covering up]] the incidents or failing to notify authorities. In the wake of the scandal, school president [[Graham Spanier]] was forced to resign, and head football coach [[Joe Paterno]] was fired without cause late in the season, while Sandusky maintained his innocence.<ref name=\"admission\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-15730317 |title=Jerry Sandusky regrets showers with boys at Penn State |date=November 14, 2011 |accessdate=November 14, 2011 |work=BBC News Online }}</ref>\n\nFormer [[FBI]] director [[Louis Freeh]], whose firm was hired by the Penn State Board of Trustees to conduct an independent investigation into the scandal, concluded, after, ostensibly, conducting over 400 interviews and reviewing over 3.5 million documents, that Paterno, Spanier, Curley and Schultz had \"repeatedly concealed critical facts relating to Sandusky's child abuse from the authorities, the Board of Trustees, Penn State community, and the public at large.\"<ref name=\"nyt-psu-child-abuse\">{{cite news|title=Penn State's Part|date=July 12, 2012|accessdate=July 13, 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/13/opinion/penn-states-part-in-the-sandusky-sexual-abuse-scandal.html}}</ref><ref name=\"usa-psu-child-abuse\">{{cite news|last1=Johnson |first1=Kevin |last2=Marklein |first2=Mary Beth |title=Freeh report blasts culture of Penn State |date=July 13, 2012 |newspaper=USA Today |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/nation/story/2012-07-12/louis-freeh-report-penn-state-jerry-sandusky/56181956/1 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/697dbG9uh?url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/nation/story/2012-07-12/louis-freeh-report-penn-state-jerry-sandusky/56181956/1 |archivedate=July 13, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"psu-child-abuse\">{{cite press release|title=Remarks of Louis Freeh in Conjunction with Announcement of Report Regarding the Pennsylvania State University |date=July 12, 2012 |publisher=Kekst and Company |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/99901024/Freeh-Report-Release |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/697bWvS4B?url=http://www.scribd.com/doc/99901024/Freeh-Report-Release |archivedate=July 13, 2012 |url-status=live |quote=Although concern to treat the child abuser humanely was expressly stated, no such sentiments were ever expressed by them for Sandusky's victims. }}</ref>  In an interview conducted by [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]'s [[60 Minutes Sports]], the former Chief Deputy Attorney General of Pennsylvania, Frank Fina, who investigated and prosecuted Jerry Sandusky, stated that he found no evidence that [[Joe Paterno]] participated in a cover-up.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.philly.com/2013-09-07/news/41836502_1_sandusky-prosecutor-jerry-sandusky-tim-curley|title=Sandusky prosecutor: Paterno not part of cover-up|work=Philly.com}}</ref>\n\nOn July 23, 2012, [[NCAA]] announced that it had fined the Penn State football program $60 million, levied a four-year ban from bowl games and vacated all of the program's 112 wins from 1998 to 2011. They were originally scheduled to lose 10 scholarships from the incoming classes in 2013, 2014, 2015 and 2016, which would have been a loss of 40 total scholarships. They were set to have a maximum of 75 players on scholarship in 2013, then be down to 65 total scholarships for 2014, 2015 and 2016, before increasing back up to 75 in 2017 and return to a full allotment of 85 scholarships for the 2018 season.<ref name=USATodayNCAA>{{cite news|title=NCAA hands out severe punishment for Penn State|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/college/football/bigten/story/2012-07-23/ncaa-penn-state-punishment-sanctions/56427630/1|last=Prisbell|first=Eric|work=USA Today|date=July 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn September 24, 2013, the NCAA announced they were restoring 25 of the 40 scholarships to Penn State \"[d]ue to Penn State University's continued progress toward ensuring athletics integrity\". After losing 10 scholarships from the 2013\u20132014 incoming class (bringing in 15 players instead of the normal 25) and only having 75 total players on scholarship, Penn State gained five scholarships back for 2014\u201315, bringing in 20 new players with 80 total players on scholarship. Full scholarships were regained for 2016\u201317, two years ahead of schedule. In total they lost only 15 scholarships, compared to the original penalty of 40 scholarships.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/executive-committee-gradually-restore-penn-state-scholarships|title=Executive Committee to gradually restore Penn State scholarships|last=aassimon|date=2013-09-24|work=NCAA.org - The Official Site of the NCAA|access-date=2018-06-13|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe decision to return the scholarships was the result of a unanimous decision of the executive committee of the NCAA following a recommendation from the former US Sen. George Mitchell. The NCAA had appointed Mitchell to monitor the progress of Penn State and adopting recommended reforms to enhance their \"security, ethics, governance and compliance structure\". The decision to accept the recommendation was based upon the belief that the restored scholarships would provide benefits to student-athletes.<ref name=CDTPennState>{{cite web|title=NCAA modifies sanctions against Penn State, restoring scholarships; may consider lifting bowl ban|url=http://www.centredaily.com/2013/09/24/3804708/breaking-penn-state-trustee-says.html|last=Dawson|first=Mike|publisher=Center Daily Times|date=September 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nSeveral lawsuits were filed against NCAA related to the levy of penalties. In September 2014 the NCAA, under the auspices of favorable reports from Mitchell, announced that Penn State would be eligible for the 2014 postseason and all scholarships restored in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/story/_/id/11489258/ncaa-drops-postseason-ban-penn-state-nittany-lions|title=NCAA drops postseason ban of Penn State Nittany Lions|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> The team's wins and records that had previously been vacated due to the scandal were restored, pending full approval, as part of a legal settlement in January 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://onwardstate.com/2015/01/16/paternos-wins-restored-and-consent-decree-replaced-in-corman-settlement/ |accessdate=November 1, 2015|date=January 16, 2015|first1=Zach |last1=Berger |publisher=Onward State |title=Corman Settlement: Paterno's Wins Restored and Consent Decree Replaced }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/story/_/id/12179571/joe-paterno-111-wins-were-vacated-restored|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=November 1, 2015|date=January 16, 2015|title=Joe Paterno is now winningest coach}}</ref>\n\n==Individual award winners==\n\n===Retired numbers===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Penn State Nittany Lions|No.|Player|Position|Career|Date of Retirement}}\n|-\n| '''22''' || [[John Cappelletti]] || [[Running back|RB]] || 1970\u201373 || September 7, 2013 <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gopsusports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/090713aac.html|title=Penn State to Retire Cappelletti's No. 22 Jersey|access-date=2018-06-13|language=en}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Players===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*'''[[Heisman Trophy]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Heisman Winners|url=http://www.heisman.com/index.php/heismanWinners#winners-year|work=Heisman Trophy|publisher=HeismanTrophy.com|accessdate=April 10, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/