il 10, 2013}}</ref>\n:[[LaVar Arrington]] \u2013 [[1999 NCAA Division I-A football season|1999]]\n:[[Paul Posluszny]] \u2013 [[2005 NCAA Division I-A football season|2005]], [[2006 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2006]]\n:[[Dan Connor (American football player)|Dan Connor]] \u2013 [[2007 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2007]]\n*'''[[William V. Campbell Trophy]]'''\n:[[John Urschel]] \u2013 [[2013 NCAA Division I-A football season|2013]]\n*'''[[Fred Biletnikoff Award]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Fred Biletnikoff Award Winners|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/awards/biletnikoff.html|work=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=USA Today Sports|accessdate=April 10, 2013}}</ref>\n:[[Bobby Engram]] \u2013 [[1994 NCAA Division I-A football season|1994]] (inaugural winner)\n*'''[[Dick Butkus Award]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Dick Butukus Award Winners|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/awards/butkus.html|work=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=USA Today Sports|accessdate=April 10, 2013}}</ref>\n:[[LaVar Arrington]] \u2013 [[1999 NCAA Division I-A football season|1999]]\n:[[Paul Posluszny]] \u2013 [[2005 NCAA Division I-A football season|2005]]\n{{col-2}}\n*'''[[Dave Rimington Trophy|Rimington Trophy]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Dave Rimington Trophy Winners|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/awards/rimington.html|work=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|accessdate=April 10, 2013}}</ref>\n:[[A.Q. Shipley]] \u2013 [[2008 NCAA Division I-A football season|2008]]\n*'''[[Lombardi Award]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Vince Lombardi Award Winners|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/awards/lombardi.html|work=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=USA Today Sports|accessdate=April 10, 2013}}</ref>\n:[[Bruce Clark (American football)|Bruce Clark]] \u2013 [[1978 NCAA Division I-A football season|1978]]\n:[[Carl Nassib]] \u2013 [[2015 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2015]]\n*'''[[Ted Hendricks Award]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Ted Hendricks Award Winners|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/awards/hendricks.html|work=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=USA Today Sports|accessdate=April 10, 2013}}</ref>\n:[[Carl Nassib]] \u2013 [[2015 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2015]]\n*'''[[Davey O'Brien Award]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Davey O'Brien Award Winners|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/awards/obrien.html|work=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=USA Today Sports|accessdate=April 10, 2013}}</ref>\n:[[Todd Blackledge]] \u2013 [[1982 NCAA Division I-A football season|1982]]\n:[[Kerry Collins]] \u2013 [[1994 NCAA Division I-A football season|1994]]\n*'''[[Outland Trophy]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=John Outland Trophy Winners|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/awards/outland.html|work=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=USA Today Sports|accessdate=April 10, 2013}}</ref>\n:[[Mike Reid (singer)|Mike Reid]] \u2013 [[1969 NCAA Division I-A football season|1969]]\n*'''[[Doak Walker Award]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Doak Walker Award Winners|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/awards/walker.html|work=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=USA Today Sports|accessdate=April 10, 2013}}</ref>\n:[[Larry Johnson (running back)|Larry Johnson]] \u2013 [[2002 NCAA Division I-A football season|2002]]\n*'''[[Chicago Tribune Silver Football]]'''<ref>{{cite news|title=Chicago Tribune's Silver Football history|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-11-30/sports/chi-silver-football-history_1_chicago-tribune-s-silver-football-heisman-trophy-chalmers-elliott|accessdate=April 10, 2013|newspaper=[[The Chicago Tribune]]|date=November 30, 2012}}</ref>\n:[[Kerry Collins]] \u2013 [[1994 NCAA Division I-A football season|1994]]\n:[[Michael Robinson (American football)|Michael Robinson]] \u2013 [[2005 NCAA Division I-A football season|2005]]\n:[[Daryll Clark]] \u2013 [[2009 NCAA Division I-A football season|2009]]\n:[[Saquon Barkley]] - [[2016 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2016]], [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2017]]\n*'''[[List of Senior CLASS Award football winners|Senior CLASS Award \u2013 Football]]'''\n:[[John Urschel]] \u2013 [[2013 NCAA Division I-A football season|2013]]\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Coaches===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*'''[[Amos Alonzo Stagg Award]]'''\n:[[Rip Engle]] \u2013 [[1969 NCAA Division I-A football season|1969]]\n:[[Joe Paterno]] \u2013 [[2002 NCAA Division I-A football season|2002]]\n*'''AT&T-ESPN Coach of the Year'''\n:[[Bill O'Brien (American football)|Bill O'Brien]] \u2013 [[2012 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2012]]\n*'''[[Big Ten Conference football individual awards#Dave McClain / Hayes\u2013Schembechler Coach of the Year|Big Ten Coach of the Year]]'''\n:[[Joe Paterno]] - [[1994 NCAA Division I FBS football season|1994]], [[2005 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2005]], [[2008 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2008]]\n:[[Bill O'Brien (American football)|Bill O'Brien]] \u2013 [[2012 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2012]]\n:[[James Franklin (American football coach)|James Franklin]] - [[2016 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2016]]\n*'''[[Bobby Dodd Coach of the Year Award]]'''\n:[[Joe Paterno]] \u2013 [[1981 NCAA Division I-A football season|1981]], [[2005 NCAA Division I-A football season|2005]]\n*'''[[Eddie Robinson Coach of the Year]]'''\n:[[Joe Paterno]] \u2013 [[1978 NCAA Division I-A football season|1978]], [[1982 NCAA Division I-A football season|1982]], [[1986 NCAA Division I-A football season|1986]]\n{{col-2}}\n*'''[[George Munger Award]]'''\n:[[Joe Paterno]] \u2013 [[1990 NCAA Division I-A football season|1990]], [[1994 NCAA Division I-A football season|1994]], [[2005 NCAA Division I-A football season|2005]]\n*'''[[Maxwell Football Club|Maxwell Coach of the Year]]'''\n:[[Bill O'Brien (American football)|Bill O'Brien]] \u2013 [[2012 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2012]]\n*'''[[Paul \"Bear\" Bryant Award]]'''\n:[[Joe Paterno]] \u2013 [[1986 NCAA Division I-A football season|1986]]\n:[[Bill O'Brien (American football)|Bill O'Brien]] \u2013 [[2012 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2012]]\n*'''[[The Home Depot Coach of the Year Award]]'''\n:[[Joe Paterno]] \u2013 [[2005 NCAA Division I-A football season|2005]]\n*'''[[Walter Camp Coach of the Year]]'''\n:[[Joe Paterno]] \u2013 [[1972 NCAA Division I-A football season|1972]], [[1994 NCAA Division I-A football season|1994]], [[2005 NCAA Division I-A football season|2005]]\n*'''[[Woody Hayes Trophy|Woody Hayes Coach of the Year]]'''\n:[[James Franklin (American football coach)|James Franklin]] - [[2016 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2016]]\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Other awards===\n*'''[[Lambert-Meadowlands Trophy|Lambert Trophy]]''' \u2013 1947, 1961, 1962, 1964, 1967, 1968, 1969, 1971, 1972, 1973, 1974, 1975, 1977, 1978, 1981, [[1982 NCAA Division I-A football season|1982]], [[1985 NCAA Division I-A football season|1985]], [[1986 NCAA Division I-A football season|1986]], [[1989 NCAA Division I-A football season|1989]], [[1990 NCAA Division I-A football season|1990]], [[1991 NCAA Division I-A football season|1991]], [[1994 NCAA Division I-A football season|1994]], [[1996 NCAA Division I-A football season|1996]], [[1997 NCAA Division I-A football season|1997]], [[1998 NCAA Division I-A football season|1998]], [[2005 NCAA Division I-A football season|2005]], [[2008 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2008]], [[2009 NCAA Division I-A football season|2009]], [[2013 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2013]], [[2016 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2016]], [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2017]]\n\n==Hall of Fame==\n===Pro Football Hall of Fame===\n{{see also|Pro Football Hall of Fame}}\nPenn State is one of 11 schools with five or more inductees in the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"pro football hof\">{{cite web|url=http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/colleges.html|title=Hall of Famers by College|publisher=Pro Football Hall of Fame|accessdate=November 5, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071021025213/http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/colleges.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = October 21, 2007}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Penn State Nittany Lions|Name|Position|NFL team(s)|Inducted}}\n|-\n| [[Jack Ham]] || [[Linebacker|LB]] || [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] || 1988\n|-\n| [[Franco Harris]] || [[Running back|RB]] || [[Pittsburgh Steelers]], [[Seattle Seahawks]] || 1990\n|-\n| [[Mike Michalske]] || [[Guard (American football)|G]] || [[Green Bay Packers]] || 1964\n|-\n| [[Lenny Moore]] || [[Wide receiver|WR]]/[[Running back|RB]] || [[Baltimore Colts]] || 1975\n|-\n| [[Mike Munchak]] || [[Guard (American football)|G]] || [[Houston Oilers]] || 2001\n|-\n| [[Dave Robinson (American football)|Dave Robinson]] || [[Linebacker (American football)|LB]] || [[Washington Redskins]], [[Green Bay Packers]] || 2013\n|}\n\n===College Football Hall of Fame===\n{{see also|College Football Hall of Fame}}\n\nIncluding former head coach Joe Paterno, 24 Nittany Lion players and coaches have been selected for the [[College Football Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"college football hof\">{{cite web|url=http://collegefootball.org/famersearch.php?name=&school=penn+state&startyear=&endyear=&inductyear=&position=&sortby=name&submitted=1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071121203916/http://collegefootball.org/famersearch.php?name=&school=penn+state&startyear=&endyear=&inductyear=&position=&sortby=name&submitted=1|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 21, 2007|title=Hall of Famers by College|publisher=College Football Hall of Fame|accessdate=November 5, 2007}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Penn State Nittany Lions|Name|Position|Inducted}}\n|-\n| [[Hugo Bezdek]] || [[Head coach|Coach]] || 1954\n|-\n| [[John Cappelletti]] || [[Running back|RB]] || 1993\n|-\n| [[Kerry Collins]] || [[Quarterback|QB]] || 2018\n|-\n| [[Shane Conlan]] || [[Linebacker|LB]] || 2014\n|-\n| [[Keith Dorney]] || [[Offensive tackle|OT]] || 2005\n|-\n| [[Rip Engle]] || [[Head coach|Coach]] || 1973\n|-\n| [[Jack Ham]] || [[Linebacker|LB]] || 1990\n|-\n| [[Dick Harlow]] || [[Head coach|Coach]] || 1954\n|-\n| [[Bob Higgins (football player)|Bob Higgins]] || [[Head coach|Coach]] || 1954\n|-\n| [[Glenn Killinger]] || [[Quarterback|QB]] || 1971\n|-\n| [[Ted Kwalick]] || [[Tight end|TE]] || 1989\n|-\n| [[Richie Lucas]] || [[Quarterback|QB]] || 1986\n|-\n| [[Pete Mauthe]] || [[Running back|RB]] || 1957\n|-\n| [[Shorty Miller]] || [[Quarterback|QB]] || 1974\n|-\n| [[Lydell Mitchell]] || [[Running back|RB]] || 2004\n|-\n| [[Dennis Onkotz]] || [[Linebacker|LB]] || 1995\n|-\n| [[Joe Paterno]] || [[Head coach|Coach]] || 2007\n|-\n| [[Mike Reid (singer)|Mike Reid]] || [[Defensive tackle|DT]] || 1987\n|-\n| [[Glenn Ressler]] || [[Center (American football)|C]]/[[Guard (American football)|G]] || 2001\n|-\n| [[Dave Robinson (American football)|Dave Robinson]] || [[End (football)|End]] || 1997\n|-\n| [[Steve Suhey]] || [[Guard (American football)|G]] || 1985\n|-\n| [[Dexter Very]] || [[End (football)|End]] || 1976\n|-\n| [[Curt Warner]] || [[Running back|RB]] || 2009\n|-\n| [[Harry Wilson (American football)|Harry Wilson]] || [[Running back|RB]] || 1973\n|}\n\n== Future non-conference opponents ==\nAnnounced schedules as of October 10, 2019.<ref name=\"nonconfopp\">{{cite web| title=Penn State Nittany Lions Football Future Schedules|publisher=FBSchedules.com|url=https://fbschedules.com/ncaa/penn-state/|accessdate=October 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Penn State Nittany Lions|2020|2021|2022|2023|2024|2025|2026|2027}}\n|-\n| [[Kent State Golden Flashes football|Kent State]]\n| [[Ball State Cardinals football|Ball State]]\n| [[Ohio Bobcats|Ohio]]\n| [[West Virginia Mountaineers football|West Virginia]]\n| at [[West Virginia Mountaineers football|West Virginia]]\n| [[Virginia Tech Hokies football|Virginia Tech]]\n| at [[Temple Owls football | Temple]]\n| [[Delaware Fightin' Blue Hens football | Delaware]]\n|-\n| at [[Virginia Tech Hokies football|Virginia Tech]]\n| [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]] \n| at [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]]\n| [[Delaware Fightin' Blue Hens football | Delaware]]\n| [[Bowling Green Falcons football | Bowling Green]]\n| [[Villanova Wildcats football | Villanova]]\n|\n| [[Temple Owls football | Temple]]\n|-\n| [[San Jos\u00e9 State Spartans football|San Jos\u00e9 State]]\n| [[Villanova Wildcats football | Villanova]]\n| [[Central Michigan Chippewas football | Central Michigan]]\n| [[UMass Minutemen football | UMass]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Penn State Nittany Lions football navbox}}\n{{Navboxes\n|titlestyle = {{CollegePrimaryStyle|Penn State Nittany Lions|color=white}}\n|list =\n{{The Pennsylvania State University}}\n{{Big Ten Conference football navbox}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Penn State Nittany Lions Football}}\n[[Category:Penn State Nittany Lions football|*]]\n[[Category:American football teams established in 1887]]\n[[Category:1887 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Penn_State_Nittany_Lions_football"}
{"title_page": "Kwaidan (film)", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Kaidan (film)|the 2007 film|Kaidan (2007 film)}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=October 2014}}\n{{missing information|the film's production, release, and legacy|date=August 2015}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Kwaidan\n| image          = Kwaidan-poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| film name      = <!--(for non-English films: film's name in its native language)-->\n| director       = [[Masaki Kobayashi]]\n| producer       = Shigeru Wakatsuki{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=217}}\n| writer         = <!-- or: | writers = -->\n| screenplay     = [[Yoko Mizuki]]{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=217}} \n| story          = \n| based on       = {{based on|''[[Kwaidan: Stories and Studies of Strange Things|Stories and Studies of Strange Things]]''|[[Lafcadio Hearn]]}}\n| starring       = {{plainlist|*[[Rentar\u014d Mikuni]]\n*[[Keiko Kishi]]\n*Kazuo Nakamura\n*Kanemon Nakamura}}\n| music          = [[Toru Takemitsu]]{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=217}}\n| cinematography = [[Yoshio Miyajima]]{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=217}}\n| editing        = Hisashi Sagara{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=217}}\n| production companies = {{plainlist|*Bengei Pro\n*Ninjin Club{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=217}}}}\n| distributor    = [[Toho]]\n| released       = {{film date|1965|1|6|Japan}}\n| runtime        = 182 minutes{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=217}}\n| country        = Japan\n| language       = Japanese\n| budget         = \n| gross          = <!--(please use condensed and rounded values, e.g. \"\u00a311.6 million\" not \"\u00a311,586,221\")-->\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''''Kwaidan'''''|\u602a\u8ac7|Kaidan|literally \"ghost stories\"}} is a 1965 Japanese [[anthology film|anthology]] [[horror film]] directed by [[Masaki Kobayashi]]. It is based on stories from [[Lafcadio Hearn]]'s collections of Japanese [[folklore|folk tales]], mainly ''[[Kwaidan: Stories and Studies of Strange Things]]'', for which it is named. The film consists of four separate and unrelated stories. ''Kwaidan'' is an [[Historical kana orthography|archaic]] [[Romanization of Japanese|transliteration]] of ''[[Kaidan]]'', meaning \"ghost story\". It won the [[Jury Prize (Cannes Film Festival)|Special Jury Prize]] at the [[1965 Cannes Film Festival]],<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/2895/year/1965.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Kwaidan |accessdate=2009-03-04|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref> and received an [[Academy Award]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]].<ref name=\"Oscars1966\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1966 |title=The 38th Academy Awards (1966) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=2011-11-06|work=oscars.org}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n===The Black Hair===\n{{nihongo|\"The Black hair\"|\u9ed2\u9aea|Kurokami}} was adapted from \"The Reconciliation\", which appeared in Hearn's collection ''Shadowings'' (1900).\n\nAn impoverished swordsman divorces his wife, a weaver, and leaves her for a woman of a wealthy family to attain greater social status. \u00a0However, despite his new wealthy status, the swordsman's second marriage proves to be unhappy. His new wife is shown to be callous and selfish. The swordsman regrets leaving his more devoted and patient ex-wife.\n\nThe second wife is furious when she realizes that the swordsman not only married her to obtain her family's wealth, but also still longs for his old life in Kyoto with his ex-wife. When he is told to go into the chambers to reconcile with her, the swordsman refuses, stating his intent to return home and reconcile with his ex-wife. He points out his foolish behavior and poverty as the reasons why he reacted the way he did. The swordsman informs the lady-in-waiting to tell his 2nd wife that their marriage is over and she can return to her parents in shame.\n\nAfter a few years, the swordsman returns to his home to find it in disrepair. He reconciles with his ex-wife, who refuses to let him punish himself. She tells him that she understood that he only left her in order to bring income to their home. The two happily exchange wonderful stories about the past and the future until the swordsman falls asleep. He wakes up the following day only to discover he had been sleeping next to his ex-wife's rotted corpse. Rapidly aging, he escapes the house only to be attacked by his ex-wife\u2019s black hair.\n\n===The Woman of the Snow===\n{{nihongo|\"The Woman of the Snow\"|\u96ea\u5973|Yukionna}} is an adaptation from Hearn's ''[[Kwaidan: Stories and Studies of Strange Things]]'' (1903).\n\nTwo woodcutters named Minokichi and Mosaku take refuge in a fisherman's hut during a snowstorm. Mosaku is killed by a [[Yuki-onna]].  When the Yukionna turns to Minokichi she remarks that he is a handsome boy and takes pity by sparing him because of his youth. The Yuki-onna warns him to never mention what happened or she will kill him.\n\nMinokichi returns home and never mentions that night.  One day while cutting wood he comes across Yuki, a beautiful young woman. She tells him that she is on her way to Edo, as she lost her family and has relatives there who can secure her a job as a lady-in-waiting. Minokichi offers to let her spend the night at his house with his mother. The mother takes a liking to Yuki and asks her to stay. She never leaves for Edo and Minokichi falls in love with her. The two marry and have children, living happily. The older women in the town are in awe over Yuki maintaining her youth even after having three children.\n\nOne night, Minokichi gives Yuki a set of sandals he has made.  She is stitching a kimono in the candlelight.  In the light, Minokichi recalls the Yuki-onna and see a resemblance between them.  He tells her about the strange encounter. It is then that Yuki reveals herself to be the Yuki-onna and a snowstorm comes over the home. Despite the fact he broke his word, she refrains from killing him because of their children. Yuki then leaves Minokichi with the children, warning him to treat them well or she will return and kill him. She disappears into the snowstorm, leaving Minokichi heartbroken.\n\n===Hoichi the Earless===\n{{nihongo|\"Hoichi the Earless\"|\u8033\u7121\u3057\u82b3\u4e00\u306e\u8a71|Miminashi H\u014dichi no Hanashi}} is also adapted from Hearn's ''Kwaidan'' (though it incorporates aspects of ''[[The Tale of the Heike]]'' that are mentioned, but never translated, in Hearn's book).{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n\nHoichi is a young blind musician who plays the [[Biwa h\u014dshi|biwa hoshi]]. His specialty is singing the chant of [[The Tale of the Heike]] about the [[Battle of Dan-no-ura]] fought between the [[Taira clan|Taira]] and [[Minamoto clan|Minamoto]] clans during the last phase of the [[Genpei War]].  Hoichi is an attendant at a temple and is looked after the others there. One night he hears a sound and decides to play his instrument in the garden courtyard.  A spectral samurai appears and tells him that his lord wishes to have a performance at his house.  The samurai leads Hoichi to mysterious and ancient court.  Another attendant notices that he went missing for the night as his dinner was not touched. The samurai re-appears on the next night to take Hoichi and affirms that he has not told anyone.  Afterwards, the priest asks Hoichi why he goes out at night but Hoichi won't tell him.  One night, Hoichi leaves in a storm and his friends follow him and discover he has been going to a graveyard and reciting the Tale of Heike to the court of the [[Emperor Antoku|dead Emperor]].  Hoichi informs the court that it takes many nights to chant the entire epic.  They direct him to chant the final battle - the battle of Dan-no-ura.  His friends drag him home as he refuses to leave before his performance is completed.\n\nThe priest tell Hoichi he is in great danger and that this was a vast illusion from the spirit of the dead.  They tell Hoichi that if he obeys them again they will tear him to pieces.  Concerned for Hoichi\u2019s safety, a priest and his acolyte write the text of The Heart Sutra on his entire body including his face to make him invisible to the ghosts and instruct him to meditate. The samurai re-appears and calls out for Hoichi.  Hoichi does not answer.  Hoichi's ears are visible to the samurai as they forgot to write the text on his ears.  The samurai, wanting to bring back as much of Hoichi as possible, rips his ears off to show his lord his commands have been obeyed. \n\nThe next morning, the priest and the attendants see a trail of blood leading from the temple.  The priest and the acolyte realize their error and believe the ears were a trade for Hoichi's life.  They believe the spirits will now leave him alone.\n\nA local lord attend at the temple with a full retinue.  They have heard the story of Hoichi the earless and wish to hear him play his biwa.  \nHe is brought to court of the lord.  Hoichi says he will play to console the sorrowful spirits and allow them to rest.  \n\nThe narrator indicates than many wealthy noble person would come to the temple with large gifts of money and Hoichi-the-earless became a wealthy person.\n\n===In a Cup of Tea===\n{{nihongo|\"In a Cup of Tea\"|\u8336\u7897\u306e\u4e2d|Chawan no Naka}} is adapted from Hearn's ''Kott\u014d: Being Japanese Curios, with Sundry Cobwebs'' (1902).\n\nAnticipating a visit from his publisher, a writer relates an old tale of an attendant of Lord Nakagawa Sadono named Sekinai. While Lord Nakagawa is his way to make a New Year's visit, he halts with his train at a tea-house in [[Hakusan, Ishikawa|Hakusan]]. While the party is resting there, Sekinai sees the face of a strange man in a cup of tea. Despite being perturbed, he drinks the cup.\n\nLater, while Sekinai is guarding his Lord, the man whose face appeared in the tea reappears, calling himself Heinai Shikibu. Sekinai runs to tell the other attendants, but they laugh and tell him he is seeing things. Later that night at his own residence, Sekinai is visited by three ghostly attendants of Heinai Shikibu. He duels them and is nearly defeated, but the author notes the tale ends before things are resolved and suggests that he could write a complete ending, but prefers to leave the ending to the reader's imagination.\n\nThe publisher soon arrives and asks the Madame for the author, who is nowhere to be found. They both flee the scene in terror when they discover the author trapped inside a large jar of water.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-4}}\n\n===Kurokami===\n\n* [[Michiyo Aratama]] as First wife\n* [[Misako Watanabe]] as Second Wife\n* [[Rentar\u014d Mikuni]] as Husband\n* [[Kenjiro Ishiyama]] as Father\n* [[Ranko Akagi]] as Mother\n\n{{Col-4}}\n\n===Yuki-Onna===\n* [[Tatsuya Nakadai]] as Minokichi\n* [[Keiko Kishi]] as the Yuki-Onna \n* [[Y\u016bko Mochizuki]] as Minokichi's mother\n* [[Kin Sugai]] as Village woman\n* [[Noriko Sengoku]] as Village woman\n\n{{Col-4}}\n\n===Miminashi H\u014dichi no Hanashi===\n* [[Katsuo Nakamura]] as Hoichi\n* [[Tetsur\u014d Tamba]] as Warrior\n* [[Takashi Shimura]] as Head priest\n* [[Yoichi Hayashi]] as [[Minamoto no Yoshitsune]]\n{{Col-4}}\n\n===Chawan no naka===\n* [[Haruko Sugimura]] as Madame\n* [[Osamu Takizawa]] as Author / Narrator\n* [[Ganjir\u014d Nakamura]] as Publisher\n* [[Noboru Nakaya]] as Shikibu Heinai\n* [[Seiji Miyaguchi]] as Old man\n* [[Kei Sat\u014d]] as Ghost samurai\n\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==Production==\nIn 1964, [[Toho]] began a three-film deal with director [[Masaki Kobayashi]] that concluded with the production ''Kwaidan''.{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=451}}\n\n==Release==\nThe [[Roadshow theatrical release|roadshow]] version of ''Kwaidan'' was released theatrically in Japan on January 6, 1965 where it was distributed by [[Toho]].{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=217}} The Japanese general release for ''Kwaidan'' began on February 27, 1965.{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=218}} ''Kwaidan'' was reedited to 125 minutes in the United States for its theatrical release which eliminated the segment \"The Woman of the Snow\" after the film's Los Angeles premiere.{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=217}} It was released in the United States on July 15, 1965 where it was distributed by [[Continental Distributing]].{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=217}} ''Kwaidan'' was re-released theatrically in Japan on November 29, 1982 in Japan as part of Toho's 50th anniversary.{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=332}}\n\n==Reception==\n{{expand section|date=August 2015}}\nIn Japan the film won [[Yoko Mizuki]] the [[Kinema Junpo]] award for Best Screenplay. It also won awards for Best Cinematography and Best Art Direction at the [[Mainichi Film Concours]].{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=217}} The film won international awards including Special Jury Prize at the [[Cannes Film Festival]] and was nominated for the Best Foreign Language Film at the [[Academy Awards]].{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=215}}\n\nIn a 1967 review, the ''[[Monthly Film Bulletin]]'' commented on the colour in the film, stating that \"it is not so much that the colour in ''Kwaidan'' is ravishing...as the way Kobayashi uses it to give these stories something of the quality of a legend.\"<ref name=\"kwaidan-mfb\">{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Monthly Film Bulletin]]|title=Kwaidan|volume=34|issue=396|pages=135\u2013136|year=1967|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|location=London|author=D.W.}}</ref> The review concluded that the ''Kwaidan'' was a film \"whose details stay on in the mind long after one has seen it.\"<ref name=\"kwaidan-mfb\" /> [[Bosley Crowther]], in a 1965 ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' review stated that director Kobayashi \"merits excited acclaim for his distinctly oriental cinematic artistry. So do the many designers and cameramen who worked with him. \"Kwaidan\" is a symphony of color and sound that is truly past compare.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9A07E4DB1639E33ABC4B51DFB767838E679EDE|work=[[New York Times]]|title=Screen: 'Kwaidan,' a Trio of Subtle Horror Tales:Fine Arts Theater Has Japanese Thriller|last=Crowther|first=Bosley|accessdate=September 28, 2016|date=November 23, 1965|authorlink=Bosley Crowther|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160609032227/http://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9A07E4DB1639E33ABC4B51DFB767838E679EDE|archivedate=June 9, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' described the film as \"done in measured cadence and intense feeling\" and that it was \"a visually impressive tour-de-force.\"{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1994|p=100}} \n\nIn his review of ''[[Harakiri (1962 film)|Harakiri]]'', [[Roger Ebert]] described ''Kwaidan'' as \"an assembly of ghost stories that is among the most beautiful films I've seen\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rogerebert.com/reviews/great-movie-harakiri-1962/|title=Harakiri Movie Review|date=November 16, 2011|accessdate=February 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]], ''Kwaidan'' holds an approval rating of 88%, based on 24 reviews, and an average rating of 7.4/10. Its consensus reads, \"Exquisitely designed and fastidiously ornate, Masaki Kobayashi's ambitious anthology operates less as a frightening example of horror and more as a meditative tribute to Japanese folklore.\"<ref name=\"rottomatoes\">{{cite web |title=KAIDAN (KWAIDAN) (GHOST STORIES) (1964) - Rotten Tomatoes |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/kwaidan |website=Rotten Tomatoes.com |publisher=Flixter |accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of ghost films]]\n* [[List of Japanese films of 1965]]\n* [[List of Japanese submissions for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[List of submissions to the 38th Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n\n== References ==\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Galbraith IV |first=Stuart |title=Japanese Science Fiction, Fantasy and Horror Films |publisher=McFarland |date=1994 |isbn=0-89950-853-7 |ref=harv|authorlink=Stuart Galbraith IV}}\n* {{cite book |last=Galbraith IV |first=Stuart |title=The Toho Studios Story: A History and Complete Filmography |publisher=Scarecrow Press |date=2008 |isbn=1461673747 |ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0058279}}\n* {{Rotten-tomatoes|kwaidan}}\n* {{Allmovie title|27783}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.jmdb.ne.jp/1965/co000070.htm|title=\u602a\u8ac7 (Kaidan)|accessdate=2007-07-16|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Japanese Movie Database]]}}\n*[https://www.criterion.com/current/posts/3756-kwaidan-no-way-out ''Kwaidan: No Way Out''] an essay by [[Geoffrey O\u2019Brien]] at the [[Criterion Collection]]\n\n===Text of Lafcadio Hearn stories that were adapted for Kwaidan===\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060620081212/http://www5.ocn.ne.jp/~kilib/hearn/works/shadowings/the_reconciliation.html ''The Reconciliation'' at K.Inadomi's Private Library]\n*[http://www.gutenberg.org/files/1210/1210-h/1210-h.htm#mimi ''The Story of Mimi-nashi-H\u014dichi'' at Gutenberg.org]\n* [http://www.gutenberg.org/files/1210/1210-h/1210-h.htm#yukionna ''Yuki-Onna''] at Gutenberg.org, read at [https://librivox.org/kwaidan-stories-and-studies-of-strange-things-by-lafcadio-hearn/ LibriVox]\n* [http://www.gutenberg.org/files/55473/55473-h/55473-h.htm#In_a_Cup_of_Tea ''In a Cup of Tea'' at Gutenberg.org]\n\n{{Masaki Kobayashi}}\n{{Cannes Film Festival Jury Prize}}\n\n[[Category:Japanese films]]\n[[Category:1965 horror films]]\n[[Category:1960s fantasy films]]\n[[Category:Horror anthology films]]\n[[Category:Jidaigeki films]]\n[[Category:Films based on short fiction]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Masaki Kobayashi]]\n[[Category:Films set in Kyoto]]\n[[Category:Japanese ghost films]]\n[[Category:Japanese horror films]]\n[[Category:Japanese fantasy films]]\n[[Category:Folk horror films]]\n[[Category:Dark fantasy films]]\n[[Category:Japanese-language films]]\n[[Category:1965 films]]\n[[Category:Toho films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Toru Takemitsu]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Kaidan (film)|the 2007 film|Kaidan (2007 film)}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=October 2014}}\n{{missing information|the film's production, release, and legacy|date=August 2015}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Kwaidan\n| image          = Kwaidan-poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| film name      = <!--(for non-English films: film's name in its native language)-->\n| director       = [[Masaki Kobayashi]]\n| producer       = Shigeru Wakatsuki{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=217}}\n| writer         = <!-- or: | writers = -->\n| screenplay     = [[Yoko Mizuki]]{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=217}} \n| story          = \n| based on       = {{based on|''[[Kwaidan: Stories and Studies of Strange Things|Stories and Studies of Strange Things]]''|[[Lafcadio Hearn]]}}\n| starring       = {{plainlist|*[[Rentar\u014d Mikuni]]\n*[[Keiko Kishi]]\n*Kazuo Nakamura\n*Kanemon Nakamura}}\n| music          = [[Toru Takemitsu]]{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=217}}\n| cinematography = [[Yoshio Miyajima]]{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=217}}\n| editing        = Hisashi Sagara{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=217}}\n| production companies = {{plainlist|*Bengei Pro\n*Ninjin Club{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=217}}}}\n| distributor    = [[Toho]]\n| released       = {{film date|1965|1|6|Japan}}\n| runtime        = 182 minutes{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=217}}\n| country        = Japan\n| language       = Japanese\n| budget         = \n| gross          = <!--(please use condensed and rounded values, e.g. \"\u00a311.6 million\" not \"\u00a311,586,221\")-->\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''''Kwaidan'''''|\u602a\u8ac7|Kaidan|literally \"ghost stories\"}} is a 1965 Japanese [[anthology film|anthology]] [[horror film]] directed by [[Masaki Kobayashi]]. It is based on stories from [[Lafcadio Hearn]]'s collections of Japanese [[folklore|folk tales]], mainly ''[[Kwaidan: Stories and Studies of Strange Things]]'', for which it is named. The film consists of four separate and unrelated stories. ''Kwaidan'' is an [[Historical kana orthography|archaic]] [[Romanization of Japanese|transliteration]] of ''[[Kaidan]]'', meaning \"ghost story\". It won the [[Jury Prize (Cannes Film Festival)|Special Jury Prize]] at the [[1965 Cannes Film Festival]],<ref name=\"festival-cannes.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/2895/year/1965.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Kwaidan |accessdate=2009-03-04|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref> and received an [[Academy Award]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]].<ref name=\"Oscars1966\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1966 |title=The 38th Academy Awards (1966) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=2011-11-06|work=oscars.org}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n===The Black Hair===\n{{nihongo|\"The Black hair\"|\u9ed2\u9aea|Kurokami}} was adapted from \"The Reconciliation\", which appeared in Hearn's collection ''Shadowings'' (1900).\n\nAn impoverished swordsman divorces his wife, a weaver, and leaves her for a woman of a wealthy family to attain greater social status. \u00a0However, despite his new wealthy status, the swordsman's second marriage proves to be unhappy. His new wife is shown to be callous and selfish. The swordsman regrets leaving his more devoted and patient ex-wife.\n\nThe second wife is furious when she realizes that the swordsman not only married her to obtain her family's wealth, but also still longs for his old life in Kyoto with his ex-wife. When he is told to go into the chambers to reconcile with her, the swordsman refuses, stating his intent to return home and reconcile with his ex-wife. He points out his foolish behavior and poverty as the reasons why he reacted the way he did. The swordsman informs the lady-in-waiting to tell his 2nd wife that their marriage is over and she can return to her parents in shame.\n\nAfter a few years, the swordsman returns to his home to find it in disrepair. He reconciles with his ex-wife, who refuses to let him punish himself. She tells him that she understood that he only left her in order to bring income to their home. The two happily exchange wonderful stories about the past and the future until the swordsman falls asleep. He wakes up the following day only to discover he had been sleeping next to his ex-wife's rotted corpse. Rapidly aging, he escapes the house only to be attacked by his ex-wife\u2019s black hair.\n\n===The Woman of the Snow===\n{{nihongo|\"The Woman of the Snow\"|\u96ea\u5973|Yukionna}} is an adaptation from Hearn's ''[[Kwaidan: Stories and Studies of Strange Things]]'' (1903).\n\nTwo woodcutters named Minokichi and Mosaku take refuge in a fisherman's hut during a snowstorm. Mosaku is killed by a [[Yuki-onna]].  When the Yukionna turns to Minokichi she remarks that he is a handsome boy and takes pity by sparing him because of his youth. The Yuki-onna warns him to never mention what happened or she will kill him.\n\nMinokichi returns home and never mentions that night.  One day while cutting wood he comes across Yuki, a beautiful young woman. She tells him that she is on her way to Edo, as she lost her family and has relatives there who can secure her a job as a lady-in-waiting. Minokichi offers to let her spend the night at his house with his mother. The mother takes a liking to Yuki and asks her to stay. She never leaves for Edo and Minokichi falls in love with her. The two marry and have children, living happily. The older women in the town are in awe over Yuki maintaining her youth even after having three children.\n\nOne night, Minokichi gives Yuki a set of sandals he has made.  She is stitching a kimono in the candlelight.  In the light, Minokichi recalls the Yuki-onna and see a resemblance between them.  He tells her about the strange encounter. It is then that Yuki reveals herself to be the Yuki-onna and a snowstorm comes over the home. Despite the fact he broke his word, she refrains from killing him because of their children. Yuki then leaves Minokichi with the children, warning him to treat them well or she will return and kill him. She disappears into the snowstorm, leaving Minokichi heartbroken.\n\n===Hoichi the Earless===\n{{nihongo|\"Hoichi the Earless\"|\u8033\u7121\u3057\u82b3\u4e00\u306e\u8a71|Miminashi H\u014dichi no Hanashi}} is also adapted from Hearn's ''Kwaidan'' (though it incorporates aspects of ''[[The Tale of the Heike]]'' that are mentioned, but never translated, in Hearn's book).{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n\nHoichi is a young blind musician who plays the biwa. [[Biwa h\u014dshi|biwa hoshi]] His specialty is singing the chant of [[The Tale of the Heike]] about the [[Battle of Dan-no-ura]] fought between the [[Taira clan|Taira]] and [[Minamoto clan|Minamoto]] clans during the last phase of the [[Genpei War]].  Hoichi is an attendant at a temple and is looked after the others there. One night he hears a sound and decides to play his instrument in the garden courtyard.  A spectral samurai appears and tells him that his lord wishes to have a performance at his house.  The samurai leads Hoichi to mysterious and ancient court.  Another attendant notices that he went missing for the night as his dinner was not touched. The samurai re-appears on the next night to take Hoichi and affirms that he has not told anyone.  Afterwards, the priest asks Hoichi why he goes out at night but Hoichi won't tell him.  One night, Hoichi leaves in a storm and his friends follow him and discover he has been going to a graveyard and reciting the Tale of Heike to the court of the [[Emperor Antoku|dead Emperor]].  Hoichi informs the court that it takes many nights to chant the entire epic.  They direct him to chant the final battle - the battle of Dan-no-ura.  His friends drag him home as he refuses to leave before his performance is completed.\n\nThe priest tell Hoichi he is in great danger and that this was a vast illusion from the spirit of the dead.  They tell Hoichi that if he obeys them again they will tear him to pieces.  Concerned for Hoichi\u2019s safety, a priest and his acolyte write the text of The Heart Sutra on his entire body including his face to make him invisible to the ghosts and instruct him to meditate. The samurai re-appears and calls out for Hoichi.  Hoichi does not answer.  Hoichi's ears are visible to the samurai as they forgot to write the text on his ears.  The samurai, wanting to bring back as much of Hoichi as possible, rips his ears off to show his lord his commands have been obeyed. \n\nThe next morning, the priest and the attendants see a trail of blood leading from the temple.  The priest and the acolyte realize their error and believe the ears were a trade for Hoichi's life.  They believe the spirits will now leave him alone.\n\nA local lord attend at the temple with a full retinue.  They have heard the story of Hoichi the earless and wish to hear him play his biwa.  \nHe is brought to court of the lord.  Hoichi says he will play to console the sorrowful spirits and allow them to rest.  \n\nThe narrator indicates than many wealthy noble person would come to the temple with large gifts of money and Hoichi-the-earless became a wealthy person.\n\n===In a Cup of Tea===\n{{nihongo|\"In a Cup of Tea\"|\u8336\u7897\u306e\u4e2d|Chawan no Naka}} is adapted from Hearn's ''Kott\u014d: Being Japanese Curios, with Sundry Cobwebs'' (1902).\n\nAnticipating a visit from his publisher, a writer relates an old tale of an attendant of Lord Nakagawa Sadono named Sekinai. While Lord Nakagawa is his way to make a New Year's visit, he halts with his train at a tea-house in [[Hakusan, Ishikawa|Hakusan]]. While the party is resting there, Sekinai sees the face of a strange man in a cup of tea. Despite being perturbed, he drinks the cup.\n\nLater, while Sekinai is guarding his Lord, the man whose face appeared in the tea reappears, calling himself Heinai Shikibu. Sekinai runs to tell the other attendants, but they laugh and tell him he is seeing things. Later that night at his own residence, Sekinai is visited by three ghostly attendants of Heinai Shikibu. He duels them and is nearly defeated, but the author notes the tale ends before things are resolved and suggests that he could write a complete ending, but prefers to leave the ending to the reader's imagination.\n\nThe publisher soon arrives and asks the Madame for the author, who is nowhere to be found. They both flee the scene in terror when they discover the author trapped inside a large jar of water.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-4}}\n\n===Kurokami===\n\n* [[Michiyo Aratama]] as First wife\n* [[Misako Watanabe]] as Second Wife\n* [[Rentar\u014d Mikuni]] as Husband\n* [[Kenjiro Ishiyama]] as Father\n* [[Ranko Akagi]] as Mother\n\n{{Col-4}}\n\n===Yuki-Onna===\n* [[Tatsuya Nakadai]] as Minokichi\n* [[Keiko Kishi]] as the Yuki-Onna \n* [[Y\u016bko Mochizuki]] as Minokichi's mother\n* [[Kin Sugai]] as Village woman\n* [[Noriko Sengoku]] as Village woman\n\n{{Col-4}}\n\n===Miminashi H\u014dichi no Hanashi===\n* [[Katsuo Nakamura]] as Hoichi\n* [[Tetsur\u014d Tamba]] as Warrior\n* [[Takashi Shimura]] as Head priest\n* [[Yoichi Hayashi]] as [[Minamoto no Yoshitsune]]\n{{Col-4}}\n\n===Chawan no naka===\n* [[Haruko Sugimura]] as Madame\n* [[Osamu Takizawa]] as Author / Narrator\n* [[Ganjir\u014d Nakamura]] as Publisher\n* [[Noboru Nakaya]] as Shikibu Heinai\n* [[Seiji Miyaguchi]] as Old man\n* [[Kei Sat\u014d]] as Ghost samurai\n\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==Production==\nIn 1964, [[Toho]] began a three-film deal with director [[Masaki Kobayashi]] that concluded with the production ''Kwaidan''.{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=451}}\n\n==Release==\nThe [[Roadshow theatrical release|roadshow]] version of ''Kwaidan'' was released theatrically in Japan on January 6, 1965 where it was distributed by [[Toho]].{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=217}} The Japanese general release for ''Kwaidan'' began on February 27, 1965.{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=218}} ''Kwaidan'' was reedited to 125 minutes in the United States for its theatrical release which eliminated the segment \"The Woman of the Snow\" after the film's Los Angeles premiere.{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=217}} It was released in the United States on July 15, 1965 where it was distributed by [[Continental Distributing]].{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=217}} ''Kwaidan'' was re-released theatrically in Japan on November 29, 1982 in Japan as part of Toho's 50th anniversary.{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=332}}\n\n==Reception==\n{{expand section|date=August 2015}}\nIn Japan the film won [[Yoko Mizuki]] the [[Kinema Junpo]] award for Best Screenplay. It also won awards for Best Cinematography and Best Art Direction at the [[Mainichi Film Concours]].{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=217}} The film won international awards including Special Jury Prize at the [[Cannes Film Festival]] and was nominated for the Best Foreign Language Film at the [[Academy Awards]].{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=215}}\n\nIn a 1967 review, the ''[[Monthly Film Bulletin]]'' commented on the colour in the film, stating that \"it is not so much that the colour in ''Kwaidan'' is ravishing...as the way Kobayashi uses it to give these stories something of the quality of a legend.\"<ref name=\"kwaidan-mfb\">{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Monthly Film Bulletin]]|title=Kwaidan|volume=34|issue=396|pages=135\u2013136|year=1967|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]|location=London|author=D.W.}}</ref> The review concluded that the ''Kwaidan'' was a film \"whose details stay on in the mind long after one has seen it.\"<ref name=\"kwaidan-mfb\" /> [[Bosley Crowther]], in a 1965 ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' review stated that director Kobayashi \"merits excited acclaim for his distinctly oriental cinematic artistry. So do the many designers and cameramen who worked with him. \"Kwaidan\" is a symphony of color and sound that is truly past compare.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9A07E4DB1639E33ABC4B51DFB767838E679EDE|work=[[New York Times]]|title=Screen: 'Kwaidan,' a Trio of Subtle Horror Tales:Fine Arts Theater Has Japanese Thriller|last=Crowther|first=Bosley|accessdate=September 28, 2016|date=November 23, 1965|authorlink=Bosley Crowther|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160609032227/http://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9A07E4DB1639E33ABC4B51DFB767838E679EDE|archivedate=June 9, 2016}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' described the film as \"done in measured cadence and intense feeling\" and that it was \"a visually impressive tour-de-force.\"{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1994|p=100}} \n\nIn his review of ''[[Harakiri (1962 film)|Harakiri]]'', [[Roger Ebert]] described ''Kwaidan'' as \"an assembly of ghost stories that is among the most beautiful films I've seen\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rogerebert.com/reviews/great-movie-harakiri-1962/|title=Harakiri Movie Review|date=November 16, 2011|accessdate=February 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]], ''Kwaidan'' holds an approval rating of 88%, based on 24 reviews, and an average rating of 7.4/10. Its consensus reads, \"Exquisitely designed and fastidiously ornate, Masaki Kobayashi's ambitious anthology operates less as a frightening example of horror and more as a meditative tribute to Japanese folklore.\"<ref name=\"rottomatoes\">{{cite web |title=KAIDAN (KWAIDAN) (GHOST STORIES) (1964) - Rotten Tomatoes |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/kwaidan |website=Rotten Tomatoes.com |publisher=Flixter |accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of ghost films]]\n* [[List of Japanese films of 1965]]\n* [[List of Japanese submissions for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n* [[List of submissions to the 38th Academy Awards for Best Foreign Language Film]]\n\n== References ==\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Galbraith IV |first=Stuart |title=Japanese Science Fiction, Fantasy and Horror Films |publisher=McFarland |date=1994 |isbn=0-89950-853-7 |ref=harv|authorlink=Stuart Galbraith IV}}\n* {{cite book |last=Galbraith IV |first=Stuart |title=The Toho Studios Story: A History and Complete Filmography |publisher=Scarecrow Press |date=2008 |isbn=1461673747 |ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0058279}}\n* {{Rotten-tomatoes|kwaidan}}\n* {{Allmovie title|27783}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.jmdb.ne.jp/1965/co000070.htm|title=\u602a\u8ac7 (Kaidan)|accessdate=2007-07-16|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Japanese Movie Database]]}}\n*[https://www.criterion.com/current/posts/3756-kwaidan-no-way-out ''Kwaidan: No Way Out''] an essay by [[Geoffrey O\u2019Brien]] at the [[Criterion Collection]]\n\n===Text of Lafcadio Hearn stories that were adapted for Kwaidan===\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060620081212/http://www5.ocn.ne.jp/~kilib/hearn/works/shadowings/the_reconciliation.html ''The Reconciliation'' at K.Inadomi's Private Library]\n*[http://www.gutenberg.org/files/1210/1210-h/1210-h.htm#mimi ''The Story of Mimi-nashi-H\u014dichi'' at Gutenberg.org]\n* [http://www.gutenberg.org/files/1210/1210-h/1210-h.htm#yukionna ''Yuki-Onna''] at Gutenberg.org, read at [https://librivox.org/kwaidan-stories-and-studies-of-strange-things-by-lafcadio-hearn/ LibriVox]\n* [http://www.gutenberg.org/files/55473/55473-h/55473-h.htm#In_a_Cup_of_Tea ''In a Cup of Tea'' at Gutenberg.org]\n\n{{Masaki Kobayashi}}\n{{Cannes Film Festival Jury Prize}}\n\n[[Category:Japanese films]]\n[[Category:1965 horror films]]\n[[Category:1960s fantasy films]]\n[[Category:Horror anthology films]]\n[[Category:Jidaigeki films]]\n[[Category:Films based on short fiction]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Masaki Kobayashi]]\n[[Category:Films set in Kyoto]]\n[[Category:Japanese ghost films]]\n[[Category:Japanese horror films]]\n[[Category:Japanese fantasy films]]\n[[Category:Folk horror films]]\n[[Category:Dark fantasy films]]\n[[Category:Japanese-language films]]\n[[Category:1965 films]]\n[[Category:Toho films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Toru Takemitsu]]\n", "name_user": "Jucachaves", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHoichi the Earless", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kwaidan_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Oklahoma Sooners football", "text_new": "{{very long|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox NCAA football school\n| TeamName = Oklahoma Sooners football\n| CurrentSeason = 2020 Oklahoma Sooners football team\n| Image = Oklahoma Sooners logo.svg\n| ImageSize = 125\n| FirstYear = 1895\n| AthleticDirector = [[Joe Castiglione (athletic director)|Joe Castiglione]]\n| HeadCoach = [[Lincoln Riley]]\n| HeadCoachYear = 3rd\n| HCWins = 36 <!-- As of games through 12/28/19 -->\n| HCLosses = 6 <!-- As of games through 12/28/19 -->\n| Stadium = [[Gaylord Family Oklahoma Memorial Stadium]]\n| FieldName = [[Owen Field]]\n| StadCapacity = 80,126\n| StadSurface = Grass\n| Location = [[Norman, Oklahoma]]\n| NCAAdivision = I FBS\n| Conference = [[Big 12 Conference]]\n| PastAffiliations = Independent (1895\u20131914)<br /> [[Southwest Conference|Southwest]] (1915\u20131919)<br />  [[Big Eight Conference|Big Eight]] (1920\u20131995)<br />\n| WebsiteName = soonersports.com\n| WebsiteURL = http://www.soonersports.com/SportSelect.dbml?DB_LANG=C&DB_OEM_ID=31000&SPID=127245\n| ATWins = 908<!-- As of games through 12/07/19 -->\n| ATLosses = 327 <!-- As of games through 12/28/19 -->\n| ATTies = 53 <!-- As of games through 10/12/19 -->\n| PlayoffApps = 4 (2015, 2017, 2018, 2019)\n| Playoffs = 0\u20134 ({{winpct|0|4}})\n| BowlWins = 29\n| BowlLosses = 23\n| BowlTies = 1\n| NatlTitles = 7 (1950, 1955, 1956, 1974, 1975, 1985, 2000)\n| UnNatlTitles = 11 (1915, 1949, 1953, 1957, 1967, 1973, 1978, 1980, 1986, 2003, 2008)\n| ConfTitles = 49<ref name=\"bigeightsports\">{{cite web |url=http://bigeightsports.com/Sports/Football/FootballChampionships.htm |title=Sports/Football/FootballChampionships |publisher=bigeightsports.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref>\n| Heismans = 7\n| AllAmericans = 80\n| uniform = File:Big12-Uniform-OU.png\n| FightSong = [[Boomer Sooner]]\n| MascotDisplay = [[Sooner Schooner]]\n| MarchingBand = [[The Pride of Oklahoma Marching Band]]\n| Rivalries = [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|Nebraska]] ([[Nebraska\u2013Oklahoma football rivalry|rivalry]])<br />[[Oklahoma State Cowboys football|Oklahoma State]] ([[Bedlam Series|rivalry]])<br />[[Texas Longhorns football|Texas]] ([[Red River Showdown|rivalry]])\n}}\nThe '''Oklahoma Sooners football''' program is a [[college football]] team that represents the [[University of Oklahoma]] (variously '''\"Oklahoma\"''' or '''\"OU\"'''). The team is a member of the [[Big 12 Conference]], which is in [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[Football Bowl Subdivision]] (formerly Division I-A) of the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA). The program began in 1895 and is one of the most successful programs since World War II with the most wins (606) and the highest winning percentage (.762) since 1945.<ref>{{cite news | title=Football is a way of life for OU and its fans | publisher=Idaho Statesman | date=December 17, 2006 | accessdate=December 19, 2006 | url=http://www.idahostatesman.com/104/story/64105.html | archive-url=https://archive.today/20140830005003/http://www.idahostatesman.com/104/story/64105.html | url-status=dead | archive-date=August 30, 2014 | first=Chadd | last=Cripe }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=OU No. 1 Program of the Modern Era |publisher=SoonerSports.com |url=http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/m-footbl-no1-program-modern-era.html |accessdate=August 21, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071120093043/http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/m-footbl-no1-program-modern-era.html |archivedate=November 20, 2007 }}</ref> The program claims 7 national championships, 49 conference championships, 162 First Team&nbsp;[[All-Americans]] (80 consensus),<ref name=\"cfbdatawarehouse\">{{cite web|url=http://cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/active/o/oklahoma/national_champs.php |title=Oklahoma All National Championships |publisher=cfbdatawarehouse.com |accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/m-footbl-all-americans.html |publisher=University of Oklahoma Athletics Department |title=SoonerSports.com \u2013 Official Site of the Oklahoma Sooners |accessdate=July 13, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100628213711/http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/m-footbl-all-americans.html |archivedate=June 28, 2010 }}</ref> and seven&nbsp;[[Heisman Trophy]] winners. In addition, the school has had 23 members (five coaches and 18&nbsp;players) inducted into the [[College Football Hall of Fame]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://footballfoundation.org/hof_search.aspx|title=Hall of Fame: Select group by school|work=[[College Football Hall of Fame]]|publisher=Football Foundation|accessdate=December 20, 2006 }}</ref> and holds the record for the longest winning streak in Division I history with 47&nbsp;straight victories. Oklahoma is also the only program that has had four coaches with 100+ wins. They became the sixth NCAA FBS team to win 900&nbsp;games when they defeated the Texas Tech Red Raiders on September 28, 2019. The Sooners play their home games at [[Gaylord Family Oklahoma Memorial Stadium]] in [[Norman, Oklahoma]]. [[Lincoln Riley]] is currently the team's head coach.\n\n==History==\n{{See also|List of Oklahoma Sooners football seasons}}\n{{split section|History of Oklahoma Sooners football|date=January 2019}}\n\n===Early history (1895\u20131905)===\nFootball at Oklahoma made its start in September 1895, 12&nbsp;years before statehood and one year after the first organized football game in [[Oklahoma Territory]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://digital.libraries.ou.edu/sooner/articles/p36-37_1936v9n2_OCR.pdf|title=Football Myths|publisher=Sooner Magazine|date=1936|accessdate=January 3, 2018}}</ref> The team was organized by [[John A. Harts]], a student from [[Winfield, Kansas]] who had played the game in his home state.<ref name=\"upsdowns\">{{cite news | first=Harold | last=Keith | pages=12\u201313, 54 | title=Football Ups and Downs | date=September 1942 | publisher=Sooner Magazine | url=http://digital.libraries.ou.edu/sooner/articles/p12-13,54_1942v15n1_OCR.pdf }}</ref><ref name=\"newsok.com\">{{cite web|url=http://newsok.com/article/3335547|title=OU football: TALE OF THE TAPE|date=January 6, 2009|accessdate=January 7, 2009|publisher=newsok.com}}</ref> That first team was composed of mostly non-students, including a local fireman.<ref name=\"newsok.com\"/> That first \"season\" saw the team go 0\u20131, being blanked 0\u201334 by a more experienced [[Oklahoma City]] Town Team (the Sooners could not even muster a [[first down]]).<ref name=\"newsok.com\"/> The first game was played on a field of low prairie grass just northwest of the current site of Holmberg Hall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soonersports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=208803880|title=STADIUM HISTORY OU Football History & Tradition|publisher=University of Oklahoma Athletics|date=2018|accessdate=September 1, 2018}}</ref> Several members of the Oklahoma team were injured, including Coach Harts, and by the end of the game, the Oklahoma team was borrowing members from the opposing squad so they would have a full lineup. After that year, Harts left Oklahoma to become a gold prospector.<ref name=\"kidsgame\">{{cite news | first=Carol | last=Burr | page=Inside front cover | title=If you think football is just a kids' game, you didn't attend the University of Oklahoma | date=Fall 1998 | url=http://digital.libraries.ou.edu/sooner/articles/prologue_1998v19n1_OCR.pdf | publisher=Sooner Magazine |format=PDF}}</ref>\n\nThe team got its first real coach in 1897 when the new modern language professor, [[Vernon Louis Parrington]], was named head coach (they played two games in 1896 with no coach).<ref name=\"astonisher.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.astonisher.com/archives/parrington.html|title=Vernon Louis Parrington: America's Greatest Historian by Bruce Brown|author=Running Dog|publisher=astonisher.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> Parrington played some football at [[Harvard]] and was more exposed to football coming from the [[East Coast of the United States|East coast]]. In his four years as head coach (1897\u20131900), Parrington's teams racked up nine wins, two losses, and one tie.<ref name=\"astonisher.com\"/><ref name=\"SoonerStats\">{{cite web | url=http://soonerstats.com/football/coaches/ou/index.cfm | title=Football Coaches | publisher=SoonerStats.com  | accessdate=August 2, 2006 }}</ref> After the 1900&nbsp;season, football began interfering with Parrington's teaching, his real passion. He stepped down as head coach shortly thereafter and went on to win the [[Pulitzer Prize for History]] in 1928&nbsp;at the [[University of Washington]].<ref name=\"astonisher.com\"/>\n\n[[File:OU-ArkCity 1899.jpg|right|thumb|300px|Oklahoma vs. Arkansas City (Kansas) Town Team in 1899 with Vernon Parrington as coach.]]\nThe Sooners had three more coaches over the next four seasons. [[Fred Roberts]] led the Sooners to a 3\u20132 season in 1901, [[Mark McMahon (American football)|Mark McMahon]] recorded an 11\u20137\u20133 record in his two years as coach in 1902 and 1903,<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/mark-mcmahon-1.html|title=Mark McMahon Coaching Record &#124; College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=sports-reference.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> and [[Fred Ewing]] recorded a 4\u20133\u20131 record in 1904.<ref name=\"SoonerStats\"/> The most notable event of those four years came in 1904 when Oklahoma had its first match against its in-state rival, [[Oklahoma State Cowboys football|Oklahoma A&M]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iRBRTABxO1EC&pg=PA7&lpg=PA7&dq=oklahoma+oklahoma+a&m+1904+football&source=bl&ots=EKjCwp8mmR&sig=Dk3QLqQyyMKkXYDWlUPg81LMbw8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjL9_CblYjWAhUX84MKHSWRCJ0Q6AEITzAL#v=onepage&q=oklahoma+oklahoma+a&m+1904+football&f=false|title=The Oklahoma Football Encyclopedia|first=Ray|last=Dozier|date=September 29, 2017|publisher=Sports Publishing LLC|via=Google Books}}</ref> The game was played on November 6, 1904 at Mineral Wells Park in [[Guthrie, Oklahoma]].<ref name=\"auto\"/> The Oklahoma team soundly defeated the Oklahoma Aggies 75\u20130, but it was an unusual touchdown that is remembered most of that game. [[Bedlam Series|Bedlam]] football, the athletic rivalry between the University of Oklahoma and Oklahoma State University, was born that day.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://newsok.com/article/2872074/a-century-old-battlebrou-osu-fans-memorialize-bedlams-beginning |title=A Century-Old Battle, OU, OSU fans memorialize Bedlam's beginning |date=October 30, 2018 |website=NewsOK.com |language=en-US |accessdate=September 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Bennie Owen era (1905\u20131926)===\n\nAfter ten years of football, the program began to get serious and started looking for a permanent head coach. They found [[Bennie Owen]],<ref name=\"bleacherreport.com\">{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/130293-sooners-legends-bennie-owen|title=Sooners Legends: Bennie Owen &#124; Bleacher Report|publisher=bleacherreport.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> a former [[quarterback]] of the undefeated [[Kansas Jayhawks football|Kansas]] team of 1899 led by famous coach [[Fielding H. Yost]].\n\n[[File:1915 Sooner Football team.png|thumb|The undefeated team of 1915.]]\nOwen's previous team beat Oklahoma twice in 1903 and 1904, so the Sooners were familiar with his ability. Owen's first two years at Oklahoma were spent between [[Norman, Oklahoma|Norman]] and [[Arkansas City, Arkansas|Arkansas City]] as Oklahoma did not have a big enough budget to keep him there all year.<ref name=\"ou.edu\">https://digital.libraries.ou.edu/sooner/articles/p12-13,54_1942v15n1_OCR.pdf</ref> The early years of Owen's tenure were tough because of budget issues. Due to a low travel budget, his teams would regularly have to play as many as three games in one trek.<ref name=\"upsdowns\"/><ref name=\"bleacherreport.com\"/> For instance, in 1905, his squad played three teams in three [[Kansas]] cities in five days and again in 1909 when they played three games in [[Missouri]] and [[Texas]] in six days.<ref name=\"ou.edu\"/> In Owen's first year, 1905, he gave Oklahoma its first victory over rival [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas]], defeating them 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/columns/story?columnist=maisel_ivan&id=2183416|title=Maisel: The top 100 in 100 years of Texas-Oklahoma|date=October 7, 2005|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> Owen's first dominant team came in 1908 when they went 8\u20131\u20131, losing only to the powerful [[Kansas Jayhawks football|Kansas]] team.<ref name=\"sports-reference.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/bennie-owen-1.html|title=Bennie Owen Coaching Record &#124; College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=sports-reference.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> His 1908 team used hand-offs directly to large runners as the forward pass was just becoming common.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0n90CQAAQBAJ&pg=PA118&lpg=PA118&dq=1908+oklahoma+football+handoffs&source=bl&ots=O1FVtGTA3z&sig=BsVW7J2U26uWwsv9ncX0Fhdha8Y&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjnmfL2lojWAhUjw4MKHV9dCEsQ6AEIUzAK#v=onepage&q=1908+oklahoma+football+handoffs&f=false|title=Oklahoma's Bennie Owen: Man for All Seasons|first=Gary|last=King|date=April 20, 2015|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|via=Google Books}}</ref> His [[1911 Oklahoma Sooners football team|1911]] team, on the other hand, had several small and fast players that the quarterback would pass directly to.<ref name=\"ou.edu\"/> That team went 8\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soonerstats.com/football/seasons/schedule.cfm?seasonid=1911#.WauFpLpFyP8|title=1911 OU Football Season Schedule \u2013 SoonerStats \u2013 Oklahoma Sooners Football, Basketball, Baseball, and Softball Scores, Records, and Stats|website=www.soonerstats.com}}</ref> Owen had two more undefeated seasons in [[1915 Oklahoma Sooners football team|1915]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/oklahoma/1915-schedule.html|title=1915 Oklahoma Sooners Schedule and Results - College Football at Sports-Reference.com|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com}}</ref> and [[1918 Oklahoma Sooners football team|1918]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/oklahoma/1918-schedule.html|title=1918 Oklahoma Sooners Schedule and Results - College Football at Sports-Reference.com|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com}}</ref> [[1920 Oklahoma Sooners football team|1920]] was also Oklahoma's first season in the stronger [[Big Eight Conference|Missouri Valley Intercollegiate Athletic Association]] after three season in the [[Southwest Conference]] of which it was a founding member.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/blog/dallas/colleges/post/_/id/4668611/history-lessons-big-12-big-8-swc|title=History lessons: Big 12, Big 8, SWC|publisher=}}</ref> In the new conference, they went 6\u20130\u20131 tying only [[Kansas State Wildcats football|Kansas State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/oklahoma/1920-schedule.html|title=1920 Oklahoma Sooners Schedule and Results - College Football at Sports-Reference.com|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com}}</ref> Owen retired after the 1926 season.<ref name=\"bleacherreport.com\"/> During Owen's 22-year career at Oklahoma, he went 122\u201354\u201316, a 67.7%&nbsp;winning percentage.<ref name=\"SoonerStats\"/><ref name=\"sports-reference.com\"/> In 1951, he became the first person from Oklahoma to be inducted into the College Football Hall of Fame in its inaugural year.<ref name=\"bleacherreport.com\"/>\n\n===Between Owen and Wilkinson (1927\u20131947)===\n\nIn 1927, OU hired [[Adrian Lindsey]] to coach the football team.<ref name=\"soonersports.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.soonersports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=208798710|title=sports_m-footbl_archive_head_coaches \u2013 Oklahoma Sooners|publisher=soonersports.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> Before arriving in Norman, Lindsey arrived from his alma mater [[Kansas Jayhawks football|Kansas]], where he served as an assistant.<ref name=\"ou.edu1\">https://digital.libraries.ou.edu/sooner/articles/p263-265,282-286_1932v4n8_OCR.pdf</ref> Lindsey is remembered as the coach who resigned quietly after failing to produce a winning team.<ref name=\"ou.edu1\"/> Lindsey finished his tenure in Norman with a 19\u201319\u20136 record.<ref name=\"sports-reference2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/adrian-lindsey-1.html|title=Adrian Lindsey Coaching Record &#124; College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=sports-reference.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> OU's teams of that era often suffered from being undermanned and undersized against their opponents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dEaACQAAQBAJ&pg=PT113&lpg=PT113&dq=adrian+lindsey+oklahoma+players+small&source=bl&ots=_ROcslCR94&sig=W-gPLExCQLxFp-gshhtNehqym6I&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiZotjWmIjWAhUI74MKHQ6iATwQ6AEIWTAL#v=onepage&q=adrian+lindsey+oklahoma+players+small&f=false|title=Campus Ghosts of Norman, Oklahoma|first=Jeff|last=Provine|date=September 17, 2013|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|via=Google Books}}</ref> Lindsey's 1929 Sooners team defeated [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|Nebraska]], 20\u20137, Nebraska's worst loss against a conference opponent in 20 years.<ref name=\"soonersports.com\"/> In 1931, Oklahoma became the first program from the Big Six to travel to [[Honolulu, Hawaii]] and play the [[Hawaii Warriors football|Hawaii Warriors]]. Oklahoma won the contest 7\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iRBRTABxO1EC&pg=PA52&lpg=PA52&dq=1931+oklahoma+vs+hawaii+football+7-0&source=bl&ots=EKjCwp9neR&sig=rWSYX4NtadQ1zZyMFpv1fFsUGEA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjyw_6BmYjWAhVK54MKHaHJDAQQ6AEILDAB#v=onepage&q=1931+oklahoma+vs+hawaii+football+7-0&f=false|title=The Oklahoma Football Encyclopedia|first=Ray|last=Dozier|date=September 29, 2017|publisher=Sports Publishing LLC|via=Google Books}}</ref> This game marked the first time a university located in the central continental United States was asked to play in the islands.<ref name=\"soonersports.com\"/> Lindsey resigned as head coach after the 1931 season.<ref name=\"soonersports.com\"/>\n\nIn 1932 following Lindsey's resignation Oklahoma hired [[Vanderbilt Commodores football|Vanderbilt]]   running backs coach [[Lewie Hardage]] as head coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xL52CQAAQBAJ&pg=PT52&lpg=PT52&dq=lewie+hardage+vanderbilt&source=bl&ots=LmfoE3bs2u&sig=xYbGwI7JJxXqfXYUrfQFtMoPfbU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjC1NqlmYjWAhXD7oMKHbDHARoQ6AEIVDAI|title=Vanderbilt Football: Tales of Commodore Gridiron History|first=Bill|last=Traughber|date=September 8, 2011|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|via=Google Books}}</ref> After being hired, he emphasized speed by fabricating new lighter uniforms and trimming the grass on Owen Field.<ref name=\"soonersports.com\"/> For much of his tenure at OU, Hardage suffered from a sickness that resulted from accidentally swallowing a poison tablet he mistook for a headache tablet.<ref name=\"google\">{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1876&dat=19321125&id=MD8sAAAAIBAJ&sjid=m8oEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5897,2006233|title=Lewie Hardage has accident|work=Herald-Journal|via=Google News Archive Search|publisher=news.google.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> After a 3\u20130 start to the 1932 campaign, the Sooners began to struggle after running back [[Bill Pansze]] suffered a season ending knee injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soonersports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=208798710|title=sports_m-footbl_archive_head_coaches|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"soonersports.com\"/> Hardage was fired as head coach of the Sooners after the 1934 season. His final record at OU was 11\u201312\u20134.<ref name=\"sports-reference3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/lewie-hardage-1.html|title=Lewie Hardage Coaching Record &#124; College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=sports-reference.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:L. M. \"Biff\" Jones.jpg|150 px|thumb|Coach Biff Jones]]\nThe next head coach, [[Lawrence Mcceney \"Biff\" Jones|Lawrence \"Biff\" Jones]], went 9\u20136\u20133 in his two seasons at the helm,<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/biff-jones-1.html|title=Biff Jones Coaching Record &#124; College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=sports-reference.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> but he is credited for reining in the athletic department's administration, finances, and methods. The whole football program was placed on a solid footing necessary for success in modern times.<ref name=\"upsdowns\"/> Jones was a \"blunt-spoken, hard-nosed military man\" who graduated from [[United States Military Academy|West Point]] in 1917.<ref name=\"Century\">{{cite book |last=Clark |first=J. Brent |title=Sooner Century: 100 Glorious Years of Oklahoma Football |year=1995 |publisher=Quality Sports Publications |isbn=1-885758-04-9 }}</ref> Jones coached [[Army Black Knights football|Army]] from 1926 to 1929 and then was the head coach of [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> His tenure at Oklahoma came during the [[Dust Bowl]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dEUtAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT19&lpg=PT19&dq=biff+jones+oklahoma+dust+bowl&source=bl&ots=UP6z9s9KeQ&sig=MlSgY2gXjdClIiUFbnxMxHyGqAs&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi5g9vcmYjWAhUD4oMKHfNuBjkQ6AEIVDAL#v=onepage&q=biff+jones+oklahoma+dust+bowl&f=false|title=Tales from the Oklahoma Sooner Sideline: A Collection of the Greatest Sooner Stories Ever Told|first1=Barry|last1=Switzer|first2=Jay|last2=Upchurch|date=October 1, 2011|publisher=Skyhorse Publishing, Inc.|via=Google Books}}</ref> The dust storms were so thick it would block the sun and the players would be covered in dust at the end of practice.<ref name=\"Century\"/> In 1954, Jones was inducted into the [[College Football Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"footballfoundation\">{{College Football HoF|id=1500|name=Lawrence \"Biff\" Jones|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 1935, Biff Jones hired [[Tom Stidham]] to become an assistant coach.<ref name=\"ou.edu2\">https://digital.libraries.ou.edu/sooner/articles/p83,%2092_1937v9n4_OCR.pdf</ref> When Jones left in 1937, Stidham became the head coach.<ref name=\"ou.edu2\"/> As Oklahoma's 10th football coach, Stidham has a Sooner record .750 winning percentage in the [[Red River Showdown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsok.com/article/3141904|title=The list: OU-Texas coaching rivalries|date=October 6, 2007|publisher=}}</ref> In 1938, Stidham led the Sooners to an undefeated regular season and to their first [[Orange Bowl]], where they lost to Tennessee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/oklahoma/1938-schedule.html|title=1938 Oklahoma Sooners Schedule and Results - College Football at Sports-Reference.com|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://game.orangebowl.org/orange-bowl-history/the-history-of-the-orange-bowl/1930s/1939/|title=1939 \u2013 Orange Bowl|website=game.orangebowl.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.saturdaydownsouth.com/games/1939orangebowltennvsokla/|title=1939 Orange Bowl Tennessee vs Oklahoma|date=August 8, 2014|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsok.com/article/2725307|title=OU goes 'home' to the Orange Bowl|date=January 1, 2001|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nWhen Stidham left in 1941, his assistant coach, [[Dewey Luster]], succeeded him.<ref name=\"google2\">{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2199&dat=19410203&id=ZWBeAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EGENAAAAIBAJ&pg=5301,4079343|work=Lawrence Journal-World|via=Google News Archive Search|title=Dewey Luster is Oklahoma Mentor|publisher=news.google.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> After Luster's first season, a 6\u20133 campaign,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/oklahoma/1941-schedule.html|title=1941 Oklahoma Sooners Schedule and Results - College Football at Sports-Reference.com|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com}}</ref> the [[Imperial Japanese Navy|Japanese]] [[Attack on Pearl Harbor|attacked Pearl Harbor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/pearl-harbor-bombed|title=Pearl Harbor bombed - Dec 07, 1941 - HISTORY.com|publisher=}}</ref> As was the case with schools all over the country, many players left the team to join the military.<ref name=\"upsdowns\"/> Luster stepped down after the 1945 season due to ill health.<ref name=\"google3\">{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1310&dat=19451108&id=DPFPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HQgEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3356,1992440|work=Eugene Register-Guard|title=Dewey Luster Quits Oklahoma Coaching|via=Google News Archive Search|publisher=news.google.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> He attained a 27\u201318\u20133 record in his four seasons at OU,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/snorter-luster-1.html|title=Snorter Luster Coaching Record|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com}}</ref> and his team never finished below second place in the Big Six.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/snorter-luster-1.html|title=Snorter Luster Coaching Record &#124; College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=sports-reference.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> After Luster's resignation, the OU Board of Regents interviewed several candidates for the head football coaching job, among them [[North Carolina]] native [[Jim Tatum]].<ref name=\"bobleesays.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bobleesays.com/Un-used-Content/Archives/All-Archives/The-Legend-(-Reality)-of-Sunny-Jim-Tatum.aspx |title=The Legend &amp; Reality of \"Sunny Jim\" Tatum \u2013 BobLee Says |author=WTE Solutions: G Dickinson |publisher=bobleesays.com |accessdate=May 7, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140315011425/http://www.bobleesays.com/Un-used-Content/Archives/All-Archives/The-Legend-%28-Reality%29-of-Sunny-Jim-Tatum.aspx |archivedate=March 15, 2014 }}</ref> With him, he brought another coach, [[Bud Wilkinson]], who would be his assistant coach.<ref name=\"bobleesays.com\"/> The Board was so impressed with Wilkinson that they considered hiring him for the head coaching position but decided against it as it would be unethical.<ref>{{cite book | title=Presidents Can't Punt: The OU Football Tradition | first=George Lynn | last=Cross | authorlink=George Lynn Cross |date=September 1977 | publisher=University of Oklahoma Press |location=Norman, Oklahoma | isbn=0-8061-1419-3 }}</ref> In the end, they decided to hire Tatum and his assistant over several other coaches including [[Paul \"Bear\" Bryant]].<ref name=\"bobleesays.com\"/> The Sooners had a relatively successful season in 1946, finishing with an 8\u20133 record<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/oklahoma/1946-schedule.html|title=1946 Oklahoma Sooners Schedule and Results - College Football at Sports-Reference.com|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com}}</ref> including a 73\u201312 win over archrival Oklahoma A&M (now Oklahoma State).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsok.com/article/2752360|title=Tatum: OU's vain attraction They called the big guy Coach... among other things|date=August 21, 2001|publisher=The Oklahoman}}</ref> Tatum left OU after one season to accept the head coaching position at [[Maryland Terrapins football|Maryland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1959/09/28/606175/the-ghost-of-jim-tatum|title=THE GHOST OF JIM TATUM|first=Kenneth|last=Rudeen|publisher=Sports Illustrated}}</ref>\n\n===Bud Wilkinson era (1947\u20131963)===\n[[File:JFK-Bud Wilkinson.jpg|thumb|Coach Wilkinson with President [[John F. Kennedy]] at the [[White House]] in 1961]]\nWhen Tatum left for [[Maryland Terrapins football|Maryland]] after the 1946 season,<ref name=\"google4\">{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1298&dat=19511228&id=QNxLAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Z4oDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1841,3529456|work=The Free Lance-Star|title=Jim Tatum Rushes Maryland into Sugar Bowl Preparations|last=Slappey|first=Sterling|via=Google News Archive Search|publisher=news.google.com|date=December 28, 1951|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> [[Bud Wilkinson]] got the promotion to head coach.<ref name=\"espn.go.com\">{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/classic/biography/s/wilkinson_bud.html|title=ESPN Classic \u2013 Wilkinson created Sooners dynasty|publisher=espn.go.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref>\nIn 1947, his first year as a head coach, [[Bud Wilkinson]]'s Sooners went 7\u20132\u20131<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/bud-wilkinson-1.html|title=Bud Wilkinson Coaching Record &#124; College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=sports-reference.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> and shared the conference title with [[Kansas Jayhawks football|Kansas]] for the second year in a row. In 1949, the Sooners went undefeated, defeating LSU 35\u20140 in the [[1950 Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsok.com/article/3918552|title=Oklahoma football: A look at the Sooners' Sugar Bowl history|date=December 27, 2013|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> However, the game is best known for the \"spy incident\", where former [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]] player [[Piggy Barnes]] was caught spying on the Sooners' practices.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5J6V5K_O4cEC&pg=PA39&lpg=PA39&dq=1950+sugar+bowl+spy+incident&source=web&ots=BW5BBhqBkx&sig=uUq8nkTBYZp_mJBsEmn29DFRXz0&hl=en |title=Bud Wilkinson: An Intimate Portrait of an American Legend \u2013 Jay Wilkinson, Gretchen S. Hirsch \u2013 Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |accessdate=April 22, 2013}}</ref> Despite going undefeated and winning their bowl game, the Sooners were denied a national championship, which was awarded to the [[1949 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|Notre Dame Fighting Irish]], though they did not play in a bowl game.<ref name=\"appollarchive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.appollarchive.com/football/ap/seasons.cfm?SeasonID=1949 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080925092936/http://www.appollarchive.com/football/ap/seasons.cfm?seasonid=1949 |archive-date=September 25, 2008 |url-status=dead |title=Welcome to www.appollarchive.com! |accessdate=May 7, 2014 }}</ref> The following year, Wilkinson went on to guide the Sooners to their first national championship, though they lost in the Sugar Bowl to [[Bear Bryant]]'s [[1950 Kentucky Wildcats football team|Kentucky]] team.<ref name=\"espn.go.com\"/> That loss was the Sooners' first loss since a season opener loss to [[Santa Clara Broncos football|Santa Clara]] in [[1948 Oklahoma Sooners football team|1948]], 31&nbsp;games earlier.<ref name=\"espn.go.com\"/> It was in 1951, while seeking funding to improve the university, that OU president [[George Lynn Cross]] said to the Oklahoma legislature that he \"would like to build a university of which the football team would be proud.\"<ref>{{cite book | last=Dozier | first=Ray | title=The Oklahoma Football Encyclopedia | page=83 | year=2006 | publisher=Sports Publishing, LLC | location=Champaign, Illinois | isbn=1-58261-699-X }}</ref>\n\nIn [[1952 Oklahoma Sooners football team|1952]], Oklahoma had its first [[Heisman Trophy]] winner in [[Running back|halfback]] [[Billy Vessels]], a local player from [[Cleveland, Oklahoma]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://heisman.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=18|title=Heisman Trophy|website=heisman.com}}</ref> In [[1953 Oklahoma Sooners football team|1953]], the Sooners opened with a loss to [[1953 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|Notre Dame]]<ref name=\"newsok.com1\">{{cite web|url=http://newsok.com/article/3885801|title=Examining the complete history of the OU-Notre Dame series|date=September 23, 2013|publisher=}}</ref> and tied [[1953 Pittsburgh Panthers football team|Pittsburgh]] the next week.<ref name=\"newsok.com1\"/> The Sooners would not lose or tie another game until losing to [[1957 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|Notre Dame]] in November 1957, a streak of more than three years.<ref name=\"espn.go.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/m-footbl-winning-streak.html |title=OU football tradition \u2013 47 game winning streak |publisher=OU |accessdate=June 27, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100627071300/http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/m-footbl-winning-streak.html |archivedate=June 27, 2010 }}</ref> This record of 47 consecutive wins has never been seriously threatened.<ref name=\"espn.go.com\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> During this streak, the Sooners won the national championship in [[1955 Oklahoma Sooners football team|1955]] and [[1956 Oklahoma Sooners football team|'56]].<ref name=\"espn.go.com\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> Additionally, the Sooners won 14 straight conference titles from 1946 to 1959, one under [[Jim Tatum]] and 13 under Wilkinson.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soonersports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=208806137|title=Conference Titles|publisher=}}</ref> The Sooners also went undefeated in conference play from November 23, 1946 to October 31, 1959; their record was only blemished by two ties.<ref name=\"espn.go.com\"/>\n\nWilkinson's best teams came during the first eleven years of his tenure. In that time, he recorded winning streaks of 31 and 47&nbsp;games and went 114\u201310\u20133, a winning percentage of 90.9%.<ref name=\"espn.go.com\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> Wilkinson left Oklahoma after the [[1963 Oklahoma Sooners football team|1963 season]] with a record of 145\u201329\u20134, 14 conference titles and 123 straight games without being shut out.<ref name=\"espn.go.com\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> During Wilkinson's tenure, another first would be recorded. [[Prentice Gautt]] would become the first black football player at the University of Oklahoma.<ref name=\"espn.go.com\"/> Gautt had been a superior student at his [[Oklahoma City]] high school.<ref name=\"espn.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/classic/s/Prentice_Gautt.html|title=ESPN Classic \u2013 Gautt was first African-American to play at OU|website=www.espn.com}}</ref> He was a member of the [[National Honor Society]] and president of his senior class.<ref name=\"espn.com\"/> During his junior and senior years of high school, he helped his team amass a 31-game win streak.<ref name=\"espn.com\"/> He was also the first black player to participate in the Oklahoma state all-star game.<ref name=\"footballmatters.org\">{{cite web|url=http://footballmatters.org/celebrating-college-footballs-racial-pioneers-prentice-gautt/|title=Celebrating College Football's Racial Pioneers: Prentice Gautt \u2013 Football Matters|date=February 11, 2016|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"Gautt\">{{cite news | first=Carol | last=Burr | pages=10\u201315 | title=Prentice Gautt: A Sooner's Story | date=Spring 1987 | url=http://digital.libraries.ou.edu/sooner/articles/p10-15_1987v7n2_OCR.pdf | publisher=Sooner Magazine |format=PDF}}</ref> Because of Gautt's academic success in high school, he was supported financially by a group of local black doctors and pharmacists.<ref name=\"footballmatters.org\"/><ref name=\"espn.com\"/> A couple months into his freshman year, Gautt was placed on athletic scholarship and the money was returned to the investors.<ref name=\"espn.com\"/> Unfortunately, some members of Gautt's team were not too happy to play with him.<ref name=\"footballmatters.org\"/> One player even left Oklahoma because he refused to play with an African American.<ref name=\"Gautt\"/> However, most of the team had his support. After a freshman game in [[Tulsa]], Gautt was refused service in the restaurant where the team was scheduled to eat.<ref name=\"footballmatters.org\"/> His teammates abruptly left and found an eating establishment that would also serve him.<ref name=\"Gautt\"/> As a player, Gautt broke out in 1958. In 1959, he was named the [[1959 Orange Bowl|Orange Bowl]] [[Most valuable player|MVP]]. He was inducted into the [[College Football Hall of Fame]] in 1985.<ref name=\"go\">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=2053792|title=College Hall of Fame to honor running back \u2013 College Football \u2013 ESPN|publisher=sports.espn.go.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Jones, MacKenzie, Fairbanks and the Wishbone (1964\u20131972)===\n[[File:Gomer Jones Nov 1929.jpg|150 px|thumb|Coach Gomer Jones]]\nWilkinson's assistant coach, [[Gomer Jones]], took over as head coach in [[1964 Oklahoma Sooners football team|1964]], a move Wilkinson engineered himself.<ref name=\"google5\">{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=888&dat=19640117&id=-NY0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=_XwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7026,3697035|work=St. Petersburg Times|title=Gomer Jones Only Known OU Candidate|via=Google News Archive Search|publisher=news.google.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014|date=January 17, 1964}}</ref> His first year would prove to be a sharp contrast from Wilkinson's early years as the Sooners went 6\u20134\u20131.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://soonerstats.com/football/seasons/schedule.cfm?SeasonID=1964 | title=1964 Football Season | publisher=SoonerStats.com  | accessdate=August 4, 2006 }}</ref> They started the season 1\u20133 with three consecutive losses to [[1964 USC Trojans football team|Southern California]], [[1964 Texas Longhorns football team|Texas]] and [[1964 Kansas Jayhawks football team|Kansas]]. The final loss came in the [[1965 Gator Bowl (January)|Gator Bowl]] to [[1964 Florida State Seminoles football team|Florida State]].<ref name=\"soonerstats\">{{cite web|url=http://www.soonerstats.com/football/games/recap.cfm?GameID=616#.UyZu9myPLIU|title=1964 Oklahoma vs. Florida State Game Recap \u2013 SoonerStats.com \u2013 Oklahoma Sooners Football, Basketball, Baseball, and Softball Scores, Records, and Stats|publisher=soonerstats.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> Prior to the game, it was found that four of Oklahoma's starters had signed professional football contracts before their college eligibility had expired. Those four were dismissed from the team prior to the bowl game,<ref>{{cite news | first=Ned | last=Hockman | title=Bowled over by a mouthful | publisher=Sooner Magazine | url=http://digital.libraries.ou.edu/sooner/articles/p22-25_1965v37n3_OCR.pdf | date=January 1965 | accessdate=August 4, 2006 | pages=22\u201325 |format=PDF}}</ref> ultimately causing Oklahoma to lose the game 36\u201319. The next season's team fared no better, going 3\u20137, Oklahoma's worst record, percentage wise, since it went 0\u20131 its inaugural season in 1895. This brought the Jones era to a quick close, although he did remain at Oklahoma as the [[athletic director]], a role he also held while he was head coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsok.com/article/5562699/gomer-jones-was-an-ohio-state-football-star|title=Gomer Jones was an Ohio State Football Star|publisher=The Oklahoman|last=Trammel|first=Berry|date=September 4, 2017|accessdate=October 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFollowing Jones's 9\u201311\u20131 record, Oklahoma brought in a young assistant coach from [[Arkansas Razorbacks football|Arkansas]] named [[Jim Mackenzie (American football)|Jim Mackenzie]].<ref name=\"cnn\">{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1080551/index.htm|title=That is Middle Guard Granville Liggins' colorful \u2013 11.13.67 \u2013 SI Vault|publisher=sportsillustrated.cnn.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> He wanted discipline for his players, so he set a curfew and required them to enroll in [[physical education]] class.<ref>{{cite news | first=Larry | last=McDade | title=Mackenzie Begins | publisher=Sooner Magazine | url=http://digital.libraries.ou.edu/sooner/articles/p4-7_1966v38n3_OCR.pdf | date=March 1966 | accessdate=August 4, 2006 | pages=4\u20137 |format=PDF}}</ref> His first season was an improvement from the previous. The [[1966 Oklahoma Sooners football team|1966 team]] went 6\u20134<ref name=\"sports-reference6\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/jim-mackenzie-1.html|title=Jim MacKenzie Coaching Record &#124; College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=sports-reference.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> with a win in the [[Red River Shootout]] over rival [[1966 Texas Longhorns football team|Texas]] coached by former Oklahoma [[defensive back]] [[Darrell Royal]], their first win over Texas since 1957. They also beat the number four team in the nation, rival [[1966 Nebraska Cornhuskers football team|Nebraska]], by a score of 10\u20139.\n\nThe 1966 season showed promise for the young coach, but, on April 28, 1967, at the age of 37, Mackenzie died of a [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]].<ref name=\"google7\">{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1876&dat=19670427&id=AEEsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Ms0EAAAAIBAJ&pg=6952,5086456|title=Sooner Coach, Jim McKenzie Dies of Heart Attack|work=Herald-Journal|via=Google News Archive Search|publisher=news.google.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014|date=April 27, 1967}}</ref>\n\nAfter the 1964 season, [[Chuck Fairbanks]], an assistant coach at [[Houston Cougars football|Houston]], was offered a job at [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]]. He wanted to accept, but it was the middle of the summer and unusually late for a coaching move, so he decided to stay loyal to Houston and remained there. After the next season, he was offered a position as an assistant on Mackenzie's staff at Oklahoma, a position he felt was a better job than the Tennessee position.<ref name=\"Destiny\">{{cite news | first=Bill | last=Connors | title=Destiny and Charles Fairbanks | publisher=Sooner Magazine | url=http://digital.libraries.ou.edu/sooner/articles/p4-7_1967v40n1_OCR.pdf | date=September 1967 | accessdate=August 4, 2006 | pages=4\u20137 |format=PDF}}</ref> Immediately after the 1965 season, Fairbanks was offered a job at [[Missouri Tigers football|Missouri]] with the promise that he would be the head coach within four years.<ref name=\"Destiny\"/> He declined and stayed at Oklahoma. Four months later, Coach Mackenzie died and Fairbanks was named head coach. It did not take long for Fairbanks to turn the team around. In his first season in 1967, his squad went 10\u20131.<ref name=\"sports-reference7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/chuck-fairbanks-1.html|title=Chuck Fairbanks Coaching Record &#124; College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=sports-reference.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> They entered their sixth game with a 5\u20131 record (their only loss was a two-point loss to rival [[1967 Texas Longhorns football team|Texas]]) and unranked<ref name=\"APNote\">All rankings post 1950 are based on the [[AP Poll]].</ref> and beat ninth ranked Colorado, 23\u20130. This propelled Fairbanks's team to a number eight ranking. They continued their romp through the season and beat #2 Tennessee 26\u201324 in the [[1968 Orange Bowl|Orange Bowl]].<ref name=\"sports-reference7\"/> They finished the season ranked number three in the country.\n\nFairbanks lost four games in each of the next three seasons. Despite the relatively mediocre record of those years, several great players came through Fairbanks's program. One of those players was [[Steve Owens (football)|Steve Owens]]. After an impressive year in 1969, despite Oklahoma's 6\u20134 record, Owens was named the Sooners' second Heisman Trophy winner. It did not take long for Fairbanks to return the team to form. He and his offensive co-ordinator [[Barry Switzer]] helped implement the use of the [[Wishbone formation|wishbone offense]]. Fairbanks' 1970 team tied Bear Bryant's [[1970 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama Crimson Tide]] in the [[1969 Bluebonnet Bowl|Bluebonnet Bowl]] to finish the season ranked #20. They began the 1971 season ranked number ten. In consecutive weeks, they beat #17 [[1971 USC Trojans football team|USC]], #3 Texas and #6 Colorado. These early-season wins propelled them to a #2 national ranking and set the stage for one of the great college football games of the century against top-ranked Nebraska.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://espn.go.com/classic/s/beano_oklaneb.html | title=The greatest game ever played | first=Beano | last=Cook | publisher=ESPN.com | accessdate=September 10, 2007 }}</ref> Led by quarterback [[Jack Mildren]] and running back [[Greg Pruitt]], Oklahoma was a scoring machine, averaging 44.5&nbsp;points per game, the second highest in team history.<ref name=\"PointsStats\">{{cite web | title=Season Points Scored Records | publisher=SoonerStats.com | url=http://soonerstats.com/football/recordbook/team/off_pts_season.cfm  | accessdate=August 4, 2006 }}</ref> The offense set the all-time NCAA single-season rushing record at 472.4 yards per game, a record which still stands to this day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalchamps.net/NCAA/database/index.htm|title=All-Time Database|website=www.nationalchamps.net|accessdate=August 24, 2017}}</ref> Equally impressive that season was Pruitt's nine yards per carry, and Mildren is often referred to as \"the Godfather of the wishbone\" by University of Oklahoma football fans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crimsonandcreammachine.com/2008/5/22/534631/sooner-legend-jack-mildren|title=Sooner Legend Jack Mildren Passes Away|publisher=|accessdate=August 24, 2017}}</ref> On November 25, 1971, Nebraska edged Oklahoma, 35\u201331 in the [[1971 Nebraska vs. Oklahoma football game|Game of the Century]] what was to be the only loss of the season for Oklahoma. Oklahoma went on to beat Oklahoma State and fifth ranked [[1971 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]] to finish the season ranked number two. Fairbanks closed out his career at Oklahoma the following year with a win in the [[1972 Sugar Bowl (December)|Sugar Bowl]] over [[1972 Penn State Nittany Lions football team|Penn State]] after having lost once all season, to Colorado.<ref name=\"sports-reference7\"/> Following this season, Fairbanks accepted a position with the [[National Football League|NFL]]'s [[New England Patriots]].<ref name=\"patriots\">{{cite web|url=http://archive.patriots.com/team/index.cfm?ac=playerbio&bio=1030|title=The New England Patriots|publisher=archive.patriots.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Barry Switzer era (1973\u20131988)===\n[[File:Barry Switzer.jpg|thumb|Coach Switzer]]\nSoon after [[Barry Switzer]], who previously served as Oklahoma's offensive coordinator, took the reins of the program, Oklahoma forfeited eight games from the 1972 season due to violations involving the alteration of transcripts.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news|title= OKLAHOMA AGREES TO FORFEIT GAMES Gives Up Eight Victories in Football in Case Involving Player's Altered Record|first= Gordon S., Jr.|last=White|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1973/04/19/99142486.html?pageNumber=57|work=New York Times|date= 19 April 1973|location=New York|accessdate=2019-12-08}}</ref><ref name=\"Gems\">{{cite book|page=74|url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/_/TWm9DwAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&bsq=forfeit|title=Touchdown: An American Obsession|first1=Gerald R.|last1=Gems|first2=Gertrud|last2=Pfister|publisher=Berkshire Publishing Group|year=2017|isbn=9781614728238|accessdate=2019-12-08}}</ref> Fairbanks denied any knowledge of this. As a punishment, the Sooners could not play in a bowl game for two years. This setback did not stop Switzer's Sooners. His 1973 team finished 10\u20130\u20131 with only a tie to the number one ranked USC team.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://soonerstats.com/football/seasons/schedule.cfm?SeasonID=1973 | title=1973 Football Season | publisher=SoonerStats.com  | accessdate=August 4, 2006 }}</ref> They finished the season ranked #3 after beating six teams who spent time in the top 20. The next year, Switzer's Sooners finished 11\u20130 and won the national championship. This was the Sooners' first undefeated season and national championship since 1956. That team was another high-scoring team averaging 43&nbsp;points per game.<ref name=\"PointsStats\"/> They were led by [[Steve Davis (quarterback)|Steve Davis]] at quarterback, [[Joe Washington]] at running back and the Selmon brothers ([[Lee Roy Selmon|Lee Roy]], [[Lucious Selmon|Lucious]], and [[Dewey Selmon|Dewey]]) on defense.\n\nSwitzer's teams in the 1970s went a combined 73\u20137\u20132 in seven years.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://soonerstats.com/football/seasons/index.cfm?decade=1970 | title=Football Seasons \u2013 1970s | publisher=SoonerStats.com  | accessdate=August 7, 2006 }}</ref> In [[1978 Oklahoma Sooners football team|1978]], Oklahoma would get their third Heisman Trophy winner in running back [[Billy Sims]]. That year, he set the Oklahoma record for most rushing yards in a season with 1,896, a record that would stand for 26&nbsp;years. His 1978 season currently ranks third in team history in yards per attempt with 7.41, behind fellow Sooners [[Greg Pruitt]] and [[Marcus Dupree]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://soonerstats.com/football/recordbook/player/rush_season.cfm | title=Season Rushing Records | publisher=SoonerStats.com  | accessdate=August 7, 2006 }}</ref> Sims also held the record at Oklahoma for most rushing yards in a career with 4,118 until it was broken by [[Samaje Perine]] in 2017.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://soonerstats.com/football/recordbook/player/rush_career.cfm | title=Career Rushing Records | publisher=SoonerStats.com  | accessdate=August 7, 2006 }}</ref> He finished second in the Heisman race the following year, 1979.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heisman.com/handbook/winning-margin.html |title=The Winning Margin: Year By Year |publisher=Heisman.com |accessdate=August 8, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061208003238/http://www.heisman.com/handbook/winning-margin.html |archivedate=December 8, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nThe early 1980s saw the Sooners begin to slip under Switzer. They lost four games each in [[1981 Oklahoma Sooners football team|1981]], [[1982 Oklahoma Sooners football team|1982]], and [[1983 Oklahoma Sooners football team|1983]]. It was the first time they lost four games in a season since 1970 under Coach Fairbanks. However, eight of those twelve losses came to the likes of [[USC Trojans football|USC]], [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas]], [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|Nebraska]] and [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]]. They began to turn things around in [[1984 Oklahoma Sooners football team|1984]] when they went 9\u20132\u20131 and finished the season at #6. The 1984 team featured [[Buster Rhymes]] at wide receiver, [[Spencer Tillman]] at running back and [[Tony Casillas]] at defensive tackle. Over the next three years, the team continued to grow and went 11\u20131 each year (with all three losses coming to [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami]]), including a national championship in [[1985 Oklahoma Sooners football team|1985]] (they finished ranked number three in 1986 and 1987).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://soonerstats.com/football/seasons/index.cfm?decade=1980 | title=Football Seasons \u2013 1980s | publisher=SoonerStats.com  | accessdate=August 7, 2006 }}</ref> Many great Sooner athletes came through the program during these years, including two-time [[Butkus Award]] winner [[Brian Bosworth]], tight end [[Keith Jackson (tight end)|Keith Jackson]] and quarterback [[Jamelle Holieway]]. While Switzer was not able to match Wilkinson's unimaginable string of 13&nbsp;consecutive conference championships, he was able to rack up 12 of his own during his career at Oklahoma.\n\nSuddenly, in 1988, it all came crashing down for Switzer. His team was placed on probation by the NCAA for violating several rules. In a six-month time frame, there was a shooting and a rape in the athletic dorm on Oklahoma's campus.<ref name = clay>{{Cite web|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1992-02-02/sports/sp-2041_1_nigel-clay |title=Invincible No More: Nigel Clay Planned to be in the NFL, but Now is Playing in a Correctional Center.|date=February 2, 1992| publisher=latimes.com |accessdate=January 19, 2013}}</ref> Switzer's house was robbed with the help of one of his athletes, and an athlete was caught attempting to sell drugs to an undercover agent.<ref>{{cite book | title=Bootlegger's Boy | last=Switzer | first=Barry | authorlink=Barry Switzer |author2=Bud Shrake |date=August 1990 | publisher=William Morrow & Co | isbn=0-688-09384-1 }}</ref> The three-year probation included a two-year ban on TV and bowl appearances and a reduction in scholarships from 25 to 18.<ref name=\"Dorsey\">{{cite news|title=Wanting your children to grow up to be \u2026 Sooners |first=Stan |last=Dorsey |date=August 19, 1996 |publisher=The Sporting News |url=http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1208/is_n34_v220/ai_18596119 |accessdate=August 7, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080101113744/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1208/is_n34_v220/ai_18596119 |archivedate=January 1, 2008 }}</ref> Nonetheless, the 1988 team established the NCAA Division I single-game record of 768&nbsp;yards rushing against [[1988 Kansas State Wildcats football team|Kansas State]] on October 15, 1988, a record that stands to this day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web1.ncaa.org/web_files/stats/football_records/DI/2009/2009FBS.pdf|title=2009 Division I Football Records Book: Football Bowl Subdivision (FBS) Records|accessdate=July 9, 2010|publisher=[[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]|page=24}}</ref> After the season, Switzer resigned as head coach.<ref name=\"articles.philly.com\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.philly.com/1989-06-21/sports/26105686_1_gary-gibbs-sooners-david-swank|title=Sooners Promote Gibbs To Head-coaching Job \u2013 Philly.com|publisher=articles.philly.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Gibbs, Schnellenberger and Blake (1989\u20131998)===\nSwitzer was succeeded by his longtime defensive coordinator, [[Gary Gibbs]].<ref name=\"articles.philly.com\"/> Gibbs appeared to be a solid choice, having spent the first two decades of his adult life at OU as a player and assistant coach. He largely succeeded in his primary task\u2014cleaning up the program's image. However, even though his rosters were smaller than normal due to the scholarship reductions, Gibbs found it hard to please boosters and administrators with an 8\u20133&nbsp;year.\n\nGibbs' squads struggled to build success off two moderately successful seasons, 1991 and 1993. In 1991, OU went 9\u20133, finished the season ranked No. 16 in the nation by the Associated Press, and soundly defeated [[1991 Virginia Cavaliers football team|Virginia]] in the [[1991 Gator Bowl (December)|Gator Bowl]]. In the 1992 follow-up campaign, however, OU finished 5\u20134\u20132, unranked and did not earn an invitation to a post-season bowl. Further, OU dropped games to rivals Nebraska and Texas and tied Oklahoma State. The draw with the Cowboys marked the first time since 1976 OU did not beat OSU in the annual Bedlam game. Gibbs' Sooners rebounded with a 9\u20133 record, a No. 17 finish in the final Associated Press poll and a Sun Bowl victory in 1993. En route, OU beat then-fifth-ranked Texas A&M, 44\u201314, and recorded its only victory against Texas under Gibbs. In 1994 season the Sooners finished 6\u20136. Gibbs announced his resignation prior to OU's losses to Nebraska in the regular-season finale and Brigham Young University in the Copper Bowl.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/11/25/sports/football-wounded-but-standing-gibbs-exits-oklahoma.html|title=Wounded but Standing, Gibbs Exits Oklahoma|author=|date=November 25, 1994|work=The New York Times|access-date=September 26, 2016}}</ref> Ultimately, it was his record against Oklahoma's major rivals that did him in. Gibbs went 2\u201315\u20131 against Texas, Nebraska and Colorado. In addition to his record, he was thought to be uncomfortable around alumni and the media, and with being a head coach in general.<ref name=\"Dorsey\"/> Gibbs' final record as head coach at OU was 44\u201323\u20132.<ref name=\"sports-reference8\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/gary-gibbs-1.html|title=Gary Gibbs Coaching Record &#124; College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=sports-reference.com|access-date=May 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nTo replace Gibbs, Oklahoma looked towards the seasoned [[Howard Schnellenberger]], then 61&nbsp;years old.<ref name=\"orlandosentinel\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1994-12-17/sports/9412170594_1_coach-howard-schnellenberger-head-coach-oklahoma|title=Oklahoma Hires Schnellenberger \u2013 Orlando Sentinel|publisher=articles.orlandosentinel.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> Schnellenberger had a well-established reputation for turning teams around. He had built [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami]] from an also-ran to a national champion in 1983, and turned around a once-moribund [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]] program. In the end, he was almost too sure of himself. He was quoted as saying, \"They will write books and make movies about my time here.\"<ref name=\"Dorsey\"/><ref name=\"articles.sun-sentinel.com\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2000-12-31/sports/0012300389_1_college-football-oklahoma-first-football-coach|title=Howard Schnellenberger Came To Oklahoma With Big Dreams And A Reputation To Back It Up. He Left As The Most Hated Man In The State. \u2013 Sun Sentinel|publisher=articles.sun-sentinel.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> His 1995 team started out well, reaching the top 10 after a 3\u20130 start. However, an embarrassing loss to [[1995 Colorado Buffaloes football team|Colorado]] on national television started a downward spiral. The Sooners ultimately finished 5\u20135\u20131,<ref name=\"sports-reference9\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/s-index.html|title=Coaches with Last Names Starting with S &#124; College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=sports-reference.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> including only their second losing conference record since World War II. Schnellenberger resigned a month after the season ended.<ref name=\"articles.sun-sentinel.com\"/> To this day, Schnellenberger is not held in high esteem by Sooner fans, in part because he made no secret of his lack of interest in the program's history.<ref name=\"articles.sun-sentinel.com\"/> For instance, he vowed to make \"Sooner Nation\" forget about Wilkinson and Switzer\u2014a boast considered to be almost heretical by the fan base. He ordered numerous old files to be thrown out; instead, they were archived without his knowledge.<ref name=\"Dorsey\"/>\n\nFor the 1996 season, Oklahoma hired former player [[John Blake (American football)|John Blake]] as head coach. Blake was the favorite to succeed Schnellenberger and was backed by Barry Switzer, Steve Owens, and former Oklahoma president [[George Lynn Cross]].<ref name=\"Dorsey\"/> However, many were skeptical of the decision. His coaching experience was very limited, especially compared to Schnellenberger. In his seven-year coaching career (four years at OU, three years with the [[Dallas Cowboys]] and one year at [[Tulsa Golden Hurricane football|Tulsa]]), he had never been more than a position coach. The skeptics were proven right. In Blake's first season, he went 3\u20138.<ref name=\"sports-reference10\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/john-blake-1.html|title=John Blake Coaching Record &#124; College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=sports-reference.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> It was the worst record, percentage wise, Oklahoma had experienced since 1895. The eight losses. which were repeated in 1997, were also the most Oklahoma had ever suffered in a season. In his three years at Oklahoma, Blake went 3\u20138, 4\u20138, and 5\u20136 for a final record of 12\u201322.<ref name=\"sports-reference10\"/> It was the first time since 1922\u20131924 that Oklahoma had three consecutive losing seasons. However, Blake's lasting contribution proved to be his recruiting. He recruited several players that would help lead the program's resurgence, including [[J.T. Thatcher]], [[Josh Norman (tight end)|Josh Norman]], [[Roy Williams (safety)|Roy Williams]] and [[Rocky Calmus]]. Many of them got a chance to play fairly quickly, since Blake's teams were often out of games early. Blake was fired after the 1998 season.<ref name=\"chicagotribune\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-11-23/sports/9811230128_1_grey-cup-canadian-football-league-championship-pro-football|title=Blake Fired As Oklahoma Football Coach \u2013 Chicago Tribune|publisher=articles.chicagotribune.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Bob Stoops era (1999\u20132016)===\n{{Very long section|date=April 2018}}\n\n====1999\u20132002: Return to glory====\n[[File:Bob Stoops Oklahoma Coach.jpg|thumb|Coach Stoops]]\nThe university looked at many candidates to replace Blake. Many big-time college coaches were considered for the post. However, Oklahoma athletic director [[Joe Castiglione (athletic director)|Joe Castiglione]] decided to hire a 38-year-old defensive coordinator from [[Florida Gators football|Florida]], [[Bob Stoops]].<ref name=\"tulsaworld\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/sportsextra/ou/oklahoma-hit-a-homer-in-hiring-bob-stoops/article_0cf84a52-22d6-5d83-b379-da467ae0a996.html|title=Oklahoma hit a homer in hiring Bob Stoops \u2013 Tulsa World: OU Sports|publisher=tulsaworld.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> Stoops quickly began to build his new program with the promise to help the program regain its former position as a perennial college football powerhouse. On his arrival to campus he would find that for all his predecessor's failings as a head football coach, John Blake had been an excellent recruiter and many of his players were potential stars.{{cite news|url=https://www.tulsaworld.com/archives/stoops-ou-title-wasn-t-inherited/article_8e0521fb-0206-5800-8112-56a3a8b015b4.html|title=Stooop's OU title wasn't inherited|publisher=Tulsa World|last=Kerr|first=Kelly|date=July 29, 2001|accessdate=January 30, 2019}} Despite the obvious talent already on-campus, no quarterback suitable for the \"spread\" offense was on the team roster. Stoops would remedy this by signing a little-known junior college quarterback, [[Josh Heupel]], to run his offense. In his first year as head coach, the Sooners showed marked improvement; starting the season with three wins over non-conference opponents amassing 132&nbsp;points to their opponents' 31. They lost the next two games, which included a 34\u201330 loss against Notre Dame at [[South Bend, Indiana|South Bend]] and finished the season with an overall record of 7\u20135.<ref name=\"sports-reference11\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/bob-stoops-1.html|title=Bob Stoops Coaching Record &#124; College Football at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=sports-reference.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> After the season, offensive coordinator [[Mike Leach (American football coach)|Mike Leach]] left OU to take the head coaching position at [[Texas Tech Red Raiders football|Texas Tech]].<ref name=\"google8\">{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1696&dat=19991210&id=l_caAAAAIBAJ&sjid=60cEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6799,1593919|title=Texas Tech Hires New Coach|work=Daily News|via=Google News Archive Search|publisher=news.google.com|date=December 10, 1999|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> This success was a breath of fresh air for a program that had fallen from perennial powerhouse to league doormat and those surrounding the Sooner football program expected great things from their new head coach. They would not be disappointed.\n\nIn 2000, the Sooners opened the season with a new offensive coordinator, [[Mark Mangino]], and ranked number 19,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://soonerstats.com/football/seasons/schedule.cfm?SeasonID=2000 | title=2000 Football Season | publisher=SoonerStats.com  | accessdate=August 7, 2006 }}</ref> the first time they opened the season ranked in five years. The Sooners opened 4\u20130, dominating their early season opponents by a combined score of 176\u201351. The annual Red River Shootout against arch-rival [[2000 Texas Longhorns football team|Texas]] would prove to be the first signature victory of the Bob Stoops era. The Sooners dominated the Longhorns by a score of 63\u201314 in what was then the most lopsided upset in the history of the rivalry. Oklahoma running back [[Quentin Griffin]] smashed the Oklahoma record for most touchdowns in a game with six scores. The Sooners were now officially back in the hunt for a national title. In the following weeks the team narrowly beat the number two ranked [[2000 Kansas State Wildcats football team|Kansas State]] 41\u201331 in Manhattan and the following week went on to beat number one ranked [[2000 Nebraska Cornhuskers football team|Nebraska]]  31\u201314. [[ESPN]]'s [[Brent Musburger]] said that, \"The Sooners' October run of burying Texas, Kansas State and Nebraska is one of the greatest 30-day stretches in college football history.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://static.espn.go.com/abcsports/bcs/columns/musburger_brent/2000/1212/940169.html | title=A remarkable season | publisher=BCSFootball.com  | accessdate=August 7, 2006 }}</ref> The Sooners narrowly escaped a loss at the hands of [[2000 Texas A&M Aggies football team|Texas A&M]] in College Station but they pulled out a victory, winning 35\u201331 on an interception return for a touchdown by linebacker [[Torrance Marshall]]. The team defeated the Kansas State Wildcats for the second time that season in the Big 12 Championship, a victory which propelled the program to its first national title berth since 1985. The Sooners finished the season with a stunning 13\u20132 win over a heavily favored [[2000 Florida State Seminoles football team|Florida State]] team in the [[2001 Orange Bowl|Orange Bowl]] and claimed the [[AFCA National Championship Trophy|Sears Trophy]].<ref name=\"sports-reference11\"/> At the end of the season, quarterback Josh Heupel had the top two spots on the list of Oklahoma's season passing records. The championship was the Sooners' 7th national title and their first since Barry Switzer's departure. The team had finally regained its status as a power in the college football world. The stoic coach from Ohio had resurrected a football giant, bringing the once great program back to the pinnacle of college athletics. The Sooners and their fans were hungry for more success and Coach Stoops would deliver. After the 2001 season, Mark Mangino stepped down as OU offensive coordinator to accept the head football coach position at [[Kansas Jayhawks football|Kansas]].<ref name=\"cnn2\">{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/college/news/2001/12/04/kansas_mangino_ap/|title=CNNSI.com \u2013 College Football \u2013 Kansas hires Sooners' Mangino as head coach \u2013 Wednesday December 05, 2001 12:58 AM|publisher=sportsillustrated.cnn.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> OU promoted [[Chuck Long]] from quarterbacks coach to offensive coordinator for the 2002 season. The Sooners had continued success in the 2002 season, going to the 2003 Rose Bowl after a season which saw the 2nd loss in so many years to Oklahoma State, and an upset loss to Texas A&M 30\u201326.\n\n====Back to back BCS championship appearances (2003\u20132004)====\n[[File:Jwhite.JPG|thumb|right|Jason White]]\nThe team's national success reemerged in the 2003 and 2004 seasons. The 2003 team was the highest scoring squad (at the time) in Oklahoma's storied history, scoring 601&nbsp;points to their opponents 214. The season included seven games of 50&nbsp;points or more with the highlights including a 77\u20130 drubbing of Texas A&M and a 65\u201313 defeat of Texas. The team, led by Heisman Trophy winner [[Jason White (American football)|Jason White]], was billed as one of \"the greatest college football teams of all time.\"  This assumption was short-lived as the Sooners were upset in the [[Big 12 Football Championship Game|Big 12 Championship Game]] by [[2003 Kansas State Wildcats football team|Kansas State]]. Prior to the Big 12 Title Game, the Sooners Defensive Coordinator, [[Mike Stoops]], accepted the head coaching position at [[Arizona Wildcats football|Arizona]], becoming the third Sooners coordinator to take a head coaching job during the Stoops era.<ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite web|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2003/nov/30/sports/sp-stoops30|title=Arizona Hires Mike Stoops \u2013 Los Angeles Times|publisher=articles.latimes.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref>  Due to their impressive strength of schedule, the Sooners were able to retain their position in the polls and their chance for the title. In a warm night in New Orleans, the Sooners were handed their second consecutive defeat and their first title loss; this time to [[2003 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]] squad by a score of 21\u201314. The heartbreaking defeats shocked the \"Sooner Nation\" while conversely establishing the team as a perennial title contender. In 2004, the Sooners were able to reach the [[2005 Orange Bowl|Orange Bowl]] undefeated, along with [[2004 USC Trojans football team|USC]]. Although the Sooners lost in the title game 55\u201319, USC later vacated the win due to NCAA infractions.\n\n====Adrian Peterson (2005\u20132006)====\n[[file:AdrianPeterson.jpg|thumb|left|Adrian Peterson]]\nIn 2005, Stoops finished the season with an 8\u20134 record, his worst season record since his inaugural season.<ref name=\"sports-reference11\"/> Jason White's backup, [[Paul Thompson (football)|Paul Thompson]], was named starting quarterback at the beginning of the season, but was replaced by redshirt freshman [[Rhett Bomar]] after a season-opening loss to [[2005 TCU Horned Frogs football team|TCU]]. Paul Thompson was moved to the wide receiver slot for the rest of the season. They started the season 2\u20133 with additional losses at [[2005 UCLA Bruins football team|UCLA]] and against eventual national champion Texas. The team started to improve as the season progressed, especially the young Bomar. The next loss came against [[2005 Texas Tech Red Raiders football team|Texas Tech]], coached by former OU offensive coordinator [[Mike Leach (American football coach)|Mike Leach]], and was a controversial loss. Texas Tech's [[Taurean Henderson]] scored on the final play of the game. The play was reviewed by replay officials, but video replays were deemed inconclusive.<ref>{{cite web | title=Tech scores on 2-yard TD as time expires, avoids upset | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=253232641 | publisher=ESPN.com  | date=November 19, 2005 | accessdate=December 4, 2006 }}</ref> The touchdown gave the Red Raiders the win, 23\u201321. It was a setback for the Sooners but they moved on and were able to soundly defeat their instate rival Oklahoma State in Norman by a final score of 42\u201314. The Sooners finished third in the Big 12 South behind [[2005 Texas Longhorns football team|Texas]] (who went on to win the 2005 BCS National Championship) and the Texas Tech Red Raiders (Oklahoma and Texas Tech both had conference records of 6\u20132, but Texas Tech won the heads up match and thus was placed over Oklahoma). The unranked Sooners would represent the Big 12 in the [[2005 Holiday Bowl|Holiday Bowl]] and they would play the sixth-ranked [[2005 Oregon Ducks football team|Oregon]]. Oklahoma went on to beat the Ducks, 17\u201314; Bomar was named the Bowl MVP and the Sooners finished the season ranked #22.<ref name=\"APNote\" /> On July 11, 2007, the NCAA announced that the Sooners would have to vacate all victories from the 2005 season, including the bowl game, due to NCAA violations related to three former players, including Bomar, thereby giving the Sooners an official 2005&nbsp;record of 0\u20134.<ref>{{cite web | title=OU must vacate '05 victories. However, Oklahoma will still recognize those eight victories including the Holiday Bowl victory. Bob Stoops' record still stands at 86\u201318. | url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/dn/latestnews/stories/071207dnspooulede.c8ab5b.html | publisher=The [[Dallas Morning News]] | date=July 11, 2007 | accessdate=July 11, 2007}}</ref>  However, on February 22, 2008, the NCAA reversed the decision and reinstated the vacated wins.<ref>{{cite news | title= NCAA gives OU back its wins for 2005 season | publisher=The Oklahoman | date= February 22, 2008 | accessdate=February 22, 2008 | url=http://newsok.com/article/3207494/1203698887}}</ref> Following the season, Sooners offensive coordinator Chuck Long left to become the head coach at [[San Diego State Aztecs football|San Diego State]], becoming the third Stoops offensive coordinator to become a head coach and fourth coordinator overall.<ref name=\"gainesville\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gainesville.com/article/20051218/GATORS20/212180363|title=San Diego State hires Chuck Long as head coach &#124; Gainesville.com|publisher=gainesville.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n2006 was a very tumultuous year for the Sooners. In the offseason, OU made [[Kevin Wilson (American football)|Kevin Wilson]] the new offensive coordinator. One day before fall practice began, returning quarterback [[Rhett Bomar]] and J.D. Quinn, a projected starter on the offensive line, were kicked off the team for violating NCAA rules when they received payment for work they did not do. Paul Thompson, who had played wide receiver in 2005 and had not practiced in the quarterback role for nearly a year, was asked to move back to quarterback which he did. In mid-September, Oklahoma played Oregon for the third time in three years. The Sooners lost this game 34\u201333. During the [[2006 Oklahoma Sooners football team#University of Oregon|game]] a controversy arose when game officials awarded an onside kick to the Ducks when it should have been Oklahoma's ball.<ref name=\"suspend\">{{cite web | title=Pac-10 suspends officials for errors that cost Oklahoma | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=2593564 | publisher=ESPN.com | accessdate=December 4, 2006 | date=September 19, 2006  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Suspension, apology leaves Stoops unsatisfied | url=http://www.newsok.com/article/2849797/?template=sports/ou | publisher=NewsOK.com | accessdate=December 4, 2006 | date=September 19, 2006  }}</ref> Following the game, all officials were suspended for one game but replay official [[Gordon Riese]] said he would take the year off;<ref name=\"suspend\" /> later in the year, he would quit completely.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gordon Riese's replay revelation |url=http://www.newsok.com/article/keyword/2975982/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929092046/http://www.newsok.com/article/keyword/2975982/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 29, 2007 |first=George |last=Schroeder |publisher=NewsOK.com |accessdate=December 4, 2006 |date=November 23, 2006 }}</ref> Gordon Riese later acknowledged that he knew Oklahoma recovered the onside kick but replay rules prevented him from correcting the on-field officials.<ref>{{cite web | title=Replay official also knew OU recovered kick | url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/15867102/ | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061126202102/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/15867102/ | url-status=dead | archive-date=November 26, 2006 | publisher=MSNBC.com | accessdate=December 4, 2006 | date=November 23, 2006  }}</ref> A few weeks later, Oklahoma lost to rival Texas. Following these setbacks, the team regrouped and the defense vastly improved. Following the Oregon game, the defense was ranked 97th nationally<ref>{{cite web|title=Football: Sooners' defense regains its swagger |url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/sports/stories/MYSA120106.01D.FBCou.defense.2a84a90.html |publisher=San Antonio Express-News |first=Tim |last=Griffin |date=November 30, 2006 |accessdate=December 4, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929105038/http://www.mysanantonio.com/sports/stories/MYSA120106.01D.FBCou.defense.2a84a90.html |archivedate=September 29, 2007 }}</ref> but by the end of the regular season, they were ranked 17th.<ref>{{cite web | title=Ranking Summary | url=http://web1.ncaa.org/d1mfb/2006/Internet/ranking_summary/2006000000522.HTML | publisher=NCAA  | accessdate=December 4, 2006}}</ref> Following the Texas game, Oklahoma played [[Iowa State Cyclones football|Iowa State]] and soundly defeated them 34\u20139. However, on the final touchdown drive for the Sooners, star running back [[Adrian Peterson]] suffered a broken [[Clavicle|collar bone]] when he attempted to dive into the end zone to finish a tough touchdown run.<ref name=\"APcollar\">{{cite news | title=Oklahoma's Peterson returns to practice | agency=Associated Press | date=December 8, 2006 | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=2691671 | accessdate=October 12, 2007}}</ref> The Sooners would turn to two untested running back to replace the Heisman-hopeful Peterson, [[Allen Patrick]], a junior, and Chris Brown, a freshman. The Sooners did not miss a step. The team went on a seven-game winning streak to finish Big 12 conference play 11\u20132. This streak included road wins over a couple of ranked opponents, Texas A&M and Missouri. The defending national champions Texas Longhorns were favored to win the Big 12 but they suffered two losses to finish their regular season which sent Oklahoma to the Big 12 Championship game against a former rival, the Nebraska Cornhuskers. The Sooners defeated the 19th ranked Cornhuskers 21\u20137 to win the Big 12 title for the fourth time under Bob Stoops, automatically sending them to the [[2007 Fiesta Bowl|Fiesta Bowl]]. The Sooners lost the wild, thrilling game in overtime, on a trick two-point conversion play by a score of 43\u201342 to [[Boise State Broncos football|Boise State]].<ref name=\"usatoday\">{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/college/football/games/2007-01-02-fiesta_x.htm|title=Boise State shocks Oklahoma with dramatic play calls in OT at Fiesta Bowl \u2013 USATODAY.com|publisher=usatoday30.usatoday.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Sam Bradford and resurgence (2007\u20132008)====\n\nThe 2007 Oklahoma team opened up with a home game against [[North Texas Mean Green football|North Texas]] and soundly beat them 79\u201310. The 79&nbsp;points scored by OU was the most in the country for Week 1. In Week 2, the Sooners played a much tougher opponent in Miami. However, the results seemed to show a mismatch, as OU easily defeated the Hurricanes 51\u201313. In Week 3, the Sooners got the best of [[Utah State Aggies football|Utah State]] with a 54\u20133 thrashing. Week 4 matched OU up with an in-state foe, [[Tulsa Golden Hurricane football|Tulsa]]. Just as it had been all season (except for the Sep 29 loss at unranked Colorado), the Sooners put up another dominant performance with a 62\u201321 victory. In Week 5 (September 29, 2007), the #4 Sooners saw their National Championship hopes take a hit as they lost to 2\u20132 unranked Colorado in Boulder 27\u201324 after leading in the second half by a score of 24\u20137. The Sooners only had 234 net yards compared to Colorado's 379 net yards. The 2007 match-up between Oklahoma and Texas on Oct. 2007 was predicted to be the #3&nbsp;game to watch in 2007 by SI.com's \"Top 20&nbsp;Games To Watch In 2007\" list. The Oklahoma football team proved itself worthy of the top ten rankings when it defeated Texas 28\u201321 at the Red River Rivalry. The Texas Longhorns played up to their potential when they answered almost every point during the October 6&nbsp;game. In the end [[Colt McCoy]] along with [[Jermichael Finley]] and the Longhorns could not withstand the adamant pressing of [[Sam Bradford]], [[DeMarco Murray]] and the Sooners.<ref>{{cite web | title = Top 20 Games To Watch In 2007 | work = SI.com | url = http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/multimedia/photo_gallery/0708/top.cfb.games.watch/content.18.html | accessdate =  September 30, 2007 }}</ref>  Oklahoma would go on to lose to an unranked Texas Tech team in an upset, although this was not enough to keep them from the Big 12 championship. They would go on to defeat [[Missouri Tigers football|Missouri]] in the Big 12 championship game and win the Big 12's automatic BCS berth, playing [[West Virginia Mountaineers football|West Virginia]] in the Fiesta Bowl. For the second consecutive year Oklahoma would lose to an underdog opponent in a BCS bowl game, although this game was not as close as the previous year.<ref name=\"scores.espn.go.com\">{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=280020201|title=West Virginia Mountaineers vs. Oklahoma Sooners \u2013 Recap \u2013 January 02, 2008 \u2013 ESPN|publisher=scores.espn.go.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> Oklahoma was down 14&nbsp;points at halftime and never pulled close than 20\u201315, eventually losing 48\u201328.<ref name=\"scores.espn.go.com\"/> After the 2007 season ended, offensive coordinator [[Kevin Sumlin]] resigned to accept the head football coach position at [[Houston Cougars football|Houston]], becoming the fourth Sooners offensive coordinator under Stoops to take a head coaching job and the fifth coordinator overall.<ref name=\"go2\">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=3153106|title=Source: Houston hires Sumlin, eighth minority coach in FBS  \u2013 College Football \u2013 ESPN|publisher=sports.espn.go.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Sooners opened 2008 ranked fourth in both the Associated Press Poll and the USA Today Coaches' Poll. Opening with back to back home victories against Chattanooga and Cincinnati and scoring over 50&nbsp;points against both opponents would vault Oklahoma to number two in both polls, coupled with, then number three, Ohio State's loss and a lackluster victory by, then number two, Georgia over South Carolina. A road victory at Washington where the Sooners again scored more than 50&nbsp;points, a home victory over then undefeated and 24th ranked Texas Christian University, and a road win at Baylor resulted in Oklahoma being ranked number one in both polls after then-ranked number one USC tumbled after a defeat at Oregon State. The Sooners had defeated each of their first five opponents by 25&nbsp;points or more before facing then-number five Texas. In a see-saw battle where Oklahoma would take their last lead at 35\u201330, Texas would come from behind with 15 unanswered points to upset the Sooners at a neutral field by a final score of 45\u201335. The Sooners could muster up only 48 rushing yards while giving up 161. Also of note, the Sooners failed to convert on three fourth down attempts and Bradford threw two interceptions. Oklahoma would fall to number four in the AP Poll and number six in the USA Today Poll, while the Longhorns would be the new number one team in both polls. The game would result in controversy later in the season. Oklahoma would rebound by defeating then-ranked #16 Kansas at home and a road win at Kansas State. By the Week 8 rankings, Oklahoma would be ranked fourth in the AP Poll, fifth in the USA Today Coaches' Poll, and debut at fourth in the BCS behind undefeated Texas, [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]], and [[Penn State Nittany Lions football|Penn State]]. The Sooners would then go on to defeat their next three opponents by more than 30&nbsp;points each, scoring 60 or more points. A home victory over Nebraska, a road win at Texas A&M and another home win over then-ranked #2 Texas Tech would result in some controversy. Along with an upset of Texas at the hands of Texas Tech and a previous loss by Penn State against [[Iowa Hawkeyes football|Iowa]], Oklahoma was ranked 3 in the Associated Press Poll and number 2 in the USA Today Coaches' Poll ahead of Texas. However, Texas would be number two in the BCS followed by Oklahoma at number three. Alabama would hold number one in all polls with an undefeated record. Closing out the season with a win against Oklahoma State and Alabama's loss to Florida would leave the Sooners at number two in the Associated Press poll, and number one in both the USA Today Coaches' Poll and the BCS. The result of the three-way tie between Oklahoma, Texas, and Texas Tech in the Big 12 South standings, where each team suffered one loss at the hands of the other, would be the cause for many fans, particularly Texas fans, to cry foul. The Big 12 tie-breaker in this scenario was for the team with the highest BCS ranking to go on to play for the Big 12 Title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/ncaa/football/recap?gid=200812060024 |title=2008 Big 12 Championship |publisher=RivalsYahoo.com |accessdate=December 29, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109032857/http://sports.yahoo.com/ncaa/football/recap?gid=200812060024 |archivedate=November 9, 2013 }}</ref> Beating 19th ranked Missouri in Kansas City assured Oklahoma of a number one ranking in both the USA Today Coaches' Poll and the BCS, despite a number two ranking in the Associated Press Poll. Texas would finish number three in all polls, rendering them ineligible to play in the title game. Additionally, quarterback [[Sam Bradford]] would win the Heisman Trophy and be named the Associated Press Player of the Year for the 2008 season.<ref name=\"go3\">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=3767667|title=Oklahoma quarterback Sam Bradford wins Heisman Trophy  \u2013 ESPN|publisher=sports.espn.go.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> On January 8, 2009, the Sooners were defeated by the Florida Gators for the BCS Championship at Dolphin Stadium in Miami by a score of 24\u201314.<ref name=\"nola\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.nola.com/tpsports/2009/01/_beats_to_win_bcs_national_cha.html|title=Florida beats Oklahoma 24-14 to win BCS national championship &#124;       NOLA.com|publisher=blog.nola.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> This was the fourth time that the Sooners were playing for the National Championship under Coach Stoops.\n\n====Landry Jones takes the snaps (2009\u20132012)====\n\nThe 2009 season was a challenge for the Sooners. After losing star quarterback Sam Bradford in the first game, and eventually for the whole season, freshman quarterback [[Landry Jones]] had to take over. The Sooners ended up with a total of 15 injuries at the end of the season. The season ended in an 8\u20135 record.<ref name=\"sports-reference11\"/> The Sooners went on to beat Stanford in the El Paso Sun Bowl 31\u201327, setting them up for a title run in the 2010 season.\n\nThe 2010 season turned out to be much more successful than the 2009 campaign. The Sooners ended the season with a record of 12\u20132<ref name=\"sports-reference11\"/> and became the Tostito's Fiesta Bowl champions by defeating [[Connecticut Huskies football|Connecticut]] by a score of 48\u201320 in Glendale, Arizona.<ref name=\"go4\">{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=310010201|title=Connecticut Huskies vs. Oklahoma Sooners \u2013 Recap \u2013 January 01, 2011 \u2013 ESPN|publisher=scores.espn.go.com|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> This was the first BCS bowl game victory for Bob Stoops and the Sooners since the 2003 Rose Bowl.<ref name=\"sports-reference11\"/><ref name=\"go4\"/> Marquee victories for the Sooners in 2010 were against [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]], [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas]], [[Oklahoma State Cowboys football|Oklahoma State]] and [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|Nebraska]]. The Bedlam match-up between the Sooners and Cowboys proved to be the decisive game in who would represent the Big 12 South in the conference championship game. The Sooners defeated the Cowboys in a high scoring affair 47\u201341. The Sooners went on to win the Big 12 Championship game 23\u201320, the final match between conference rival [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|Nebraska]]. After the 2010 season, offensive coordinator Kevin Wilson left OU to become head coach at [[Indiana Hoosiers football|Indiana]], becoming the fifth Sooners offensive coordinator under Bob Stoops to become a head coach and the sixth coordinator overall.<ref name=\"go5\">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=5896426 |title=Kevin Wilson given 7-year deal to coach Indiana Hoosiers \u2013 ESPN |publisher=sports.espn.go.com |accessdate=May 7, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140307013337/http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=5896426 |archivedate=March 7, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nWith star players, Landry Jones, Ryan Broyles, and Travis Lewis coming back for the 2011 season, there were high expectations for Bob Stoops and his Sooner football team. Stoops hired former Sooners quarterback Josh Heupel as offensive coordinator to replace the departed Wilson. OU began the season ranked #1 in both the AP and Coaches polls. The Sooners became the first teams to reach the top ranking in the Associated Press poll 100 times since the poll began in 1936.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/story/_/id/6957853/oklahoma-sooners-ranked-no-1-associated-press-poll-100th-time | title=AP ranks Sooners No.1 for 100th time | publisher=espn.go.com | accessdate=September 11, 2011 }}</ref> Under Stoops, OU has been ranked No. 1 more weeks than they have not been ranked in the top 25. They were able to accomplish this feat without even stepping foot on the field, as they had their bye week this weekend. Their early season match-up with fellow top five team Florida State proved to test the Sooners, as they looked to prove that their #1 ranking was warranted. As the Sooners played well the first few weeks the Sooners were thought to be out of the National Title race with a heartbreaking loss to the unranked Texas Tech Red Raiders snapping a school-record 39&nbsp;game home win streak. However, the Sooners bounced back the following. few weeks to become ranked fifth in the country despite losing star receiver Ryan Broyles only to lose to Baylor for the first time in school history. They stayed in the hunt for a share of the conference title and a [[Fiesta Bowl]] appearance until losing to in-state rival Oklahoma State in the last game of the season. They finished the regular season 9\u20133 and went on to defeat Iowa 31\u201314 in the [[2010 Insight Bowl|Insight Bowl]].<ref name=\"sports-reference11\"/>\n\n====Late Stoops era (2013\u20132014)====\n\nThe 2013 Oklahoma Sooners football team represented the University of Oklahoma in the 2013 college football season, the 119th season of Sooner football. Conference play began at home on September 7 with a win against the West Virginia Mountaineers and ended in the annual Bedlam Series on December 7 against the Oklahoma State Cowboys in Stillwater with the Sooners upsetting the Cowboys 33\u201324. With the victory over the Kansas State Wildcats on November 23, head coach Bob Stoops got his 158th career win to move past Barry Switzer for the most wins in program history. After finishing the regular season with a record of 10\u20132 (7\u20132 in Big 12 play), finishing in a tie for second place in the conference. The Sooners received an at-large bid to participate in the [[2014 Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl]], where they defeated the Alabama Crimson Tide, the previous year's national champions, with a final score of 45\u201331. [[Trevor Knight]] was named Sugar Bowl MVP.\n\nIn 2014, the Oklahoma Sooners football team represented the University of Oklahoma in their 120th season and the inaugural season for the [[College Football Playoff]]. Knight was the starting quarterback for the season. The Sooners opened the season ranked 4th and quickly jumped to a 4\u20130 record.  The Sooners then lost their 5th game to [[2014 TCU Horned Frogs football team|TCU]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fbschedules.com/ncaa-14/big-12/2014-oklahoma-sooners-football-schedule.php|title=2014 Oklahoma Sooners Football Schedule \u2013 OU|author=|date=|publisher=|access-date=September 26, 2016}}</ref> They then slid past their old rival [[2014 Texas Longhorns football team|Texas]] but suffered a loss to [[2014 Kansas State Wildcats football team|Kansas State]], 31\u201330 at home.  The Sooners closed the regular season with an 8\u20134 record after losing to in-state rival [[2014 Oklahoma State Cowboys football team|Oklahoma State]] in overtime.  The Sooners got one more chance to redeem themselves as they faced the 18th-ranked [[2014 Clemson Tigers football team|Clemson Tigers]] in the Russell Athletic Bowl (Orlando, Florida), but instead suffered one of the worst bowl losses in Sooner history as they lost, 40\u20136. \n[[File:2017-0717-Big12MD-BakerMayfield.jpg|thumb|Baker Mayfield]]\n\n==== First College Football Playoff appearance and Back-to-Back Big 12 Conference Titles (2015-2016) ====\nThe Sooners would regain national prominence during the 2015 season. [[Baker Mayfield]] took over as the starting quarterback at the start of the season, and led the Sooners to a 11-1 regular season record with the help of his high-powered offense including wide receiver [[Sterling Shepard]] and running back [[Samaje Perine]]. The Sooners would capture the 2015 Big 12 Conference Title. Oklahoma earned the fourth and final spot in the College Football Playoff, as Mayfield would finish fourth in Heisman Trophy voting. The stage was set for a rematch against [[2015 Clemson Tigers football team|Clemson]] in the [[2015 Orange Bowl]]. They would lose, once again, to Clemson by a score of 37-17, even though they led at halftime 17-16. Shepard would leave for the [[2016 NFL Draft]].\n\nThe 2016 season was a continuation of the success the Sooners had the year before. Mayfield was granted the season of eligibility that he had lost due to Big 12 Conference transfer restrictions, and [[Dede Westbrook]] and the controversial, oft-suspended [[Joe Mixon]] had breakthrough years. The Sooners wouldn't be able to make the College Football Playoff this time around, as they lost 2 of their first 3 games (Week 1 vs. [[2016 Houston Cougars football team|Houston]] and Week 3 vs. [[2016 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]]). They still enjoyed a successful season - defeating [[2016 Oklahoma State Cowboys football team|Oklahoma State]] 38\u201320 to win their second Big 12 Conference Title in a row, and having two Heisman Trophy finalists (Mayfield and Westbrook). They would go on to defeat the [[2016 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn Tigers]] in the [[2017 Sugar Bowl]], 35-19. During the game, Perine became the school's career rushing yards leader with 4,122, and would forgo his senior year to leave for the [[2017 NFL Draft]].\n\nOn June 7, 2017, it was confirmed that Stoops would retire effective immediately after 18 seasons as the Sooners head football coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/19571249/bob-stoops-steps-coach-oklahoma-sooners|title=Sooners' Stoops steps down after 18 seasons|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Lincoln Riley era (2017\u2013present)===\n\n==== Baker Mayfield's Heisman Season (2017) ====\nAfter Stoops' retirement, OU promoted offensive coordinator [[Lincoln Riley]] to head coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2017/06/08/lincoln-riley-oklahoma-football-coach/|title=Lincoln Riley, 33, takes over as Oklahoma's football coach|date=June 8, 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn his first season, Riley led the Sooners to a 12\u20131 regular season record, beating the 10 win record held by [[Barry Switzer]] and [[Chuck Fairbanks]] for most wins by a first-year coach in program history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.myajc.com/sports/college/lincoln-riley-sets-win-record-for-1st-year-oklahoma-head-coach/2Gb3JKUElzoCMJ6ZSfL8SI/|title=Lincoln Riley sets win record for 1st year Oklahoma Head Coach|date=November 25, 2017|publisher=}}</ref> Riley and the Sooners beat TCU 41\u201317 in the [[2017 Big 12 Championship Game]] at [[AT&T Stadium]] in Arlington on December 2, 2017 and were crowned Big 12 Conference champions for the third time in a row (2015, 2016, and 2017). Mayfield would finally win the [[List of Heisman Trophy winners|Heisman Trophy]] in 2017 in his fifth-year senior season (and would later become the first pick in the [[2018 NFL Draft]]). Riley and the Sooners played the [[2017 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia Bulldogs]] on January 1, 2018 at the [[2018 Rose Bowl|Rose Bowl]] in the [[College Football Playoff]] Semi-Final game. The game was the first matchup between the two teams in program history. Oklahoma lost in double overtime 54\u201348.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.winsipedia.com/oklahoma/vs/georgia|title=Georgia VS Oklahoma|date=2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==== Kyler Murray Takes Over at QB and Wins the Heisman (2018) ====\nWith Mayfield leaving for the NFL, Kyler Murray took over the reins as the starting quarterback for [[2018 Oklahoma Sooners football team|2018 season]]. He immediately picked up where Mayfield left off and led OU to a 5-0 start with help from star wide receivers [[Marquise Brown]] and [[CeeDee Lamb]].\n\n==Conference affiliations==\nOklahoma has been independent and a member of three conferences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/oklahoma/index.html|title=Oklahoma Sooners School History|publisher=Sports Reference.com|accessdate=January 1, 2017}}</ref>\n* Independent (1895\u20131914) \n* [[Southwest Conference]] (1915\u20131919) \n* [[Big Eight Conference]] (1920\u20131995) <!-- Missouri Valley Intercollegiate Athletic Association 1920-27 is claimed by Big Eight -->\n* [[Big 12 Conference]] (1996\u2013present)\n\n==Championships==\n\n===National championships===\nOklahoma claims seven consensus national championships won by selection in the major college football polls.<ref name=\"2018MG\">{{cite web |title=2018 Media Guide |url=http://www.soonersports.com/fls/31000/pdfs/18fb_media_guide.pdf |website=soonersports.com |publisher=Oklahoma Athletics |accessdate=August 24, 2018 |format=PDF}}</ref>{{rp|13}} In addition, in ten years other than those seven championship seasons, Oklahoma has appeared atop lists by selectors designated by the NCAA as \"major\", primarily using math rating formulas.<ref name=\"Walsh2007\">{{cite book|author=Christopher J. Walsh|title=Who's #1?: 100-Plus Years of Controversial National Champions in College Football|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=580XAQAAMAAJ|year=2007|publisher=Taylor Trade Pub.|isbn=978-1-58979-337-8|page=53}}</ref><ref name=\"2017ncaabook\" />{{rp|108\u2013115}}\n\n====Claimed national championships====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Oklahoma Sooners|Season|Coach|Selector(s)|Record|Bowl|Opponent|Result}}\n|- \n| [[1950 Oklahoma Sooners football team|1950]] || [[Bud Wilkinson]] || [[AP Poll|AP]], Berryman, Helms, Litkenhous, UPI [[Coaches' Poll|Coaches]], Williamson<ref name=\"2017ncaabook\" />{{rp|112}} || 10\u20131 || [[1951 Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl]] || [[1950 Kentucky Wildcats football team|Kentucky]] || L 7\u201313\n|- \n| [[1955 Oklahoma Sooners football team|1955]] || Bud Wilkinson || AP, Berryman, Billingsley, DeVold, Dunkel, Football Research, FW, Helms, INS, Litkenhous, National Championship Foundation, [[Poling System|Poling]], Sagarin, Sagarin (