com/books?id=0myCDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT618&lpg=PT618&dq=oklahoma+football+1972+ncaa+penalty+forfeit&source=bl&ots=NwjRYuc3Bg&sig=ACfU3U1fwe_YeGEegB4YKzl3dRh13opOmQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjg2cvE0afmAhURXa0KHVPSC_oQ6AEwDXoECBIQAQ#v=onepage&q=oklahoma%20football%201972%20ncaa%20penalty%20forfeit&f=false}}</ref>\n\n===Division championships===\nThe Sooners have been a member of only one division, the Big 12 South, in their entire history. They were members from 1996 until 2010, after which the Big 12 ceased divisional play.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Oklahoma Sooners|Season|Division|Coach|Overall Record|Conference Record|Opponent|CG result}}\n|-\n| [[2000 Oklahoma Sooners football team|2000]] || [[Big 12 Conference#Membership|Big 12 South]]  || [[Bob Stoops]]  || 13\u20130 || 8\u20130 || [[2000 Kansas State Wildcats football team|Kansas State]] || '''W''' 27\u201324\n|-\n| [[2002 Oklahoma Sooners football team|2002]] \u2020 || Big 12 South || Bob Stoops || 12\u20132 || 6\u20132 || [[2002 Colorado Buffaloes football team|Colorado]] || '''W''' 29\u20137\n|-\n| [[2003 Oklahoma Sooners football team|2003]] || Big 12 South || Bob Stoops || 12\u20132 || 8\u20130 || [[2003 Kansas State Wildcats football team|Kansas State]] || L 7\u201335\n|-\n| [[2004 Oklahoma Sooners football team|2004]] || Big 12 South || Bob Stoops || 12\u20131 || 8\u20130 || [[2004 Colorado Buffaloes football team|Colorado]] || '''W''' 42\u20133\n|-\n| [[2006 Oklahoma Sooners football team|2006]] || Big 12 South || Bob Stoops || 11\u20133 || 7\u20131 || [[2006 Nebraska Cornhuskers football team|Nebraska]] || '''W''' 21\u20137\n|-\n| [[2007 Oklahoma Sooners football team|2007]] || Big 12 South || Bob Stoops || 11\u20133 || 6\u20132 || [[2007 Missouri Tigers football team|Missouri]] || '''W''' 38\u201317\n|-\n| [[2008 Oklahoma Sooners football team|2008]] \u2020 || Big 12 South || Bob Stoops || 12\u20132 || 7\u20131 || [[2008 Missouri Tigers football team|Missouri]] || '''W''' 62\u201321\n|-\n| [[2010 Oklahoma Sooners football team|2010]] \u2020 || Big 12 South || Bob Stoops || 12\u20132 || 6\u20132 || [[2010 Nebraska Cornhuskers football team|Nebraska]] || '''W''' 23\u201320\n|-\n|}\n\u2020 Co-championship\n\n==Head coaches==\n{{Main|List of Oklahoma Sooners head football coaches}}\nThe team has had 22 head coaches, with [[Lincoln Riley]] as the current head coach in his third season.<ref name=\"coach hist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/head_coaches.html |author=OU Athletic Department |title=Head Coaches |accessdate=May 16, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100523222607/http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/head_coaches.html |archivedate=May 23, 2010 }}</ref> Oklahoma started organized football with the nickname ''Sooners'' in 1895.<ref name=\"year by year rec\">{{cite web|url=http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/m-footbl-yr-by-yr-season-results.html |author=OU Athletic Department |title=Football Year by year season results |accessdate=May 16, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100523222608/http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/m-footbl-yr-by-yr-season-results.html |archivedate=May 23, 2010 }}</ref> The Sooners have played in more than 1,100 games in a total of 96 seasons.<ref name=\"year by year rec\"/> In those seasons, nine coaches have led the Sooners to postseason bowl games: [[Tom Stidham]], [[Jim Tatum]], [[Bud Wilkinson]], [[Gomer Jones]], [[Chuck Fairbanks]], [[Barry Switzer]], [[Gary Gibbs]], [[Bob Stoops]], and Lincoln Riley. Nine coaches have won [[Athletic conference|conference]] championships with the Sooners: [[Bennie Owen]], Stidham, [[Dewey Luster]], Tatum, Wilkinson, Fairbanks, Switzer, Stoops, and Riley. Owen is the all-time leader in games coached and years coached, while Switzer is the all-time leader in [[winning percentage]]. Bob Stoops is the leader in wins. [[John A. Harts|John Harts]] is, in terms of winning percentage, the worst coach the Sooners have had; he lost the only game he coached, giving him a .000 winning percentage. [[John Blake (American football)|John Blake]] has the lowest winning percentage of those who have coached more than one game with .353.<ref name=\"coach hist\"/>\n\nOf the 22 Sooner coaches, Owen, [[Lawrence Mcceney \"Biff\" Jones|Lawrence Jones]], Tatum, Wilkinson, and Switzer have been inducted in the [[College Football Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/m-footbl-hall-of-famers.html |author=OU Athletic Department |title=Hall of Famers |accessdate=May 16, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100523224631/http://www.soonersports.com/sports/m-footbl/archive/m-footbl-hall-of-famers.html |archivedate=May 23, 2010 }}</ref> Wilkinson, Switzer, and Stoops have each received National Coach of the Year honors from at least one organization.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soonersports.com/school-bio/bob_stoops.html|author=OU Athletic Department|title=Bob Stoop Biography|accessdate=May 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Stadium==\n[[File:OMSFront.jpg|thumb|Gaylord Family \u2013 Oklahoma Memorial Stadium]]\n\nThe Sooners play their home games at [[Gaylord Family Oklahoma Memorial Stadium]] also known as The Palace on the Prairie. The stadium was formerly called Oklahoma Memorial Stadium but the administration decided to add 'Gaylord Family' to recognize the contributions made by [[Edward K. Gaylord]] and his family over the years (estimated at over $50&nbsp;million).<ref>{{cite web|title=OU Regents OK Stadium Name Change |url=http://hub.ou.edu/articles/article.php?article_id=1460658802 |first=Justin Noel |last=Shimko |date=September 22, 2002 |accessdate=January 8, 2007 |publisher=OU Daily }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The playing surface is called Owen Field after Bennie Owen, Oklahoma's coach from 1905 to 1926. The stadium was built in 1923 with an original capacity of 500.<ref name=\"SS_OMS\">{{cite web|title=Oklahoma Memorial Stadium History |url=http://www.soonerstats.com/football/stadium/index.cfm |publisher=SoonerStats.com |accessdate=January 8, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070809232045/http://www.soonerstats.com/football/stadium/index.cfm |archivedate=August 9, 2007 }}</ref> In 1925, 16,000&nbsp;seats were added and 16,000 more seats were added in 1929 bringing the total capacity to 32,000. The stadium has had a natural grass playing surface for the majority of its existence. The stadium had an [[artificial turf]] from 1970 to 1994.<ref name=\"SS_OMS\" /> The stadium had a major renovation in 2003 when a new upper deck was added to the east side of the stadium, adding over 8,400 new seats. The official seating capacity of the stadium, following renovations in 2015, is 83,489. which makes it the 15th largest college stadium in the U.S. and second largest in the Big 12 Conference.<ref name=\"SS_OMS\" /> Despite the official capacity, the Sooners routinely average well above capacity, most recently 86,857 for the 2017 season. The largest crowd ever was 88,308 on November 11, 2017 against TCU.<ref name=\"steele\">{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=Summer 2017|title=Football Game Attendance Records \u2013 Home|url=http://soonerstats.com/football/research/attendance-game.cfm?location=H#.WZ8-fj6GOUk|journal=SoonerStats|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Rivalries==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2018}}\n\n===Nebraska===\n{{Main|Nebraska\u2013Oklahoma football rivalry}}\nOklahoma's rivalry with the [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|Nebraska Cornhuskers]] historically had national championship implications, with the winner usually advancing to the [[Orange Bowl]]. The teams often met on [[Thanksgiving (United States)|Thanksgiving]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/1865367-why-we-wish-nebraskas-real-thanksgiving-rivalries-would-come-back|title=Why We Wish Nebraska's Real Thanksgiving Rivalries Would Come Back|date=November 25, 2013|accessdate=August 24, 2018}}</ref> For the majority of the 20th century Oklahoma and Nebraska competed as part of the [[Big Eight Conference]] where from 1907 to 1995 the programs won a combined 77 conference titles. The teams are noted for playing in the [[1971 Nebraska vs. Oklahoma football game|Game of the Century]], in 1971 which OU lost 35\u201331. In 1996, the teams joined the [[Big XII Conference]] when Nebraska joined the North Division, and Oklahoma joined the South Division, thus ending the annual match-ups between the programs in 1998 and 1999. In 2000 the series resumed with Nebraska and Oklahoma being ranked number one and two in the BCS rankings. OU won 31\u201314. Oklahoma leads the inactive series 45\u201338\u20133 as of 2018 with the last game being the [[2010 Big 12 Championship Game]], won by Oklahoma 23\u201320. The two programs are scheduled to resume the rivalry in 2021, and 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/8691411/oklahoma-sooners-nebraska-cornhuskers-resume-storied-series-2021|title=Nebraska-Oklahoma to resume series|publisher=[[ESPN.com]]|last=Trotter|first=Jake|date=November 29, 2012|accessdate=August 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Oklahoma State===\n{{Main|Bedlam Series}}\nOklahoma leads the series 89\u201318\u20137 through the 2019 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.winsipedia.com/oklahoma/vs/oklahoma-state|title=Winsipedia - Oklahoma Sooners vs. Oklahoma State Cowboys football series history|website=Winsipedia}}</ref>\n\n===Texas===\n{{Main|Red River Showdown}}\nThe Red River Showdown or the OU\u2013Texas Game is the annual matchup in [[Dallas]] during the [[State Fair of Texas]] between Oklahoma and the [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas Longhorns]]. Since 1929, the game has been played annually at the [[Cotton Bowl (stadium)|Cotton Bowl]], halfway between [[Norman, Oklahoma|Norman]] and [[Austin, Texas|Austin]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsok.com/article/4896891/ou-texas-much-to-celebrate-about-cotton-bowl-commitment|title=OU-Texas: Much to celebrate about Cotton Bowl Commitment|publisher=[[The Oklahoman]]|last=Trammel|first=Berry|date=June 10, 2014|access-date=April 28, 2019}}</ref> For the majority of the 20th century the game was a non-conference match-up. Texas competed in the [[Southwest Conference]]. In 1996, the two programs became part of the [[Big XII Conference]] South division. That year Oklahoma won the first overtime game of the series, after a tie the previous year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/884172-oklahoma-vs-texas-the-10-greatest-red-river-rivalry-games#slide3|title=Oklahoma vs Texas 10 greatest Red River Rivalry Games|publisher=Bleacher Report|last=Copp|first=Martha|date=October 8, 2011|access-date=August 24, 2018}}</ref> The stadium is split along the 50-yard line with Oklahoma fans occupying the south half of the field. Texas leads the series 62\u201348\u20135 through the 2019 season.<ref>http://www.winsipedia.com/oklahoma/vs/texas</ref>\n\n===Missouri===\n{{Main|Missouri\u2013Oklahoma football rivalry}}\nOklahoma leads the inactive series 67\u201324\u20135 as of 2018 with the last game played in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.winsipedia.com/oklahoma/vs/missouri|title=Winsipedia - Oklahoma Sooners vs. Missouri Tigers football series history|website=Winsipedia}}</ref>\n\n==Pageantry==\n===School colors===\n{|  style=\"float:right; border:1px solid #666; padding:2px;\"\n|-\n| style=\"background:#841617; width:50px; height:50px; padding:2px; border:1px solid #aaa;\"| &nbsp;\n| style=\"background:#FDF9D8; width:50px; height:50px; padding:2px; border:1px solid #aaa;\"| &nbsp;\n|-  style=\"line-height:90%; text-align:center;\"\n|| Crimson\n|| Cream\n|}\nOklahoma's official school colors are crimson and cream.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.soonersports.com/trads/crimson-creme.html# | title=Oklahoma Traditions: Crimson & Cream | work=SoonerSports.com | publisher=[[University of Oklahoma]] | access-date=August 21, 2007 | url-status=dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070718195736/http://www.soonersports.com/trads/crimson-creme.html | archive-date=July 18, 2007 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> These colors were picked in 1895 by May Overstreet, the only female faculty member at the time. The colors were her own personal choice and she decided on them after viewing many color samples and materials.<ref>{{cite book | series = Sooner Yearbook | year=1916 | title=The Origin of the University Yell and Colors | page=326 }}</ref> After her decision, the colors were brought in front of the student body who enthusiastically approved of her selections. In recent years,{{When|date=April 2019}} red and white have sometimes replaced crimson and cream.\n\n===Mascot===\nOklahoma has had several mascots. The first was a stray dog named ''Mex''. Mex was found in Mexico during the [[Mexican Revolution]] by Mott Keys, an army hospital [[medic]].<ref name=\"OUFBEnc\">{{cite book | last=Dozier | first=Ray | title=The Oklahoma Football Encyclopedia | year=2006 | publisher=Sports Publishing, LLC | location=Champaign, Illinois | isbn=1-58261-699-X }}</ref> Keys' [[Company (military unit)|company]] adopted the dog and Keys took the dog back to [[Hollis, Oklahoma]] when he completed his duty. When Keys was enrolled in the university, he took Mex with him to Norman. With his experience as an army medic, Keys landed a job with the football team and a residence at the [[Kappa Sigma]] [[Fraternities and sororities|fraternity]] house.<ref name=\"OUFBEnc\" /> Mex's main duty during games was to keep stray dogs from roaming the field. He wore a red sweater with a big \"O\" letter on the side. Mex received national attention in October 1924 when the Oklahoma football team lost a game against [[Drake University]]. Mex was lost when the team boarded a train in [[Arkansas City, Kansas]]. The media blamed the loss on the field on the loss of their mascot.<ref name=\"SS_SS&M\">{{cite web|title=Sooner Schooner & Mascots |work=SoonerSports.com |publisher=[[University of Oklahoma]] |url=http://www.soonersports.com/trads/schooner-mascots.html |accessdate=August 21, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070811162821/http://www.soonersports.com/trads/schooner-mascots.html |archivedate=August 11, 2007 }}</ref> Mex was found later by two Oklahoma graduates. Mex died of old age on April 30, 1928. The campus was closed and classes were canceled on the day of his funeral. He was buried in a casket somewhere under the stadium.<ref name=\"OUFBEnc\" />\n\n[[File:SoonerSchooner.jpg|thumb|The [[Sooner Schooner]] on the field during a football game.]]\nNever an official mascot, ''Little Red'' began appearing at games in 1953. He was an [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Indian]] who wore red tights, [[Loincloth|breech cloth]] and a war bonnet and was last portrayed by Randy Palmer.<ref name=\"OUFBEnc\" />  In April 1970, Little Red was banished by Oklahoma president ''[[John Herbert Hollomon, Jr.]]'' The student court issued a temporary restraining order to keep Little Red from appearing at Sooner games.<ref name=\"OUFBEnc\" /> Despite this order, Palmer showed up as Little Red for the 1970 season opener where he was met with cheers from the crowd. When Palmer was [[Draft (sports)|drafted]] after the 1971 season, no one showed up for try-outs to replace him.<ref name=\"OUFBEnc\" />\n\nThe current mascot for Oklahoma is the ''[[Sooner Schooner]]'', a [[conestoga wagon]] similar to the primary method of transportation used by early settlers in Oklahoma.<ref name=\"SS_SS&M\"/> The Schooner is driven by two white [[pony|ponies]] named [[Boomer and Sooner (mascots)|Boomer and Sooner]]. In 2005, the university also introduced two costumed mascots also named Boomer and Sooner to serve as mascots for football games and events that do not permit a covered wagon.<ref name=\"SS_SS&M\"/>\n\n===Music===\nThe official fight song of the Sooners is \"[[Boomer Sooner]].\"  This song is played frequently at football games and is played by the band after touchdowns, field goals, after significant plays, and when the team or crowd need a boost of energy.  \"OK Oklahoma\" is another school song that is played after an extra point and when the [[Sooner Schooner]] rolls onto the field.  The official Alma Mater song is the \"[[OU Chant]]\", which is sung by OU fans before sporting events and at ceremonial occasions.  Other tunes frequently heard at OU football games include the state song \"[[Oklahoma (Rodgers and Hammerstein song)|Oklahoma]]\" and an alternate fight song titled \"Fight for OKU.\"\n\n[[The Pride of Oklahoma Marching Band]] is a nationally renowned ensemble founded in 1904.  The largest student organization on campus, the band performs at all home games and frequently travels to other games.  The band holds a game ball from the [[Bedlam Series]] game in 1983, the day \"the Pride\" won.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cooter|first1=Terri|title=100 Years of Pride 1904\u20132004: A Documented History of the Pride of Oklahoma Marching Band|date=2004|publisher=Terri Cooter|location=Norman|pages=173\u2013175}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n\n===Heisman Trophy===\nThe [[Heisman Trophy]] is awarded annually to the nation's most outstanding college football player. Seven Oklahoma players have won the Heisman Trophy, six more finished runner-up. [[Kyler Murray]] is the most recent winner having won the 2018 Heisman Trophy.<ref name=\"winners and runners-up\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Player !! Position !! Points !! Notes\n|-\n| '''1952''' || '''{{sortname|Billy|Vessels}}''' || '''[[Halfback (American football)|HB]]''' || '''525''' ||<ref name=\"winners and runners-up\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/sportsextra/ousportsextra/ou-football-a-look-at-the-sooners-heisman-trophy-winners/article_e5020eb2-0055-5b8f-8f99-724f3e63f7ea.html |title=OU football: A look at the Sooners' Heisman Trophy winners and runners-up  |last=Bailey |first=Eric |date=December 9, 2017 |access-date=2018-06-22}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1954 || {{sortname|Kurt|Burris}} || [[Center (gridiron football)|C]] || 838 ||<ref name=\"winners and runners-up\" />\n|-\n| '''1969''' || '''{{sortname|Steve|Owens|Steve Owens (American football)}}''' || '''[[Running back|RB]]''' || '''1,488''' ||<ref name=\"winners and runners-up\" />\n|-\n| 1972 || [[Greg Pruitt]] || [[Running back|RB]] || 966 ||<ref name=\"winners and runners-up\" />\n|-\n| '''1978''' || '''{{sortname|Billy|Sims}}''' || '''[[Running back|RB]]''' || '''827''' ||<ref name=\"winners and runners-up\" />\n|-\n| 1979 || {{sortname|Billy|Sims}} || [[Running back|RB]] || 773 ||<ref name=\"winners and runners-up\" />\n|-\n| 2000 || {{sortname|Josh|Heupel}} || [[Quarterback|QB]] || 1,552 ||<ref name=\"winners and runners-up\" />\n|-\n| '''2003''' || '''{{sortname|Jason|White|Jason White (American football)}}''' || '''[[Quarterback|QB]]''' || '''1,481''' ||<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://newsok.com/article/1960402/sooner-jason-white-wins-heisman-trophy |title=Sooner Jason White wins Heisman trophy |last=Schroeder |first=George |date=December 14, 2003 |website=newsok.com |access-date=2018-06-22}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2004 || {{sortname|Adrian|Peterson}} || [[Running back|RB]] || 997 ||<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/news/story?id=2732041 |title=Peterson, '04 Heisman runner-up, to enter NFL draft |date=January 16, 2007 |access-date=2018-06-22}}</ref>\n|-\n| '''2008''' || '''{{sortname|Sam|Bradford}}''' || '''[[Quarterback|QB]]''' || '''1,726''' ||<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/news/story?id=3767667 |title=Oklahoma quarterback Bradford wins Heisman |date=December 14, 2008 |website=espn.com |access-date=2018-06-22}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''2017''' || '''{{sortname|Baker|Mayfield}}'''|| '''[[Quarterback|QB]]''' ||  '''2,398''' ||<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.