Bobby Hoying]]\n*1996 Greg Bellisari\n*1999 [[Ahmed Plummer]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==College Football Hall of Fame==\nBeginning with Chic Harley and Howard Jones in the 1951 inaugural class, Ohio State has had 32 former players and coaches inducted into the [[College Football Hall of Fame]].{{CN|date=August 2019}}\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*1951 [[Chic Harley]] and [[Howard Jones (American football coach)|Howard Jones]]\n*1954 [[Wes Fesler]] and [[John Wilce]]\n*1969 [[Les Horvath]]\n*1971 [[Bill Willis]] and [[Francis Schmidt]]\n*1973 [[Gaylord Stinchcomb]]\n*1974 [[Jim Parker (American football)|Jim Parker]]\n*1975 [[Gust Zarnas]]\n*1976 [[Vic Janowicz]]\n*1977 [[Jim Daniell]]\n*1978 [[Gomer Jones]]\n*1979 [[Howard \"Hopalong\" Cassady]]\n*1983 [[Woody Hayes]]\n*1984 [[Warren Amling]]\n*1986 [[Archie Griffin]]\n*1989 [[Aurealius Thomas]]\n*1991 [[Jim Stillwagon]]\n*1996 [[Bob Ferguson (American football)|Bob Ferguson]]\n*1998 [[Randy Gradishar]]\n*2001 [[John Hicks (American football)|John Hicks]]\n*2002 [[Earle Bruce]]\n*2004 [[Jack Tatum]]\n*2005 [[Jim Houston]]\n*2007 [[Rex Kern]]\n*2008 [[John Cooper (American football)|John Cooper]]\n*2009 [[Chris Spielman]]\n*2011 [[Eddie George]]\n*2013 [[Orlando Pace]]\n*2015 [[Jim Tressel]]\n*2016 [[Tom Cousineau]]\n*2020 [[Keith Byars]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Media==\n{{Further|Ohio State IMG Sports Network}}\nThe Buckeyes are covered on the radio by the Ohio State IMG Sports Network. [[WBNS (AM)|WBNS]]/Columbus (1460&nbsp;AM) and sister station [[WBNS-FM]]/Columbus (97.1&nbsp;FM) serve as flagship stations, with more than 60 affiliates in Ohio, and two additional affiliates in [[West Virginia]]. [[Paul Keels]] is the current play-by-play announcer, while former Buckeye [[left guard]] [[Jim Lachey]] serves as color analyst.  They are joined by sideline reporter Matt Andrews and Skip Mosic, host of the network pregame and halftime shows.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ohiostatebuckeyes.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/radio-network.html|title=Buckeyes Radio Network|publisher=Ohio State Buckeyes|accessdate=April 30, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130127064844/http://www.ohiostatebuckeyes.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/radio-network.html|archive-date=January 27, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[WBNS-TV]] (channel 10) in Columbus is the long-standing \"official TV home\" of the Buckeyes, airing the official coach's show ''Game Time with Ryan Day'' (simulcast statewide on [[Fox Sports Ohio]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wbns.titantv.com|title=TitanTV Programming Guide \u2013 What's on TV, Movies, Reality Shows, and Local News|first=Decisionmark Corp. 818 Dows Road SE, Cedar Rapids, Iowa|last=52403|website=wbns.titantv.com}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, Ohio State football games are broadcast by their student radio organization, Scarlet and Gray Sports Radio on OhioStateSports.net\n\n== Future non-conference opponents ==\nAnnounced schedules as of November 7, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://247sports.com/college/ohio-state/Article/Ohio-State-Buckeyes-football-completes-schedule-through-2023-Notre-Dame-Fighting-Irish-Oregon-Ducks-134672534/?liveconnect=B4-00-16-28-61-54-AE-1A-B9-19-95-73-9B-45-21-6D190822_121532OhioStateBuckeyes|title=Ohio State completes football schedule through 2023|website=Bucknuts|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-22}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Ohio State Buckeyes|2020|2021|2022|2023|2024|2025|2026|2027|2030|2031}}\n|-\n| vs [[Bowling Green Falcons football|Bowling Green]] (9/5)\n| vs [[Oregon Ducks football|Oregon]] (9/11)\n| vs [[Notre Dame football|Notre Dame]] (9/3)\n| vs [[San Jose State Spartans football|San Jose State]] (9/9)\n| at [[Washington Huskies football|Washington]] (09/14)\n| vs. [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas]] (8/30)\n| vs. [[Ball State Cardinals football|Ball State]] (9/5)\n| at [[Boston College Eagles football|Boston College]] (9/18)\n| at [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]] (9/14)\n| vs [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]] (8/30)\n|-\n| at [[Oregon Ducks football|Oregon]] (9/12)\n| vs [[Tulsa Golden Hurricane football|Tulsa]] (09/18)\n| vs [[Arkansas State Red Wolves football|Arkansas State]] (9/10)\n| vs [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|Western Kentucky]] (9/16)\n| \n| vs [[Washington Huskies football|Washington]] (09/13)\n| at [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas]] (9/12)\n| \n|\n|\n|-\n| vs [[Buffalo Bulls football|Buffalo]] (9/19)\n| vs [[Akron Zips football|Akron]] (9/25)\n| vs [[Toledo Rockets football|Toledo]] (09/17)\n| at [[Notre Dame football|Notre Dame]] (9/23)\n| \n| vs. [[UConn Huskies football|UConn]] (10/18)  \n| vs [[Boston College Eagles football|Boston College]] (9/19)\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n== Fan base ==\n\nIn 2011, [[New York Times]] reporter [[Nate Silver]] conducted a study of college football fans, and through his research determined that Ohio State has the most fans of any college football team in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/ohio-sports-blog/index.ssf/2011/09/ohio_state_football_take_heart.html|title=Ohio State Buckeyes estimated to have the most fans of any college football team in the country, study finds|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book\n| author=Jack Park\n| chapter=\n| title=The Official Ohio State Football Encyclopedia\n| publisher=Sports Publishing LLC\n| isbn= 1-58261-006-1\n| year=2002| pages=}}\n*{{cite book\n| author=Jim Tressel\n| chapter=\n| title=What It Means To Be A Buckeye\n| editor=Jeff Snook\n| publisher=Triumph Books\n| isbn=1-57243-602-6\n| year=2003\n| pages=\n| url-access=registration\n| url=https://archive.org/details/whatitmeanstobeb0000unse\n}}\n*{{cite book |author1=Greenberg, S. |author2=Ratermann, D. |chapter= |title=I Remember Woody |publisher=Triumph Books |isbn=1-57243-674-3 |year=2004 |pages= |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/irememberwoodyre0000gree }}\n*{{cite book\n| author=Robert Vare\n| chapter=\